<a href=#L10000> Follow keywords </a><pre>
<a name=L10000></a><a href=#L10001>So</a>: U-af
From: mam@tattoo.ed.ac.uk
Newsgroups: africa.horn
Subject: Scottish Sudan News 29
Date: 30 Jun 1996 20:37:40

From: Michael Marten  mam@tattoo.ed.ac.uk 

                   ****SCOTTISH CHURCHES' SUDAN GROUP***

*Please feel free to forward this to anyone you think might be interested!*
(You must include the following paragraph regarding copyright of material.)

[The information reproduced below consists primarily of news items which have
appeared in the printed Newsletter. Unless otherwise noted, you should assume
it is copyright Scottish Churches' Sudan Group. Therefore permission MUST be
requested if you wish to reproduce or distribute it in any form (permission
will normally be freely given provided full acknowledgments are included).
Items that are marked as being copyright for someone else may not be copied
without first contacting the copyright holder. Subscription details and our
address are located at the end of this document. If you have any comments or
would like to send us materials (possibly for inclusion in the Newsletter)
please write to us - all correspondance welcome!]
***************************************************************************
Issue No. 29                                                      JUNE 1996
***************************************************************************

WAR
In eastern Sudan: the Sudan Allied Forces, a group of secularist soldiers who
belong to the opposition National Democratic Alliance and are based in
Eritrea, killed six soldiers near the town of Kassala along the Eritrean
border on 19/5/96. In June a land-mine blew up a water tanker on a border
road. Ethiopia also accused Sudan of launching raids into its territory in
May.
In South Sudan: the Sudan People's Liberation Army attacked units of its
rival faction, the South Sudan Independence Army, which has recently made
peace with the Khartoum regime. The SSIA claimed that one SPLA soldier died
in the attack. Instability continues in Bahr al-Ghazal, according to the
Sudan Democratic Gazette which says that Nuer forces have been raiding
cattle, and Arab militias have been raiding for cattle and slaves in the
north of the province. Fighting between the SPLA and the government continued
- an army convoy was ambushed near Wau on 12/5/96. And some reports speak of
a mutiny of government soldiers in a garrison near Juba - their term of duty
expired three years ago but they are still at the front, with no pay for
three months.
However, one SSIA commander has signed an agreement with John Garang's SPLA
to unify forces. John Luk Jok is from the Nuer tribe, which dominates the
SSIA, and has been at odds with its leadership for over a year.
(Reuter 20/5/96, 26/5/96, 5/6/96; Sudan Democratic Gazette 6/96; Sudan News
and Views 6/96)

***************************************************************************

INSTABILITY AND CRUCIFIXION
Darfur is the westernmost province of Sudan, lying on the borders with Chad
whose people are mostly African [non-Arab] Muslims. The area saw great deal
of instability in the 1980's, when 7,000 were reportedly killed in acts of
lawlessness and banditry. The rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army has tried
to take the war in the South to Darfur, and a previous government was
suspected of fomenting a massacre of Southerners by an Arab tribe in Darfur
in 1985. However in the 1990's the government seemed to be in control of the
area: 31,000 firearms were confiscated in 1992. Now instability is returning
- in March armed robbers killed two of the provincial governor's bodyguards
in an attack on his car, and in May a judge in Darfur sentenced six men to
hang and three men to be crucified for armed robbery. Others were sentenced
to prison terms. The gang had 85 automatic rifles in their possession when
they were arrested.
The Qur'an and Sudan's version of Islamic law allow for the crucifixion of
armed bandits. 
(Reuter 24/5/96, 30/5/96)

***************************************************************************

PEACE CHARTER
A peace deal was signed in Khartoum in April between the government and two
factional rivals of the opposition Sudan People's Liberation Army - Riek
Machar's South Sudan Independence Army and the forces of Kerubino Kuanyin
Bol. Machar is now reported to be uniting his forces with government troops
at Malakal in readiness for an attack on SPLA positions at Bor, the home town
of John Garang, leader of the SPLA.
The agreement was denounced as treason by the SPLA in South Sudan and by the
exiled northerners in the opposition. Both militias were militarily
insignificant, they added. 
The government and its allies continue to press the virtues of the accord. An
SSIA spokesman in Nairobi said that the government had conceded the right of
self-determination in the South by signing it, and expected a referendum
within 24 months. And Joseph Lagu, leader of the South's liberation struggle
in the 1970's, returned to Sudan in May to back the deal. Lagu called on the
government to involve John Garang of the SPLA and his allies in the northern
opposition in the deal. The accord drew qualified approval from a
representative of the banned Umma party speaking on behalf of its leader
al-Sadiq al-Mahdi at a religious festival in Khartoum recently - this
underlines the fact that the northern opposition parties, now in alliance
with the SPLA, often see the problem of the South in terms similar to the
current northern regime. 
The government held another signing ceremony in Khartoum on 16/5/96 when
James Othow signed the peace charter on behalf of yet another rebel faction,
SPLA-United, a group based in northern Upper Nile, drawing its support from
the Shilluk tribe. The Shilluk king was also there. It is led by Lam Akol, a
leading southern intellectual who split from the SPLA in 1991. However, Lam
Akol issued a condemnation of the accord and said that Othow, a government
official since last year, had nothing to do with his movement.
The accord has greatly exacerbated tribal tensions in Sudan and elsewhere.
John Garang belongs to the Dinka tribe, which dominates the South by its
size. Machar belongs to the smaller Nuer tribe. In Kakuma refugee camp in
Kenya, where 47,000 refugees live, Nuers and Dinkas clashed in June with
clubs and spears leaving six dead, says the UNHCR. Kenyan sources say that
guns were involved, and put the number of dead at 26.
(Umma Party Information Office UK 30/4/96; al-Ray al-Akher 5/96; Voice of
America 16/5/96; Reuter 16/5/96, 26/5/96, 5/6/96; Sudan News and Views 6/96)

***************************************************************************

SANCTIONS
The UN imposed limited diplomatic sanctions on Sudan on 10/5/96 after it
failed to produce three men alleged to have participated in an assassination
attempt against Egypt's President Mubarak.. Since then the US, UK and Egypt
have all reduced the size of Sudanese missions in their capitals. The
Egyptians expelled 38 Sudanese diplomats.
The UN also called on the Sudanese government to stop aiding international
terrorism. President al-Bashir told an Arabic magazine in May that all
foreign opposition groups would be expelled from Sudan. His office denied the
remarks the next day, but his foreign minister told another newspaper at the
end of May that the opposition groups, like the Palestinian Islamic militant
group Hamas, would indeed be asked to leave. Hamas had said earlier it would
not be going. 
One of the many larger than life characters in Sudan is Osama bin Laden, a
billionaire of Saudi origin who is believed to bankroll many of the Islamic
militant groups in the world. He fought fearlessly in the Afghan war and then
went to live in Sudan after he was expelled from Saudi Arabia for criticising
the corruption of the regime. His fate is not known at the moment - the
Sudanese foreign minister says he left Sudan for Afghanistan of his own
accord; his UN ambassador says he was expelled; other sources say that there
is a deal to deport him in return for Saudi oil. 
Sudan reportedly set up informal contacts with its arch enemy Israel last
month, presumably to discuss its relations with Hamas. Sudan's support for
such militant groups deeply agitates its neighbours - the Egyptian government
hanged six Muslim militants last month who had been trained in Sudan.
Reuter 15/5/96, 26/5/96, 2/6/96; AP 3/6/96; Sudan News and Views 6/96

***************************************************************************

OTHER NEWS
IMF talks: Sudan's $1.7 billion arrears on repayments due to the
International Monetary Fund were the subject of talks in Khartoum in May.
Sudan was almost expelled from the organisation last year for its arrears,
but saved its membership by agreeing to make token repayments of $4 million a
month. It has not been keeping up with these. Government newspapers in
Khartoum said agreement had been reached, but this was denied by anonymous
IMF sources. (Reuter 15/5/96)

Teachers to be expelled: Yemen will reduce by 25% the number of expatriate
teachers employed by its ministry of education. This will affect 1,500
Sudanese teachers in Yemen. Sudan's government has promised jobs to any
teachers obliged to return. (SUNA 18/5/96)

Oil: Arakis, the Canadian company drilling for petroleum in Upper Nile, says
one well under development will produce 4,500 barrels a day, making it the
company's most productive well in the world. The Energy and Mining minister,
on a visit to Tehran, discussed the possibility of Iranian help in building
an oil refinery in Khartoum. Southern Sudanese have long rejected all
attempts by Northern government to control the oil wealth of their region.
Meanwhile, President al-Bashir promised that June will see the first Sudanese
produced petrol. (Reuter 22/5/96, 23/5/96; al-Sharq al-Awsat 28/5/96)

Inflation up, earnings down: Inflation reached 83% in Sudan in April, up from
71% in December. Sudan earned $120 million from its exports in the first
quarter of 1996 - 55% less than was anticipated by last year's budget. (Sudan
News and Views 6/96)

Operations cancelled: Sudan's largest hospital closed its surgical theatres
after six women died in operations in May. The Khartoum Hospital had earlier
closed its dialysis unit, and its morgue cannot take any more bodies because
there is no money for burials. (Sudan News and Views 6/96)

Yes it hurt, No it didn't work: The current regime in Sudan will celebrate
seven years of power this month but President al-Bashir admitted to a London
newspaper that the economy could do better - he is thinking of holding an
economic conference to revise government policy. (al-Hayat 23/5/96)

Children protest: Sudanese children on Sunday marched through Khartoum and
handed a memorandum to the United Nations to protest against sanctions it
imposed on Sudan in May. War orphans and others chanted "We will never
succumb, nor are we going to be humiliated or yield to the Americans. Oh
United Nations, Sudan is deeply rooted in our hearts. No to the diplomatic
sanctions against the Sudan". (Reuter 26/5/96)

Purges forgotten: 124 diplomats, teachers and journalists who lost their jobs
after the current regime took power in 1989 were reinstated in May, while 582
others had their pensions enhanced. 63 others had been reinstated by February
of this year. The government has taken several measures to broaden its
support and include any members of the opposition prepared to accept its
supremacy. It has dismissed 75,000 employees since 1990, says the Sudan Human
Rights Organisation. (Reuter 22/5/96; SHRO 4/96)

Jailbreak: An independent Khartoum newspaper reported on 17/5/96 that 95
prisoners in a prison 120 miles south of Khartoum briefly took control of
their prison after exchanging fire with warders. The men were all detained in
connexion with an alleged coup attempt in March. The next day a police
spokesman dismissed the affair as a minor incident, but the regime suspended
the publication of the newspaper, al-Ray al-Akher. Unidentified armed men
visited its offices, threatened a janitor and took away 20,000 copies of the
paper. Everyone assumed it was the security forces. (Reuter 17/5/96, 20/5/96;
ca was the target of a campaign by the Dutch-based justice and peace group
Pax Christi last year - the group wanted an end to arms supplies for the
Sudanese regime. (UPI 11/5/96)

Cholera Epidemic: 700 people were killed in a cholera epidemic which has
spread northwards from Adok in western Upper Nile to Ler, Leek and Jikany.
Cholera has also been identified in northern Bahr al-Ghazal, and acute
diarrhoea in Juba. These reports come from Medecins sans Frontieres, an
international aid agency working in Sudan, which fears that the present rainy
season will isolate people from medical help. 
The reports were denied by Khartoum's Ministry of Health, which said that
they were aimed at "tarnishing the image of Sudan abroad". A senior official
there said that 10 medical teams despatched to all parts of the country had
found no evidence to support the aid agency's fears.
(Reuter 4/6/96, 5/6/96)

Neighbours from Hell: A family in Hounslow, London, who led a three year
campaign of abuse, intimidation, arson and stabbing against the black and
Asian residents of their housing scheme were evicted for racial harassment
last month after one of their neighbours reported them to the local council.
A father of two from Southern Sudan spoke out against them and was forced to
spend last Christmas on somebody's floor. When asked how he had found the
courage to stand up to the racial hatred, he said: "I have lived with civil
war for 17 years. I am not scared as I hold my life in my hands." (Hounslow
and London Recorder 17/5/96)

***************************************************************************

HUMAN RIGHTS
Two highly critical reports on the human rights situation in the Sudan were
published at the end of May. Amnesty International, which led a major
campaign against human rights abuses in Sudan last year, said that the policy
of brutality against the opposition has continued, although the government
had made minor concessions in 1995. Amnesty repeated its call for the
international community to set up a human rights monitoring operation for
Sudan. 
A longer report  from Human Rights Watch in New York entitled Behind the Red
Line : Political Repression in Sudan, details the denial of basic freedoms of
speech, assembly and association, combined with the threat of arbitrary
arrest, detention and torture by an ever-present security apparatus, as well
as abuses committed in the course of the war. The report is based on two
missions to Sudan in 1995, and contains detailed recommendations to the
government and others. 
The two reports press the allegation that Sudan tolerates or encourages the
slave trade - the government has long denied this in tones of outraged
dignity. However, the minister of justice announced last month that a
committee would be set up to investigate the claim. Its members appear too
have been drawn exclusively from the security forces.

HUMAN RIGHTS CAMPAIGN
The Geneva based OMCT/SOS Torture said on 30/5/96 that four people detained
in Kober prison were released on 26/5/96: Mr  Elsir Osman Babu, politician;
Mr Sir Elkhtim Osman Alhag, politician; Mr
Mutwakil Hag Hamed and Mr Noor Sharaf Eldin, farmer. 32 others are still in
detention, among them Mr  Mohmed Hussain Ali a 14 year old student.
SOS-Torture is very concerned for the safety of Dr. Sati Gah-ElRasoul, Mr
Ismail Mahadeen and Mr Moneir ElBaru, who were arrested, presumably without
charge, on 26 May 1996 and are currently being detained at Kober Prison. They
ask that appeals be sent to the Sudanese authorities on behalf of the men,
asking that they be released immediately if they are being detained without
charge. If valid charges are held against them, they should be brought
promptly to a fair trial. Please address appeals to: His Excellency
Lieutenant General Omar Hassan al-Bashir, President of the Republic, People's
Palace, PO Box 281, Khartoum, Sudan.
(Amnesty International 29/5/96; Human Rights Watch Africa 29/5/96; OMCT - SOS
Torture 30/5/96)

***************************************************************************
ho have to struggle hard to believe that they are freed by God's power. Pray
for the ordinary Christians and the clergy who have to explain what freedom
means to themselves and to others [see page 4]

***************************************************************************

WRESTLERS FOR GOD - A NUBA THEOLOGY OF LIBERATION
by Renato Kizito Sesana - see end of article for copyright
The Nuba mountains in the centre of Sudan are the scene of some of the worst
atrocities in the current civil war. Here, a Roman Catholic priest who
visited the mountains recently writes how the trials of the Nuba affect their
vision of God's presence with them, in their ancient culture and in their
hopes for the future. One of the most famous of Nuba traditions is the
wrestling matches in the villages ... 
Luka, a lanky 15 year old, has accompanied me during many long exhausting
trips on foot. He carried my luggage on a shoulder and a machine-gun on the
other. In every village we visited he had some friends to pray with first,
and to be riotously happy with after. One day after having walked for hours
under the sun and then having helped to dig a grave, he joined the team of
local wrestlers in challenging those from up the Moro Hills. He engaged in
the wrestling three times, losing each time to older and stronger opponents.
Every time he lost he smiled and complimented the winner. At the end, as he
was lifting from the ground the luggage and the machine-gun for two more
hours of walking, he told me smiling: "Abuna (father), did you enjoy the
wrestling? Sometime in the future I'll be strong enough to win!". Then he
smiled, exposing the holes where some of the front teeth had been removed in
the initiation to manhood, and said: "The same with the government. Soon,
with the help of God, we will be strong enough to wrestle them to the
ground!".
The confidence of Luka might prove to be too optimistic. During my first
visit to the Nuba in the beginning of August 1995, I met William "Shaker"
Kuali, 26, an SPLA freedom fighter and musician. When Shaker started playing
his guitar and singing his melodies nobody could resist smiling and dancing.
And when he joined the wrestling arena the public was all for him. Shaker
told me about his love for singing and writing poetry, and of his
determination that Sudan be a place where all people of different religions
and culture could live in harmony. "My place is here to fight for a better
tomorrow" he said, but he expressed also his ardent desire that the war would
end soon. I learned when I went back to the Nuba in December that Shaker will
never sing again his songs of hope, freedom and love. Just a few days after
we met, August 18th, he was gunned down by government soldiers while
defending his home village. 
Honey from the Rock: If wrestling is the symbol of the indomitable resistance
of the Nuba, there is another symbol properly depicting their soul. "I will
satisfy you with the wild rock honey", God promises to his people in Psalm
81:16. Why wild rock honey? I asked myself this question many times when the
Nuba offered me wild rock honey as the best treat you can find in their
Mountains. It is really the best honey I ever tasted. The honey from the rock
of the Nuba Mountains is a proper image for the delicate feelings of the
Nuba. I have never received such generous hospitality as in Sudan. The Nuba
routinely surprise me with gifts of beautifully decorated gourds, bead
necklaces and hand carved crosses. People have thanked me in endless personal
ways for my visits. A Protestant pastor broke down in tears when we had to
part ways after a few days of walking together. The Nuba are people who value
friendship. Happy are those who receive the honey of their friendship. 
Their struggle, like everything in their life, has a strong communitarian
aspect. In the Nuba community all participate.  There are no superstars. At
the market, during the dancing, the liturgy, or the wrestling competition the
participation of each person is total, at whatever level of involvement in
the action. Christmas night was moonless. In the vast yard around the little
c like becoming part of one body. It was a unique Nuba way of expressing
their joy and faith in Jesus. "I have no longer any doubt - I told them -
Christ is a Nuba. I have seen Him in your generous love for the Church, in
your faith, in the eyes of your children, in your dances. Christ is
definitely a Nuba." 
Liberation and Inculturation: It would be good to be able to express the
faith of the Nuba people in a Nuba way; to write a Nuba theology starting
from the experience of oppression, Africaness, culture, liberation and faith
of the Nuba people. A prominent feature of the Nuba people is that in their
present experience, struggle for liberation and faith in God intersect. Their
own human liberation and the defence of their culture become the reason and
sustenance of their struggle. Christ meets them at this junction. The
liberation theology which emerged in Latin America during the turmoil of the
sixties proclaimed a faith centred concept of integral liberation to the
oppressed. African theology instead started from culture and developed the
idea of inculturation. Now there are signs that the two theologies of
liberation and inculturation are going to meet and proclaim a liberation
rooted in inculturated faith. 
To an evangelizing Catholic Church struggling to shed its ethnocentric roots,
to overcome its own long history of cultural oppression and persecution, and
to align itself with all those who hunger for justice, the Nuba offer a very
special gift. The Nuba Christ is crucified on a cross where the vertical beam
represents the thrust for liberation, a liberation which transcends the
economic and political to reach divinization. The horizontal beam represents
the reaching out to culture, to the people in their concrete way of life. In
the eyes of the world the Nuba are crucified on a cross of degrading misery
and backward culture. Yet the same cross, in their hands, becomes an
instrument of salvation, redemption and resurrection, a new way of life where
human dignity and faith in God are one. Evangelization of the Nuba means to
enter into this double dynamic of inculturation and liberation.
(c)Africanews 4/96

