  02 JUL 96 - SUDAN-SECURITY
  
Sudanese Security Forces on Alert at Eritrea Border

   
   
   KHARTOUM, Sudan (PANA) - Sudanese security personnel have been
   dispatched to Tokker in the country's east, on the border with
   Eritrea, where two landmines have reportedly injured a number of
   people.
   
   The mines are believed to have been planted by an Eritrea-based group
   opposed to the Sudanese government.
   
   Eritrea has accused Sudan of training dissidents seeking to oust
   president Essaias Afwerki. Khartoum has denied any wrong doing.
   
   Reporting the incident Tuesday, an independent daily quoted the
   eastern Sudan province commissioner, Abdel Rahman Balal, as saying "a
   large number" of civilians had volunteered to take up arms to protect
   their country against any armed incursion.
   
   The commissioner, however, told the daily that the Sudanese forces
   would not launch "any aggression against the Eritrean people." He
   described relations between the two countries as "intimate".
   
   Meanwhile, the governor of the Red Sea State, Badawi el-Khair Idris,
   has told the visiting Sudanese Vice-President, Gen. George Kongor
   Arop, measures had been take to contain the disquiet created by the
   landmine explosions in Tokker.
   
   The Red Sea State borders Eritrea in the south and Egypt on the
   extreme north.
   
   Sudan and Egypt have both claimed ownership of the Halaib triangle on
   their common border for the last four years. At least three Sudanese
   soldiers were killed at the height of the crisis when Egypt massed
   thousands of troops in the area.
