From: Ray Mitchell  rmitchellai@gn.apc.org 
Newsgroups: africa.horn
Subject: AI UA170/96 SUDAN Possible POCs
Date: Fri, 05 Jul 1996 17:08:17 +0100 (BST)

From: Ray Mitchell  rmitchellai 

/* Written  5:06 PM  Jul  5, 1996 by rmitchellai in gn:ai.uan */
/* ---------- "AI UA170/96 SUDAN Possible POCs" ---------- */
+------------------------------------------------------+
+ Paper reprints authorised. Electronic redistributors +
+ must request permission from Amnesty International.  +
+ Contact:   rmitchellai@gn.apc.org (UK)               +
+            sharrison@igc.apc.org (USA)               +
+            ggabriel@amnesty.cl.sub.de (Germany)      +
+------------------------------------------------------+
 
EXTERNAL                                     AI Index: AFR 54/13/96
                                             5 July 1996
 
UA 170/96   Fear of ill-treatment / Possible prisoners of 
            conscience / Health concern                         
 
SUDAN      Galal Hamid, former Director of the Gezira (agriculture)
                                                    Scheme
           Taj al-Sir Ahmad Abdallahi, President of Ahli Football
                                                    Club
           al-Kheir Ali Arbab, doctor
           Abdeen Miheisi, architect and engineer
           Osman Abdelgader, trade unionist
           Mohamed Abdelghafar, businessman
           Mubarak Mohamed al-Hassan
           and 23 other men (names unknown)
 
The seven men named above are among 30 men reported to have been
arrested on or around 23 June 1996 in Wad Medani, Sudan's second
city, which is located approximately 250 kilometres southeast of
Khartoum in an area known as the Gezira.  They have not been brought
to court or charged and are currently reported to be undergoing
intensive interrogation in two Sudan Security detention centres, the
first in Barakat, eight miles south of Wad Medani, and the second
in Wad Medani town itself. Relatives are reported to have been
denied access.  Amnesty International is concerned that the men are
possible prisoners of conscience and that they are at risk of ill-
treatment.
 
The arrests are part of a round-up of suspected opponents of the
government following a public statement by supporters of the banned
National Democratic Alliance (NDA), an umbrella grouping of banned
political parties and trade unions, issued in Wad Medani in
mid-June. al-Kheir Ali Arbab and Abdeen Miheisi, who is a diabetic,
are reported to have signed the statement on behalf of the Doctors'
Union and Engineers' Union respectively. Some of the other men are
former prominent trade unionists or left-wing activists.
 
BACKGROUND INFORMATION
 
There were a succession of public challenges to the government by
the NDA in various cities in Sudan in June 1996. A public statement
by the NDA, signed by leading political opponents living inside
Sudan and issued in Khartoum on 10 June, called on the government
to step down in favour of an interim administration.  This was
followed by at least 15 arrests of suspected political opponents who
remain in detention (see UA 157/96, AFR 54/12/96, 28 June 1996).  
   
 
For further background information, see Sudan: Progress or public
relations?, AFR 54/06/96, 29 May 1996. 
 
RECOMMENDED ACTION: Please send telegrams/telexes/express/airmail
letters in English, Arabic or your own language: 
 
- expressing concern at the detention without charge of 30 men
(naming some or all of the seven) arrested in Wad Medani on or
around 23 June 1996, who may be prisoners of conscience imprisoned
for their suspected opposition to the Sudan Government; 
 
- asking assurances that they are not being ill-treated; 
 
- urging that they be given immediate and regular access to their
families, legal representatives and also to any necessary medical
attention, particularly Abdeen Miheisi, who is a diabetic; 
 
- appealing for them to be released if they are not to be charged
with recognizably criminal offences and brought promptly to a fair
trial.  
 
APPEALS TO:
 
His Excellency Lieutenant General Omar Hassan al-Bashir
[Salutation: Your Excellency]
President of the Republic of the Sudan
People's Palace
PO Box 281, Khartoum, Sudan
Telegrams:  Lt Gen Omar Hassan al-Bashir, Khartoum, Sudan
 
Mr 'Abd al-Basit Sabdarat               [Salutation: Dear Minister ]
Minister of Justice and Attorney General     
Ministry of Justice
Khartoum, Sudan
Telegrams: Minister of Justice 'Abd al-Basit Sabdarat, Khartoum,
Sudan 
Telexes:   c/o 22411 KAID SD or 22604 IPOL SD
 
Mr Ali Osman Mohamed Taha         [Salutation: Dear Minister]
Minister of Foreign Affairs
Ministry of Foreign Affairs
PO Box 873
Khartoum, Sudan
Telegrams:  Foreign Minister Ali Osman Mohamed Taha, Khartoum, Sudan
 
PLEASE SEND COPIES OF YOUR APPEALS TO:  His Excellency Sayed Omer
Yousif Bireedo, Embassy of Sudan, 3 Cleveland Row, St James's,
London SW1A 1DD. Fax: 0171 839 7560
 
AND, IF POSSIBLE, TO THE FOLLOWING:
 
Mr Obeid Haj Ali
Chief Justice
Law Courts
Khartoum, Sudan
 
The Chairman
Human Rights Committee of the National Assembly,
Omdurman, Sudan
 
PLEASE SEND APPEALS IMMEDIATELY.  Please do not send appeals after
30 August 1996.
 
