Subject: IPS: /DEVELOPMENT BULLETIN 08/ SUDA
Date: 28 May 1996 16:08:44 -0800 (PST)

       Copyright 1996 InterPress Service, all rights reserved.
          Worldwide distribution via the APC networks.

                      *** 25-May-96 ***

Title: /DEVELOPMENT BULLETIN 08/ SUDAN: IMF Says Agreement Remains
Elusive

By Rose Umoren

WASHINGTON, May 23 (IPS) - The International Monetary Fund (IMF)
says an agreement with the Sudanese military government of Omar El
Bashir on either a monitored programme or terms for clearing the
country's 1.7-billion-dollar repayment arrears to the financial
institution is still elusive.

Sudan's finance minister Abdel Wahhab Osman was quoted last week
as saying the two sides had reached an agreement on terms for
paying the arrears. But an IMF official told IPS an agreement on
either issue was still a long way off.

''It is inconceivable that the rather very large arrears could be
regularised in such a fashion,'' said the official who preferred
not to be identified.

He said the earliest the IMF would make a new decision on Sudan
was Aug. 8 when its executive board deliberates on the report of a
mission that returned from Khartoum last weekend.

The board will review both the ''latest developments and overall
relationship with Sudan'' at the meeting, he said.

The official was, however, not optimistic that an agreement will
be reached even then. For one, he said it would be difficult to
convince the board that the El Bashir government would keep policy
promises or maintain any arrears- clearing schedule under the
agreement.

''Past experience has taught us that it cannot,'' he said.

Under an existing agreement on the arrears, Khartoum is supposed
to pay the IMF four million dollars monthly. ''It has not kept
this schedule for the past four months,'' said the official.

He acknowledged that, in any event, Sudan's recently heightened
international isolation could affect how the board views its case.

''Countries are better off when they have friends,'' he said.
''Political complications do have economic impact, including
direct impact.'' He would not elaborate.

Politics aside, ''relations with Sudan are very complicated, it
is not just the arrears,'' said the official. ''We know they do
not have this money. What we want is for them to come up with a
credible package of policies that can unleash the potential of the
economy.''

With that, he said, the IMF would put the country in what it
calls a rights accumulation programme. Under such an arrangement,
a country in arrears adopts policies the IMF deems necessary for
restoring its external viability. In return, the Fund encourages
bilateral creditors to provide loans for clearing the Fund
arrears.

According to the IMF, eight of the 11 countries for which the
programme was created have cleared their arrears. They include
Zambia, the most recent case, Sierra Leone, and Peru.

Sudan is among the countries that have yet to clear their
arrears.

''The executive board has been giving it extension after
extension over the last two years to improve its financial
situation to no avail,'' said the IMF source.

Describing Sudan as ''one unhappy story,'' the official said that
''various Sudanese officials had, in the past, come to th}
executive board, making pledge after pledge which they did not
live up to.''

Such pledges formed the basis of a staff-monitored programme
which usually precedes a full IMF-monitored plan. But because of
Khartoum's record on carrying out agreed policies, the staff
programme lapsed in 1995. (END/IPS/RU/YJC/96)


Origin: Amsterdam//DEVELOPMENT BULLETIN 08/ SUDAN/
