<a name=L10000></a><a href=#L10001>So</a>: U-af
From: newsdesk@igc.apc.org
Newsgroups: africa.news
Subject: IPS: /ENVIRONMENT BULLETIN 01/ AFRI
Date: 28 May 1996 16:11:25 -0800 (PST)

       Copyright 1996 InterPress Service, all rights reserved.
          Worldwide distribution via the APC networks.

                      *** 25-May-96 ***

Title: /ENVIRONMENT BULLETIN 01/ AFRICA: EU Aims To Sweep Up Africa's
Fishing 'Gold Mines'

By Tjitske Lingsma

AMSTERDAM, May 20 (IPS) - Their own seas sucked clean of viable
stocks of fish, the European Union's industrial fishing fleets are
heading south to African waters -- with, say NGOs, EU diplomats
clearing the way with a series of inequitable fisheries pacts.

''The whole logic of these fisheries agreements is: how can we
find fish to catch for our redundant European fishing fleets,''
says Magda Aelvoet, a Belgian Green party member of the European
Parliament.

The EU is desperate to preserve the domestic fishing industries
of Spain, Portugal, Britain and others, to save jobs in European
regions dependent on employment in fishing and keep its
technological edge against commercial challenges form the East.

''The accords are purely commercial,'' says her Dutch colleague
Jan Willem Bertens. ''The only thing that counts in the accords is
safeguarding European fishing interests.''

Currently the EU has a dozen fishing agreements with African
countries and plans this year to start negotiations on renewing
accords with countries with Angola, Gambia and Senegal. Agreement
heralds arrival of massive European trawler fleets; sometimes
local aid, trade contracts, technology transfer or other
compensation.

Generally however the developing nations are ill-equipped -- both
diplomatically and industrially -- to effectively contest the EU's
claim to fish their waters. ''Developing countries are in a weak
position and are forced to yield,'' says Aelvoet.

''The EU takes the lead and does everything it wants. If I see
how the game is being played with developing countries, I can only
say that it is played very hard.

The fishing question is a 'hot issue' acknowledges Bertens. Spain
and Portugal, whose ships roam the globe in search of fish
international waters, have demanded the EU take a strong line on
the fishing rights talks <a name=L10001></a><a href=#L10002>so</a> as to open up new areas for their
declining industries closer to home.

''For Spain and Portugal it is a vital question. It has become a
hard sector,'' says Bertens. Competition has become even more
acute as the problem of overfishing has worsened. The U.N. Food
and Agriculture Organisation (FAO) says 70 percent of the world's
fish stocks are fully exploited, over exploited, depleted or
recovering.

The fisheries agreements became a necessity in the wake of the
1982 United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea (UNCLOS). It
gave coastal states acquired the control over an Exclusive
Economic Zone (EEZ) extending 200 miles form their coast,
including the zone's natural resources.

The convention put 35 percent of the world's oceans under the
jurisdiction of coastal states -- and 95 percent of identified
global fish stocks under the control of mainly underdeveloped
coastal countries, notes the Brussels-based Coalition for Fair
Fisheries Agreements.

The developed world's fishing fleets got the European Union,
Russia, Japan, China and South Korea, among others to start work
on pacts that would give them access to these waters and quotas
setting minimums and maximum catches.

The pacts cost the EU money -- 280 million ECU (342 million
dollars) in additional aid in 1995 alone -- but most of the extra
funds go to national budgets and very little to help developing
world fishing industries, unable to compete with the EU's monster
trawlers.

International environmental and development NGOs say the income
in aid hardly comes close to fairly compensating the developing
world fishing communities and holds European trawler fleets
largely responsible for overfishing in African waters.

''The problem is overfishing,'' says Harry de Vries of the Dutch
development organisation NOVIB, which this week began a campaign
highlighting the effect of the EU's fishing policy on Senegal as
an example of the wider problem. ''The accords form a sort of
legalisation for looting the oceans.''

The European Parliament backs Bertens and Aelvoet, and views the
fishery accords as counter-productive that not only fail to aid
the development of Third World countries but actually hinder the
growth of local fishing sectors. Millions in the South make a
living as traditional fishers, using small boats and homemade
nets.

Bertens and Aelvoet say the EU fishery pacts clash with the EU's
guiding Maastricht Treaty of political union, which is supposed to
ensure 'coherence' -- ensuring that EU initiatives do not
frustrate EU development goals in developing countries.

''In fishing activities it means that it should be impossible for
the EU signs agreements that undermine the interests of, for
example, the Senegalese fishing communities,'' said Aelvoet. ''But
in Senegal's waters over-fishing is looming.

''It is completely contrary to the coherence principle,'' she
said, noting that the same priorities are not allowed to undermine
the EU's own fishery or agricultural policies.

Bertens says some blame can be laid at the door of the developing
nations themselves, some of whom prefer to see short term gains
from pacts with the EU instead of looking to long-term sustainable
development of their own traditional fleets. ''They don't want to
be seen as a developing country, but want to be taken seriously
and prefer a commercial approach,'' he suggested.

Not all countries give in however. In 1991 Namibia refused to
come to an agreement with the Europeans and the Moroccans fought
long and hard for the best deal they could get out of the EU in
1995.

At the time the EU was furious, but MP Bertens was elated by the
'Namibian approach'. After the negotiations broke down, the
Namibians decided to invite the private sector to come up with
their own cooperative deals.

Foreign investors have since invested 45 million dollars in a new
Namibian fishing industry employing 1,500 people, considered quite
an achievement in Namibia, which has a population of 1.5 million.

Morocco's own decision to block renewal of an existing pact in
April 1995 left 700 EU fishing vessels tied up in ports in
southern Spain, the Canary Islands and Portugal. Up to 40,000 EU
fishing industry jobs were put in doubt and it took months of
negotiation before a new pact was agreed in November last year.

Rabat's firm stand during the negotiations saw EU fleet access to
its waters reduced, a 'rest period' banning fishing to allow stock
to replenish themselves and for more fish to be landed for
processing in Morocco, thereby boosting local employment.

EU fishing fleet owners will be ordered to land 30 percent of
their squid and octopus catches in Moroccan ports by the end of
the final year of the four year pact. The EU will also pay
compensation of 162 million dollars a year in return for fishing
rights, up from 135 million under the previous three-year
agreement.

Morocco, which says that overfishing by EU boats have forced it
to lay up a third of its fleet of 2,000 vessels, is also expected
to receive at least 420 million dollars in extra EU aid over the
next three years for other projects, and concessions on access to
EU markets for other agricultural products.

Fish accounts for 15 percent of all Moroccan exports and the
industry employs at least 150,000 people. Morocco is the largest
world exporter of sardines. In comparison income from fishing
makes up only one percent of Spain's gross domestic product but
indirectly employs three percent of its working population -- and
25 percent in the north western province of Galicia.

The two Euro-MPs think more African cooperation is necessary and
that countries should learn from each other's experiences. ''It is
important to strengthen links between countries with worse and
better agreements,'' said Aelvoet.

She hopes this will consolidate their position during
negotiations with the EU. ''At present they are being played off
against each other.'' (END/IPS/TL/RJ/96)


