Subject: IPS: ZAMBIA-POLITICS: Bomb Scares R
Date: 29 May 1996 07:35:39

Path: gn!cdp!igc.apc.org!not-for-mail
From: newsdesk@igc.apc.org
Newsgroups: africa.news
Subject: IPS: ZAMBIA-POLITICS: Bomb Scares R
Message-ID:  APC&1'0'728c7008'237@igc.apc.org 
Date: 27 May 1996 16:08:55 -0800 (PST)
X-Gateway: notes@gn.apc.org
Lines: 129

       Copyright 1996 InterPress Service, all rights reserved.
          Worldwide distribution via the APC networks.

                      *** 24-May-96 ***

Title: ZAMBIA-POLITICS: Bomb Scares Rock Capital

by Joe Chilaizya

LUSAKA, May 24 (IPS) - Three bomb scares issued by a shadowy
opposition group brought the business centre of the Zambian
capital to a virtual standstill Friday, two days after parliament
passed a controversial constitutional amendment bill.

Shoprite Checkers, a busy South African-owned supermarket
chain, closed its doors Friday afternoon when it received a phone
call from a man claiming to represent the dissident 'Black Mambas'
warning that a bomb had been planted in its premises.

Police bomb disposal experts rushed to the scene and sealed off
the area, and another supermarket also allegedly threatened, only
to receive warning of a devise at the offices of the state-owned
newspaper the 'Times of Zambia'.

It was the second time in 24-hours that the paper had been
targeted in the new terror campaign. On Thursday night a death
threat was posted on the outside wall of the printing plant in
Ndola on the Copperbelt, listing the names of reporters to be
eliminated by <a name=L10001></a><a href=#L10002>so</a>-called Black Mamba hit squads.

Top of the hit list is the paper's managing director and editor-
in-chief, Emmanuel Nyirenda, features editor Samuel Ngoma and
political correspondent Kondwani Chirambo who were labeled as
'propagandists'.

Samuel Ngoma, who has taken an openly pro-government stand on
the constitutional crisis, says he is unmoved by the threats.

''I will not allow them to scare me. I have nothing to be
scared about dying,'' says the born again Christian. ''I have my
accommodation in heaven.''

But Chirambo appeared shaken. ''I really don't know how to take
this. You never know... it could be nothing, but it could be
something too. We can rule out nothing and have to be ready for
any eventuality,'' he told IPS.

The Black Mambas began issuing death threats immediately it
became apparent that the government of President Frederick Chiluba
would not bow to local and international pressure to have the
controversial constitution adopted by a constituent assembly
instead of the ruling Movement for Multiparty Democracy (MMD)-
dominated parliament.

The police have issued a 3,000 dollar reward leading to the
capture of any member of the Black Mambas.

Speculation is intense over who is behind the group with the
finger most often pointed at former President Kenneth Kaunda's
party, the United National Independence Party (UNIP).

During the Zambian independence struggle, Kaunda was nicknamed
the 'Black Mamba' by the colonial administration. UNIP had also
threatened unrest with the passing of the constitutional
ammendment bill which rules Kaunda out from standing in the
October presidential elections because, according to the
contentious clause, his parents were not Zambian.

UNIP on the other hand claims that the Black Mambas are a
creation of the MMD, looking to give itself a scapegoat for any
acts of violence which may erupt in the country as a result of
their uncompromising stand on the constitution.

In a new twist, the independent 'Chronicle' newspaper alleges
it has unimpeachable evidence that the Black Mambas are a group of
Islamic fundamentalists angry at the government's decision to
enshrine the declaration of Zambia as a Christian nation in the
constitution.

Many here had dismissed the group as a hoax until last week's
botched bombing attempt at Chiluba's state house residence which
blew a small hole in the perimeter wall.

Now bomb scares are suddenly a regular occurrence. There was
one at the five-star Hotel Intercontinental in Lusaka on Thursday
night followed by the three Friday.

Not all Zambians are however taking them seriously. ''Aaah,
this is just politics. These guys (the Black Mambas) are practical
jokers and besides, it would be most un-Zambian,'' said a street
vendor.

''Zambians are not violent. These are just scare tactics by
some political players,'' he added.

Police say they are not leaving anything to chance. Security
has been reinforced around the president and his cabinet ministers
and other prominent government figures.

''We shall take everything very seriously until we are
convinced that there is nothing to the threats. Meanwhile,
investigations are still going on,'' Police spokesman Francis
Musonda told IPS.

Underlining the crackdown, a former Zambia air force officer,
Capt. Patrick Mphangula, was picked up for questioning Thursday
night, apparently over the Black Mamba campaign.

Mphangula is a member of Kaunda's UNIP who was fired two-years
ago from the air force for unknown reasons. He was previously an
MMD member who had expressed a desire to challenge Chiluba for
party leadership. (END/IPS/JC/oa/96)


Origin: Harare/ZAMBIA-POLITICS/
