<a name=L10000></a><a href=#L10001>So</a>: U-af
From: newsde3@emertel.gn.apc.org
Newsgroups: africa.news
Subject: IPS: LIBERIA: Pressure Grows for Mo
Date: 29 May 1996 07:36:18

Path: gn!cdp!igc.apc.org!not-for-mail
From: newsdesk@igc.apc.org
Newsgroups: africa.news
Subject: IPS: LIBERIA: Pressure Grows for Mo
Message-ID:  APC&1'0'728c700b'345@igc.apc.org 
Date: 27 May 1996 16:13:05 -0800 (PST)
X-Gateway: notes@gn.apc.org
Lines: 146

       Copyright 1996 InterPress Service, all rights reserved.
          Worldwide distribution via the APC networks.

                      *** 24-May-96 ***

Title: LIBERIA: Pressure Grows for More U.S. Action

by Rose Umoren

WASHINGTON, May 24 (IPS) - As death and destruction mount in
Liberia, pressure is growing for U.S. President Bill CLinton to do
more to help bring peace to the country the United States founded
for its freed slaves 150 years ago.

Five senators from Clinton's democratic party wrote this week to
the president, asking him to take the lead in getting the United
Nations to upgrade its presence in the war-torn country.

A peacekeeping force, says the letter, ''should be drawn from
interested African states, including troops from the existing
(West African) ECOMOG force,'' and it should be ''placed under the
authority of the United Nations.''

The U.N. Observer Mission in Liberia (UNOMIL), which numbered
93 before the renewed factional warfare, has been reduced to only
five military observers in recent days. The mission was supposed
to arrange elections and disarm more than 60,000 fighters.

The United States ''can play a role in providing appropriate
transportation and logistical assistance'' in a U.N. peacekeeping
force, says the letter, written by Senators Russel Feingold,
Patrick Leahy, Dianne Feinstein, Carol Mosley-Braun, and Paul
Simon.

Re-stating their longstanding support for ECOMOG, the senators
note that ''given the most recent fighting, however, it appears
that the West African peacekeeping operation does not have the
adequate resources or capabilities to restore security.''

They remind Clinton that ''the U.S. has a long and unique
relationship with Liberia and her people.'' For this reason, they
argue, ''we have a responsibility to take the lead in helping
formulate ways to address this tragic situation.''

They also point out that continued hostilities in Liberia ''will
only add to the humanitarian disaster and lead to increased
regional instability.''

Accordingly, they say, ''we have a compelling national interest
to take a more active role in securing peace.''

As television and newspapers parade pictures of child soldiers,
corpses, and destroyed property, U.S. citizens have increasingly
taken up Liberians' call for more U.S. action.

''The cars (in Liberia) are American, the Liberian flag is
patterned after the U.S. flag and <a name=L10001></a><a href=#L10002>so</a> are the aspirations of the
people,'' wrote columnist William Raspberry recently in the
Washington Post. ''This gives us a special interest in helping.''

Instead, he wrote, the United States has stood by while
''Liberia's neighbours are involved in a way that is quite
extraordinary for that part of the world.'' Naming Nigeria, Ghana,
Sierra Leone, and Guinea, Raspberry points out that ''all this
(effort has been) from countries with per capita incomes downward
from 450 dollars a year.''

The United States should ''either vastly increase its material
assistance to the countries whose troops are trying to stop the
carnage ... or lead the U.N. in supplying troops,'' he said.

A letter to the Post last Friday noted ''historical facts'' the
writer said were missing from the public discourse.

Liberia ''has permitted its flag to be used to build one of the
world's largest merchant marine fleets, including giant tankers,
with the proviso that in the event of war, this fleet would
automatically be placed under the U.S. flag for our use, as indeed
it was,'' According to the writer, Edward K. Moss.

The letter continued: ''Liberia's resources have been supplied
to the U.S., including the world's purest iron ore and rubber
grown in the world's largest such plantation, both under
concessions to U.S. companies.''

Moss also pointed out that the U.S. ''actively supported Samuel
Doe (under whose military regime the war began) for years, with
many times the 60 million dollars we have provided to (ECOMOG) for
more than six years.''

Now, he charged, ''we are piously saying we should let the West
Africans persuade the...warring factions to lay down arms.''

Liberians and several non-governmental organisations (NGOs)
have for several months waged a campaign to get Washington to
dispense more logistic assistance to ECOMOG, which many Liberians
insist must lead the peacekeeping.

The Clinton administration has repeatedly said it is too
financially strapped to provide such assistance. Renewed fighting
and increased pressure led Washington to last week release 10
million dollars for the purchase of helicopters and trucks from
U.S. companies for ECOMOG.

The helicopters have been delivered, while the trucks ''are on
their way,'' Col. MacArthur DeShazer of the National Security
Council told a forum on Liberia organised by the black lobby
Constituency for Africa Thursday.

Liberians at the forum poured scorn on a proposal publicly
promoted by the United Nations special representative James Jonah
that Liberia be placed under U.N. trusteeship.

The tempers were only queslled with assurances from Ellen
Johnson Sirleaf, the U.N. Development Programme's assistant
administrator and director of the regional bureau for Africa.

''I have the latest report of the (U.N.) secretary-general on
Liberia and I can tell you that trusteeship is not in it and is
not being discussed by the Security Council,'' said Sirleaf.

She said that one of three options being considered, is a quick
disbursement by the United States of the 30 million dollars
recently approved by Clinton for ECOMOG, <a name=L10002></a><a href=#L10003>so</a> the force could carry
out the disarmament of troops.

Another option would have Washington send in U.S. troops to
scare the warriors into voluntary disarmament. The third option
calls for a national conference. (END/IPS/RU/YJC/96)


Origin: Washington/LIBERIA/
