<a name=L10000></a><a href=#L10001>So</a>: U-af
From: newsdesk@igc.apc.org
Newsgroups: africa.news
Subject: IPS: SUDAN-MEDIA: And Then There We
Date: 30 May 1996 15:39:34 -0800 (PST)

       Copyright 1996 InterPress Service, all rights reserved.
          Worldwide distribution via the APC networks.

                      *** 27-May-96 ***

Title: SUDAN-MEDIA: And Then There Were None

by Nhial Bol

KHARTOUM, May 27 (IPS) - Sudan's last independent daily has been
closed following a raid by an unidentified group of armed men who
seized the newspaper's plates, a year's supply of newsprint, and
20,000 copies of the paper awaiting distribution.

'Rahi al Akhar' (Alternative View Point) editor-in-chief, Mohi
Eddin Titawe, told IPS that the men who stormed his office Friday
looked and behaved like armed ruffians.

''Without providing any official paper as to who issued the
orders of the confiscation, these gang (members) entered our
building and told us to leave. We all quit the place at gun
point,'' a still shaken Titawe said.

The paper's journalists and workers have been ordered to stay
at home until a decision is made as to whether the paper will be
allowed to re-open.

''I don't know whether this was an act of a gang, a government
body, or a group of people who could drop in armed with pistols,
rifles and threaten journalists and take away all the copies and
plates for their own needs,'' Titawe said.

''I have not been notified as why this paper was closed or
suspended,'' and added that he believed his life is now in danger.

When Gen. Omar Hassan al Bashir overthrew Sudan's elected
government in 1989, one of his first acts was to shut down the
independent press. The restrictions were relaxed only in 1995,
allowing two private papers to operate, ahead of state managed no-
party general elections in March this year.

Then earlier this month, 'Akar Khabar' (The Last News) was
banned, followed last week by 'Rahi al Akhar', leaving just two
government-owned papers publishing in a country of 28 million
people.

''Relations between... the private media (and the government)
is going from bad to worse,'' commented former minister of
information, Ali Shammo.

He said the raid on 'Rahi al Akhar' proved the government was
opposed to a private press carrying independent views.

A security official told IPS that 'Rahi al Akhar' had over the
past few months repeatedly run anti-government stories in which
opposition groups were allowed to express their views in a country
where political parties are banned.

One report last week, said to have ruffled official feathers,
attacked a recent peace deal between the government and two rebel
factions which Bashir has trumpeted as a significant step towards
ending the country's 13-year secessionist civil war in the south.

Taking a more cynical view, the paper pointed out last Thursday
that the main rebel group, the Sudanese People's Liberation Army
(SPLA), had condemned the <a name=L10001></a><a href=#L10002>so</a>-called Political Charter and went on
to suggest that its signing by the two dissident groups were due
to their failure on the battlefield.

According to security sources though, the final straw was the
paper's claim in its seized Friday edition that 95 soldiers,
detained for their alleged role in an abortive coup and jailed in
Ed Dueim, 200 kms south of Khartoum, had rioted and seized control
of part of the prison.

The ministry of the interior, while accepting a revolt had
taken place, denied that there were any political prisoners in the
jail and the disturbances were due to inmates protesting over
delays in their appeals being heard.

Titawe however stands by his account. ''We got the story from
our experienced journalist in the area, the government should not
hide the truth from its citizens.''

''Despite the closure of our paper and warnings to our life, I
am prepared to take the issue anywhere. The revolt was led by the
coup-makers who have not been tried yet and is not a rumour nor
was it hear-say,'' he insists.

Over the weekend, the government-run Press and Publication
Council, responsible for the media here, announced that the paper
had been closed as a security measure and would be allowed to
resume next month if it denied the prison story. On Monday it then
said that 'Rahi al Akhar' had been suspended for violating press
laws.

The Council's release said the Ed Dueim report was harmful to
army morale and the paper should have checked with the ministry of
the interior over the incident and should have published the
ministry's denial.

''I am 57-years-old and this is the right age to accept the
truth, let them do whatever suits their needs but we cannot
publish a denial,'' Titawe said. ''Instead, I want them to come
and arrest me or take me for interrogation any time.''
(end/ips/nb/oa/96)


Origin: Harare/SUDAN-MEDIA/
