<pre>
So: U-env
From: nsundt@igc.apc.org
Newsgroups: climate.news
Subject: Global Change: Recent Pubs, Jun96 (
Date: 31 May 1996 20:41:53 -0800 (PST)

from Global Change Electronic Edition...
RECENT RELEASES, JUNE 1996 (PART I)

Note: Inclusion of any item on this list does not constitute an
endorsement of any kind. Items have not necessarily been
carefully reviewed by Global Change.

Andreae, Meinrat O., "Raising Dust in the Greenhouse," Nature,
380 (6573): 389-390 (4 April 1996). "The amount of dust in the
atmosphere is increasing, largely because of human activity. Its
climatic importance is becoming clear, as is our ignorance about
aerosols in general."

Athanasiou, Tom, Divided Planet: The Ecology of Rich and Poor
(New York: Little Brown, April 1996). $24.95.

Biondo, Brenda, "Warming up to Solar Energy," Solar Industry
Journal, 7 (1): 22-27 (First Quarter 1996). ["As the insurance
industries turn their attention to global warming, investments in
solar energy take on growing appeal."]

Bird, Michael, Allan R. Chivas and John Head, "A Latitudinal
Gradient in Carbon Turnover Times in Forest Soils," Nature, 381
(6578): 143-146 (9 May 1996). 

Blackside, Inc, Breakthrough: The Changing Face of Science in
America. An Atmosphere of Change, 1996. Videotape, 1 hour. The
Breakthrough series "profiles 20 contemporary African-American,
Latino and Native-American scientists and engineers who are
making advances in biology, astronomy, physics, mathematics and
many other scientific disciplines." The series was presented by
WGBH Boston and originally aired on Public Broadcasting System
(PBS) television stations. In An Atmosphere of Change, three
scientists are described, including Mario Molina. Molina is an
atmospheric chemist from the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology. He was a co-winner of the 1995 Nobel Prize for
Chemistry for his research on ozone-depletion. The other two
scientists described in the program are a toxicologist and a
biologist working on issues not directly related to climate
change or ozone depletion. Videotapes are available for
educational purposes from PBS Video, 1320 Braddock Place,
Alexandria, Virginia 22314. Tel: +1 800 328 PBS1.

Bolin, Bert (Chairman, Intergovernmental Panel on Climate
Change), "A brief overview of the IPCC Second Assessment Report,"
United Nations Climate Change Bulletin, 10: (2nd Quarter 1996).
Available on the World Wide Web at
<a href=http://www.unep.ch/iucc/bulltn10.html.>http://www.unep.ch/iucc/bulltn10.html.</a>

Brite TV (London,UK) Bangladesh: Living With Flooding, 1996.
Videotape (VHS or 3/4" U-matic), 20 minutes. Available from Films
for the Humanities and Sciences, PO Box 2053, Princeton, NJ
08543. Tel: +1 800 257 5126 or +1 609 275 1400. Fax: +1 609 275
3767. Order #AGT6166, Purchase price $99 (May 1996 price).
According to Films for the Humanities and Sciences: "Bangladesh
is particularly vulnerable to cyclones and seasonal flooding.
Making extensive use of graphics, this program explains why. To
understand the true impact of the floods, the program takes a
close look at the more than 200,000 people who live on the island
of Moheshkhali, which is on average barely 20 inches above seas
level. Why do its inhabitants live there? How do they make a
living? What is life like living with so much vulnerability to
flooding?"

Brown, Lester R., Christopher Flavin and Hal Kane, Vital Signs
1996. The Trends that Are Shaping our Future (Washington, DC:
Worldwatch Instititute, 1996). 

