RECENT RELEASES, MAY 1996 (PART II)

Note: Inclusion of any item on this list does not constitute an
endorsement of any kind. Items have not necessarily been
carefully reviewed by Global Change.

National Public Radio (NPR), Talk of the Nation's Science Friday
[Hour 1]. Host Ira Flatow discusses the future of environmental
legislation with with the administrator of the US Environmental
Protection Agency, and with Robert Walker (Republican from
Pennsylvania), Chairman of the Science Committee of the US House
of Representatives, 19 April 1996 (Washington, DC: National
Public Radio, 1996), sound cassette, 1 hour. Available for $12.95
+ $2.50 (domestic postage) from NPR Audience Services, 635
Massachusetts, NW, Washington, DC 20001. Tel: +1 202 414 3232.
Fax: +1 202 414 3046. Information on Science Friday and its
programs is available on the World Wide Web at
<a href=http://www.npr.org/scifri/.>http://www.npr.org/scifri/.</a> To enhance the educational benefits
of this and other editions of Science Friday, the site includes
the Science Friday Kids Connection. For the topics covered each
Friday, NPR provides a synopsis, student questions, student
projects, and lists of information resources. The Kids Connection
for this episode of Science Friday is available on the World Wide
Web at
<a href=http://majorca.npr.org/sfkids/showarchive/sfkc.96.04.19.html.>http://majorca.npr.org/sfkids/showarchive/sfkc.96.04.19.html.</a> 

National Public Radio (NPR), Talk of the Nation's Science Friday
[Hour 2]. Host Ira Flatow discusses biodiversity with David
Tilman, Professor of Ecology, University of Minnesota
(Minneapolis, Minn.); Walter Reid, Vice President for Programs,
World Resources Institute (Washington, DC); and Abigail Salyers,
Professor of Microbiology, University of Illinois (Urbana, Ill.).
Recorded on 19 April 1996 (Washington, DC: National Public Radio,
1996), sound cassette, 1 hour. Available for $12.95 + $2.50
(domestic postage) from NPR Audience Services, 635 Massachusetts,
NW, Washington, DC 20001. Tel: +1 202 414 3232. Fax: +1 202 414
3046. Information on Science Friday and its programs is available
on the World Wide Web at <a href=http://www.npr.org/scifri/.>http://www.npr.org/scifri/.</a> To enhance
the educational benefits of this and other editions of Science
Friday, the site includes the Science Friday Kids Connection. For
the topics covered each Friday, NPR provides a synopsis, student
questions, student projects, and lists of information resources.
The Kids Connection for this episode of Science Friday is
available on the World Wide Web at
<a href=http://majorca.npr.org/sfkids/showarchive/sfkc.96.04.19.html.>http://majorca.npr.org/sfkids/showarchive/sfkc.96.04.19.html.</a>

National Research Council, A Review Of The U.S. Global Change
Research Program And NASA's Mission To Planet Earth/Earth
Observing System (Second Letter Report) (Washington, DC: National
Academy of Sciences, 1996). ["The U.S. Global Change Research
Program was created in 1990 to advance scientific knowledge about
and predictions concerning the world's environment, assist
federal agencies, and provide reliable information for decision-
making. A Research Council study committee is assessing the
program's scientific progress and reviewing the role of systems
for observing the Earth and its environment. This letter report
examines federal responses to the recommendations presented in
the committee's first report, issued in September 1995."]

National Research Council, Sustaining Industry's Voluntary
Environmental Protection Efforts (Washington, DC: National
Academy of Sciences, 1996). ["Discusses ways to enhance and
sustain voluntary efforts by industry and government facility
managers in environmental protection efforts."]

National Research Council, Toward A New Generation Of Vehicles:
Phase II (Washington, DC: National Academy of Sciences, 1996).
["The progress of the Partnership for a New Generation of
Vehicles -- a joint effort by the federal government and
Detroit's Big Three automakers to create a safe, affordable,
fuel-efficient, and nearly pollution-free car -- is assessed in
this second Research Council report on the program."]

National Research Council, Toward A New National Weather Service:
The Importance Of The United States Weather Research Program For
NWS Modernization (Washington, DC: National Academy of Sciences,
1996). ["The National Weather Service has been upgrading its
technological capacity for detecting and warning of severe
weather for the past decade. This letter to Congress, the
National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, and other
federal agencies emphasizes the importance of continuing support
for research that will help improve short-term forecasts and
warnings. It also suggests high-priority research areas to
accomplish these objectives."] 

National Weather Service, Office of Hydrology, The Hidden Danger:
