Thirteen/WNET New York and Granada Television (producers), Savage
Skies: Fire and Rain, Video (VHS), 1 hour, 1996. The first of
four episodes in the Savage Skies series. According to an
announcement issued by the Public Broadcasting System: "The first
episode looks at the beauty of clouds and the destructive power
of rain. It follows weather watchers who roam the globe to
photograph the glorious images of clouds. The program visits
Colorado's Thompson Canyon, where survivors of a fatal flood in
1976 share their stories, and Lynmouth, England, which was
destroyed in a flash flood. Families whose worldly goods were
carried off by Mississippi River floods are also interviewed.
Finally, the program travels to Bombay to speak with the owner of
an umbrella factory. For her, the yearly monsoons create a
livelihood, not to mention relief for the Indian people, who
suffer from annual droughts." Tapes are available for $19.95
(+shipping) from Savage Skies VHS, PO Box 2284, South Burlington,
VT 05407. Tel (US Only): 1 800 336 1917. (posted May 1996).

Thirteen/WNET New York and Granada Television (producers), Savage
Skies: Riders on the Storm, Video (VHS), 1 hour, 1996. The second
of four episodes in the Savage Skies series. According to an
announcement issued by the Public Broadcasting System: "Episode
two pursues tornadoes and lightning. First the program looks at
storm chasers, individuals who live to encounter the weather that
most people dread. Among them are Antonio, a Brazilian whose one
dream before he dies is to see a tornado, and Marty Feely, a
Texas tornado-broker who is determined to track down a twister
for Antonio. The program illustrates how destructive tornadoes
can be by re-creating a fatal day in 1991 when a family of
twisters wiped out a Kansas town. The second half of the episode
tells amazing stories of lightning, including incredible footage
