So: U-env
From: nsundt@igc.apc.org
Newsgroups: climate.news
Subject: MICHIGAN MAN INFECTED WITH MALARIA
Date: 31 May 1996 20:42:02 -0800 (PST)

from Global Change Electronic Edition...
                                
               MICHIGAN MAN INFECTED WITH MALARIA
  Higher temperatures and humidities raise disease threat in US

The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention report that a 31-
year Michigan man was hospitalized in early September 1995 with
malaria. According to the CDC's Morbidity and Mortality Weekly
Report (MMWR) (pp 398-400, 17 May 1996), the disease probably was
transmitted by a locally infected mosquito of the genus Anopheles
carrying the malaria parasite (of the genus Plasmodium). The
authors report that mosquito-borne malaria has not been
transmitted and recorded that far north in the United States
since 1972.

The article, "Mosquito-Transmitted Malaria -- Michigan, 1995,"
cites several factors in support of its conclusion that the
patient acquired malaria in Michigan from a local mosquito. These
factors include above normal temperatures in Michigan during the
month of August 1995 when the man probably was bitten by the
insect. The area's average evening temperature that month was
24.2oC (75.6oF), about 3.3oC (5.9oF) above the 30-year average.
The authors write that the higher temperatures "may have
facilitated malaria transmission because warmer external
temperatures shorten the reproductive (sporogonic) cycle of the
parasite and prolong Anopheles spp. survival."

This is not the only recently reported case of malaria
transmitted in the US from mosquitoes. In the January-March 1996
issue of Emerging Infectious Diseases, the CDC's Jane R. Zucker
reports on recent (1986-1994) outbreaks of malaria in California,
New Jersey, New York and Texas. "A common feature of all recent
outbreaks has been weather that is hotter and more humid than
usual," Zucker writes in "Changing Patterns of Autochthonous
Malaria Transmission in the United States: A Review of Recent
Outbreaks."

Malaria once was endemic in many parts of the US. But incidence
of the disease apparently peaked in the late 19th century and by
the 1950s the CDC concluded it had been eradicated. Since that
time, nearly all reported cases of malaria in the US were among
people infected outside the country. In Michigan, for example, an
average of 30 imported malaria cases are believed to occur
annually. From 1957 through 1994, only 76 cases of malaria are
believed to have been locally transmitted by mosquitoes in the
US.

WARMER TEMPERATURES INCREASE DISEASE RISK

The spread of the disease begins with favorable breeding
environments for the mosquitoes: sitting water and mild
temperatures. Next, infected humans must be available. In the US,
most of the available human hosts originally picked up the
disease outside the country from areas where malaria is endemic.
After the insects draw blood from infected humans, the mosquitoes
cannot transmit malaria unless they live long enough for the
malarial parasites to complete their sporogonic cycles within the
mosquitos. Zucker explains that infected mosquitos in the US
rarely transmit malaria partly because their lifespans are often
shorter than the sporogonic cycles.

But this situation can change dramatically as air temperatures
rise. For example, below 16-18oC (61-64oF), the malaria parasite
P. vivax cannot complete its sporogonic cycle. At about 18oC
(64oF), the cycle takes 30 days. With just a 2oC (4oF) increase
-- to 20oC (68oF)-- the cycle is cut by 1/3 to 20 days. And at
27oC (81oF), the cycle only takes 8-13 days. 

At the same time, higher temperatures -- and humidities -- help
mosquitoes develop and survive. So warmer temperatures and higher
humidities, through their dual effect on both the parasite and
the mosquito, can greatly increase the risk of malaria
transmission.

US MAY SEE "REEMERGENCE OF MALARIA AS A SERIOUS PUBLIC HEALTH
PROBLEM"

In testimony before the Congress on 9 March 1993, Patrick J.
Michaels of the University of Virginia, said that "one very
reliable set of data (though limited to the coterminous United
States) indicated that almost all [climate] warming had taken
place at night" and reassured the Congress that this was "benign
climate change." Michaels, a Professor in the Department of
Environmental Sciences at the University of Virginia, is a
notorious and vocal critic of what he has called "the current
popular vision of climate gloom and doom." 

More recently, a publication edited by Michaels (World Climate
Report, 29 April 1996) claimed that "recent outbreaks of tropical
diseases can't logically be attributed to global warming." The
publication says that even with warming "malaria's impact will be
greater in undeveloped countries," adding parenthetically (and
incorrectly) that "malaria was wiped out in Europe and the United
States in the 1800s."

Despite such reassurances from Michaels and others, the recent
outbreaks add to mounting evidence which suggest that climate
warming, even if concentrated at night, may be far from benign.
In fact, nighttime warming may be particularly problematic in
some respects, since mosquitoes feed mostly at night. And among
disease-transmitting insects, the World Health Organization (WHO)
warns in The World Health Report 1996, "the mosquito is the
greatest menace." The WHO, which estimates that 2.1 million
people died in 1995 from malaria alone, adds that "the effects of
climate change may allow some diseases to spread to new
geographical areas." 

Speaking specifically of the US, Zucker cautions that
environmental changes along with greater drug resistance and air
travel "could lead to the reemergence of malaria as a serious
public health problem" in the US. The warning is supported by
recent research results which suggest climate change may produce
conditions in North America which are much more favorable to the
spread of malaria. And unlike residents of areas where malaria
presently is endemic, most people in the US have little or no
resistance to the disease.

What measures can be taken to deal with the emerging threat?
Researchers reported last year in the CDC's MMWR (pp 295-303, 21
April 1995), that "[i]mportant strategies for preventing the re-
establishment of malaria as an endemic disease in the United
States are prompt recognition and reporting of cases of malaria;
appropriate treatment of all malaria cases...and implementation
of appropriate control measures."

