So: U-env
From: nsundt@igc.apc.org
Newsgroups: climate.news
Subject: 6-7 JUNE: CLIMATE CHANGE ANALYSIS W
Date: 31 May 1996 20:42:05 -0800 (PST)

from Global Change Electronic Edition...
                                
                CLIMATE CHANGE ANALYSIS WORKSHOP
              Springfield, Virginia, 6-7 June 1996

A group of US government agencies will sponsor on 6-7 June 1996 a
Climate Change Analysis Workshop, in Springfield, Virginia.
According to a Federal Register notice (Vol. 61, No. 79, pp
17893-17894, 23 April 1996), the "purpose of the workshop is to
provide a forum to share and discuss information on analytical
issues to help inform U.S. policymakers and the interested public
as we move forward in negotiations concerning possible next steps
under the Berlin Mandate." The sponsors include the US
Departments of Agriculture, Commerce, Energy and State; and the
Environmental Protection Agency. 

The Berlin Mandate of the Framework Convention on Climate Change
(FCCC) emerged from the FCCC's first Conference of the Parties
(COP-1) held in Berlin, Germany, from 28 March to 7 April 1995.
The Berlin Mandate launched negotiations which are supposed to
lead the parties "to take appropriate actions for the period
beyond 2000." The negotiations are to be completed by the third
Conference of the Parties (COP-3) in Autumn 1997.

The worskhop will focus on the Berlin Mandate's key issues.
According to the Federal Register announcement, the issues are:
   
   *the elaboration of policies and measures, 
   
   *the setting of quantified emissions limitation and reduction
   objectives, and 
   
   *actions to advance the implementation of existing commitments
   under Article 4.1 for Parties not included in Annex 1.

The announcment adds that the workshop will give the US
government agencies the opportunity to "present the interim
results of their ongoing analyses related to the economic and
environmental impacts of issues arising in the context of these
negotiations." Others also will be allowed "to present analytical
studies that contribute to an improved understanding of the
issues..."

For details, contact the Workshop Information Line at +1 703 934
3870.

*****************

