Subject: GLOBAL CHANGE, RECENT POSTINGS
Date: 31 May 1996 20:42:09 -0800 (PST)

from Global Change Electronic Edition...
                                
                        NEW ARTICLES IN
               GLOBAL CHANGE ELECTRONIC EDITION
             TO BE POSTED FIRST WEEK IN JUNE 1996.

IMPACTS
Consequences of Climate Change and Ozone Depletion ... 
   
   MICHIGAN MAN INFECTED WITH MALARIA. Higher temperatures and
   humidities raise disease threat in US. The Centers for Disease
   Control and Prevention report that a 31-year Michigan man was
   hospitalized in early September 1995 with malaria. The disease
   probably was transmitted locally by an infected mosquito.
   Mosquito-borne malaria has not been transmitted recorded that
   far north in the United States since 1972.(1 June, 1996) 

ECONOMICS
   
   CENTER FOR GLOBAL CHANGE RELEASES STATE CARBON TAX MODEL. The
   Center for Global Change at the University of Maryland has
   produced a model which "provides a reasonable estimate of the
   revenues from a state carbon tax, their distribution among
   fuels and sectors, and the direct burden on households." (1
   June 1996) 

OTHER SOURCES OF INFORMATION
   
   CENTER FOR GLOBAL CHANGE: PUBLICATIONS. The University of
   Maryland's Center for Global Change closed its doors on 31 May
   1996. We list the publications it produced since it opened in
   1989. Links to more than a dozen of the Center's publications
   are provided. (posted 1 June, 1996) 
   
   RECENT RELEASES, JUNE 1996 (PART I) (posted 1 June 1996). 
   
   RECENT RELEASES, JUNE 1996 (PART II) (posted 1 June 1996). 
   
   CLIMATE CHANGE AND OZONE DEPLETION UPDATES FROM THE UK. The
   Atmospheric Research and Information Center of the Manchester
   Metropolitan University (Manchester, UK) continues in 1996 to
   post 4-6 news "snippets" on global change each month. The most
   recent stories are dated April 1996. (posted 1 June, 1996) 
   
   GUIDE TO IPCC-RELATED PUBLICATIONS. Includes the latest
   information on the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change's
   Second Assessment Report. The report, entitled Climate Change
   1995, has just been published by Cambridge University Press.
   (1 June, 1996). 

