So: U-env
From: P.DIEHL@OLN.comlink.apc.org
Newsgroups: energy.nuclear
Subject: World's 1st Nuclear Laundry
Date: 20 Jun 1996 21:46:00

message forwarded from NucNet News:

==========================================================================
   The World's Nuclear News Agency
   Operated by the European Nuclear Society                    13-Jun-1996
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

         World's First "Nuclear Laundry" Washes Whiter

A company in the Netherlands has come up with the answer to those nuclear
"washday blues" by starting up the world's first commercial laundry for
industrial clothing, worn by workers at nuclear facilities, which might be
slightly contaminated by radioactivity.

If clothes start radiating more than just good style, the firm with the
solution is Euro Nuclear Services, which has just announced the opening of
its unique facility at Coevorden in north-east Holland, close to the border
with Germany. The laundry, covering an area of 2500 square metres,
eliminates the need for the operators of nuclear facilities to maintain
their own dedicated equipment and personnel for washing
slightly-contaminated clothing, and the company says the large-scale of the
specialist operation makes it economical.

Soiled material is sent in special containers to the laundry where it is
screened for radioactive contamination. Depending on the results, the
laundry is separated into two process lines. It either goes to one for
slightly-contaminated clothing, such as overalls, or to another for
non-contaminated goods, such as underwear and towels.

The washing is done with the use of specially-developed formulas, and
humidity-controlled dryers are also part of the process. State-of-the-art
detectors are used to check for residual radioactivity, before the
freshly-laundered goods are folded and repackaged, ready for return to the
customer - and another shift at the nuclear plant.

In addition to the laundering process, the company offers a complete
leasing programme, saving customers the expense of purchasing, storing and
stock-taking special clothing supplies which are sometimes only needed for
short periods.

---------------------------------------------------------------------------
Source: Euro Nuclear Services
Company contact: Benno Reichert, phone +49-2639-1515, fax +49-2639-1670
Editor / contact: Jack Ashton
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
