<pre>
So: U-env
From: iatp@igc.apc.org
Newsgroups: env.biotech
Subject: IP/Biodiversity News 6-10-96
Date: 14 Jun 1996 10:51:59 -0800 (PST)

INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY & BIODIVERSITY NEWS
Produced by the Institute for Agricultue and Trade Policy
June 10, 1996
Volume 5, Number 5
__________________________________________
Headlines:
- NEW PATENT LAW ADOPTED BY BRAZIL
- APPLICATIONS CREATE BACKLOG AT U.S. PATENT OFFICE
- PATENT OF BREAST CANCER GENE OPPOSED
- INDIAN TRIBE AWARDED ROYALTIES
- GENETICALLY MODIFIED MAIZE SEED REJECTED BY EU
- COCOA TREE GENETICS RESEARCHED
- SHELLFISH IMMUNIZATION FOCUS OF RESEARCH 

NEW PATENT LAW ADOPTED BY BRAZIL

Brazil, the world's sixth largest market for pharmaceuticals, 
adopted a new patent law in May that extends intellectual 
property protection to foods and pharmaceuticals. The United 
States lobbied intensively for stronger intellectual property 
rights in Brazil. "Brazil has done the right thing...We see 
it as a model for the rest of Latin America and the world," 
said a spokesman for the Pharmaceutical Research 
Manufacturers of America. Supporters of the law contend that 
the law should stimulate outside investment, while critics 
contend that in the short run it will drive commercial 
research offshore or into the hands of multinational 
companies because of the lack of local capacity. Sara Kanter, 
technical director of the Association of the National 
Pharmaceutical Laboratories in Brazil said, "Our industry is 
still in the copy-and-innovative phase, and our market share 
does not allow us to have capital enough to invest in 
research...90% of the Brazilian academic research [in the 
field] is being absorbed by multinational companies."

"Patent Law Closes Drug Loophole," SCIENCE, Vol. 272, May 17, 
1996.

APPLICATIONS CREATE BACKLOG AT U.S. PATENT OFFICE

The immense amount of genetic data churned out by automated 
DNA sequencers has created a flood of patent applications to 
the U.S. Patent and Trademarks Office (PTO). According to PTO 
official John Doll, it could take a single senior staffer 
more than 90 years to examine the DNA sequences that 
havealready been submitted for patents. The PTO held public 
briefings to outline the scope of the problem, and public 
hearings to elicit ideas on how to streamline a painstaking 
and time-consuming process. It takes 60 to 65 hours to 
examine a batch of 100 sequences, at a cost of about $5,000. 
The sequences now awaiting review will cost more than $20 
million to process, yet fees may come to only $100,000.

For example, to maximize the $1,000 filing fee, companies 
that specialize in high volume DNA sequencing put clusters of 
sequences into a single application. Incyte Pharmaceuticals 
of California and Human Genome Sciences of Maryland have been 
channeling data from their mechanized processes into the PTO 
at a torrential rate. Incyte puts as many as 5000 DNA 
sequences into a single application. Randy Scott, Incyte's 
chief scientific officer, estimates the company has filed 
"over 400,000" sequences.

Eliot Marshall, "Patent Office Faces 9-Year Backlog," 
SCIENCE, Vol. 272, May 3, 1996.

PATENT OF BREAST CANCER GENE OPPOSED

A coalition of hundreds of women's and cancer advocacy groups 
is forming to oppose Myriad Genetics' application for a 
patent on a gene, BRCA1, which is linked to breast cancer. 
Nancy Evans, a vice president of Breast Cancer Action, a 
member of the newly formed coalition, said, "We want to 
promote as much research as possible...if someone patents 
this gene, they'll control the research. And they may not 
always want to encourage competition for products they're 
developing. That's not in the public interest, and it worries 
us." Carl Feldbaum, president of the Biotech Industry 
Organization said, "If people think new drugs and new cures 
come out of basic research funded by the Government, that's a 
misperception...they don't, they won't. All the important new 
gene therapies are based on genes that had patent protection. 
Without that protection, investors won't put up the millions 
of dollars for research." According to Wendy McGoodwin, 
executive director of Council for Responsible Genetics, the 
research was not entirely dependent on investors; the 
government has paid for much of the basic genetic research 
and is committed to continuing it. She said, "It seems unfair 
that a private company using the benefit of that research 
would patent it, then turn around and charge us more."

Tamar Lewin, "Move to Patent Cancer Gene Is Criticized," NEW 
YORK TIMES, May 21, 1996.

INDIAN TRIBE AWARDED ROYALTIES

The intellectual property rights to the active ingredient of 
a plant long known to combat stress has been awarded to the 
Kani, an indigenous tribe in the southern Indian state of 
Kerala. Tropical Botanical Garden and Research Institute 
(TBGRI), a government-owned research facility developed a 
drug, jeevani, which is based on the active ingredient, and 
sold the "know-how" to Arya Vaidhya Pharmacy. The Kani tribe 
will receive half of the know-how fee and a share of a two 
percent royalty on future drug sales. Ralupu Pushpangadan, 
director of TBGRI,  said, "The world did not know about this 
unique plant until the Kani people led us to it." He 
commented, "Our jeevani acts like Chinese ginseng...but it is 
superior, because it does not contain any steroid." Before 
deciding to market the drug, extensive trials were carried 
out on Indian athletes.

"Indian Ginseng Brings Royalties for Tribe," NATURE, May 16, 
1996.

GENETICALLY MODIFIED MAIZE SEED REJECTED BY EU

A European Union regulatory body denied approval of Ciba-
Geigy's maize seed genetically engineered to be pesticide 
resistant for use in the European agriculture industry for 
two reasons. It was considered not to be sufficiently labeled 
and a gene engineered into the seed would have poisoned 
insect larvae. Some member states of the EU fear that the 
gene could be transferred into the wild once the maize seed 
sprouted. 

The rejection by the regulatory committee will be passed onto 
the Council of Ministers who can choose to accept the 
rejection or favor approval, in which case it would be sent 
back to the regulatory body for input from the executive 
body. The regulatory body consists of representatives from 
member states and was set up under the EU's Directive 
90/220 on Deliberate Release of Genetically Modified 
Organisms into the Environment.

"Regulatory Body Rejects Approval of Genetically Modified 
Maize Seed," INTERNATIONAL ENVIRONMENTAL REPORTER, May 1, 
1996.


COCOA TREE GENETICS RESEARCHED

Researchers at Reading University are using genetic-
fingerprinting technologies on all types of cocoa trees, with 
funding provided by a grant from Cocoa Research, UK. The 
technology used to track down criminals is being used for the 
fingerprinting of the cocoa trees. The project will first 
catalogue the varieties of cocoa trees in greenhouses in UK, 
and then import leaves from cocoa trees around the world. By 
the end of the year, it plans to produce a report with 
genetic details of each variety. Mr. Eric Beauchamp, 
secretary of Cocoa Research said, "In the long term we want 
to transform and alter the way the trees produce cocoa to 
make them more efficient and resistant to diseases and 
pests."

Deborah Hargreaves, "Geneticists Compile Cocoa Catalogue," 
FINANCIAL TIMES, May 10, 1996.

SHELLFISH IMMUNIZATION FOCUS OF RESEARCH 

Oysters, clams and mussels have been genetically engineered 
with a retrovirus that would immunize the shellfish from such 
viruses as hepatitis A, which can be passed on to humans. 
Thomas Chen of the University of Connecticut and Jane Burns 
of the University of California, San Diego, have completed 
experiments in which they altered the protein coating of a 
retrovirus, loaded it with a test gene, and injected it into 
the surf clams. The gene was passed on to the offspring, 
becoming a permanent part of their genetic code.

David Graham, "Gene Therapy: New Hope for Bivalves," BUSINESS 
WEEK, May 20, 1996.

_________________________________________
Intellectual Property and Biodiversity News is produced by 
the Institute for Agriculture and Trade Policy, Mark Ritchie, 
President.  Editor: Jean Carruthers.  Electronic mail 
versions are available free of charge for subscribers. For 
information about fax subscriptions contact: IATP, 1313 Fifth 
Street SE, Suite 303, Minneapolis, MN 55414.  For information 
on subscribing to this and other IATP news bulletins, send e-
mail to:  iatp-info@iatp.org.  IATP provides contract 
research services to a wide range of corporate and not-for-
profit organizations.  For more information, contact Dale 
Wiehoff at 612-379-5980, or send email to: dwiehoff@iatp.org.














