<pre>
So: U-env
From: patrick@igc.apc.org
Newsgroups: env.dams
Subject: Press Release: US EX-IM SAYS NO TO
Date: 30 May 1996 14:05:52 -0800 (PST)

From: patrick@irn.org (Patrick McCully)
Subject: Press Release: US EX-IM SAYS NO TO THREE GORGES ! 

PRESS RELEASE
Thursday, May 30, 1996

Owen Lammers
(510) 848-1155

 EXPORT-IMPORT BANK SAYS NO TO WORLD'S M0ST DESTRUCTIVE DAM
           OTHER EXPORT CREDIT AGENCIES URGED TO DO SAME

After nearly two years of review, the US Export-Import Bank today denied
support to US corporations chasing contracts on China's Three Gorges Dam.
Caterpillar and Rotec Industries of Illinois and Voith Hydro of
Pennsylvania were hoping for letters of intent for loan guarantees from
Ex-Im which would enable them to submit formal bids to sell China
construction equipment for the dam.

Ex-Im Bank's President Martin A. Kamarck issued a statement today stating
that the Bank's board "has concluded that Ex-Im Bank cannot issue a letter
of interest for this project at this time. The information received [from
China] though voluminous, fails to establish the project's consistency with
the Bank's environmental guidelines."

"This is phenomenal," says International Rivers Network Executive Director
Owen Lammers. "It represents a serious blow against what would become the
world's most socially and environmentally ruinous dam."

According to Kamarck, "the major (though not only) issues of concern" for
Ex-Im were reservoir water quality, the endangered species and other
"ecological resources" threatened by the project, the "environmental and
socioeconomic impacts associated with the proposed resettlement of 1.3
million people", and the "protection of cultural resources".

The Chinese government has had numerous problems finding foreign financing
for the dam, estimated to cost up to $75 billion. The World Bank, the
leading international funder of large dams, has for some time stated that
it will not help fund the project. An international bond offering first
scheduled for release in April 1994 has been delayed indefinitely due to
concerns within the investment community over the financial risks inherent
to the dam.

China wants foreign equipment suppliers to arrange cheap loans to pay for
their equipment from their national export credit agencies (ECAs). With the
US declining interest, international attention will now focus on the ECAs
of Canada, Japan, Germany and Switzerland which are also considering
providing credits.

Owen Lammers says: "We hope that these other countries reach the same
conclusions as the US. Without international financial and technical
support it will be very hard for the Chinese government to complete the
dam. Opponents of the dam within China will stand a far greater chance of
stopping it."

In September 1995, following a year-long review of the project, the
National Security Council recommended that Ex-Im deny support for the
project. In December 1993, the US Bureau of Reclamation cancelled its
contract with the Chinese government to provide technical assistance for
the Three Gorges Dam.

If completed, the Three Gorges Dam would stretch nearly a mile across and
tower 575 feet above the bed of the Yangtze. Its reservoir would stretch
over 350 miles upstream and force the displacement of 1.3 million people.
It would be the most powerful hydroelectric dam in the world. Construction
began in 1994 and is scheduled to take 20 years.

In March 1991, opposition to the project in China forced the suspension of
the dam, but the project was swiftly resurrected by Premier Li Peng in the
aftermath of the Tiananmen Square massacre.

ENDS


