<pre>
So: U-env
From: patrick@igc.apc.org
Newsgroups: env.dams
Subject: NBA INTERNATIONAL UPDATE
Date: 10 Jun 1996 20:04:47 -0800 (PST)

From: patrick@irn.org (Patrick McCully)

From: Shripad Dharmadhikary
Narmada Bachao Andolan

NARMADA INTERNATIONAL UPDATE
3 June, 1996

1. Narmada Satyagraha - Monsoon 1996

The Monsoon Satyagraha has been the focus of our fight every year. This
year, however, the monsoon will be different. Due to the people's struggle,
construction on the dam has been at a standstill for the last
one-and-a-half years. The Supreme Court of India too has taken significant
cognizance of the issues raised by the people and has stayed the work on
the central portion of the dam till at least 16 July, 1996, when the case
resumes for hearing. Given this, the Andolan has decided that the
satyagraha this year will be of a different nature.

Now the people of the valley want to assert their right to live in the
valley - and this satyagraha will be an expression of this right. This will
be done by the launching of many different programs of construction and
development (nav nirman) in the Valley. It will be a celebration of living
in the valley. Tree planting on a massive scale, housing, bio-gas, soil
water conservation, small irrigation schemes, libraries, schools (four new
ones have already started) and so on. This is the people's way of saying,
asserting that they are determined to stay in the Valley, and will work to
make this stay better, prosperous and bountiful.

Moreover, on one hand, the people have stopped further destruction by
stopping construction. But for those who have fought, and have seen their
houses, farms, property all submerged by the partly built dam,
rehabilitation is still a distant dream. Many of those who have faced the
submergence have of course declared from the beginning that they will not
move, that they will not leave the valley. And they are still there. There
were others, especially from the villages of Gujarat, who had taken the
Government for its word and had agreed to shift, some as early as 12-14
years back. Their state today is terrible. Many have abandoned their
"resettlement" sites and have gone back to their original village. Many
more are on the verge of doing so.

All these people and the Andolan are now demanding that until the
Government can ensure the proper rehabilitation of all those already
affected, it should not impound any water in the dam. Thus, the other major
demand of the satyagraha this year is the call to the Government to reopen
the sluices of the dam at 18 m, and to keep those at 53 m open.

The people are aware that it is as yet a fragile victory. The people are
aware that strong forces are reigned against them and these forces of the
vested interests could succeed in getting the construction work to start
again. The people, the valley, are prepared for such an eventuality, and if
this happens, the Andolan is perpetually ready to launch the do or die
struggle. This satyagraha will thus be also a means to monitor the
situation, to let the Government know that the people - not only of the
valley but of the whole Country - are watching their every move, and are
prepared to launch the highest struggle against this symbol of destructive
development.

The satyagraha will be launched from 21 June 1996, in the whole valley, but
with the centres at Jalsindhi (Jhabua District, Madhya Pradesh) and
Domkhedi (Dhule District, Maharashtra).

2. Harivallabh Parikh, head of the Anand Kiketan Ashram - one of the two
main pro-dam, pro-Government NGO's in Gujarat engaged in the rehabilitation
of the oustees who were vehemently trying to oppose the NBA - has been
charged with the rape of a 20 year-old tribal girl who was taking sewing
classes in his Ashram (Institute). While the police are searching for the
72 year-old "social worker," he is absconding. Many organisations,
including women's organisations, have called for his immediate arrest. It
is suspected that he may be getting political protection due to connections
in high places. While the rape case has been making headlines in Gujarat
for the last 10 days, it is a public secret that there have been many such
"going ons" in the Ashram for many years. But the Ashram has been very
powerful and it has been difficult for people to raise the issue.

3. Regarding the proposed Asian Development Bank loan for the State of
Gujarat, details are now available. The ADB is planning a massive
structural adjustment program (SAP) at the State level in Gujarat. The ADB
states that the Gujarat loan is being given to assist this, and the amount
will be determined by the adjustment costs of restructuring. However, the
money will go straight to the State budget to cover "revenue shortfalls due
to the SAP." Thus, it still leaves open the possibility that the money
could be used for SSP, as the funds would be fungible. NBA has requested
the ADB to give us the calculations that will determine this "cost of
adjustment" which will be used to determine the loan amount. NBA has also
asked that it be kept informed. ADB has refused to make any commitment on
the former. The loan amount is tentatively put at 250 million US$ in first
phase to be followed by loans of further 500 to 750 million US$. It is
likely to go to the Board by the year end. We must continue to monitor.

4. It may be recollected that the Supreme Court had asked the party states
to resolve their differences in three months and has fixed the date of
hearing for 16 July. Information available to us indicates that the states
have not been able to do so as yet. Much will depend upon the new
Government at the Center. Last month, after the Parliament elections, the
right wing party BJP was invited to form the Government, but this lasted
only 15 days as it could not get the required majority. A new coalition
Government has now taken charge headed by Deve Gowda of the Janata Dal, a
centrist party. The new Government will seek the vote of Confidence only on
10 June. Any meetings on the SSP are likely only after this.

5.  Gujarat oustees are getting more and more frustrated. These oustees,
who had never opposed the project but had sought resettlement with the help
of pro-dam NGOs, have been displaced over the last 12-14 years. Their
living conditions are now terrible, and the Government seems not to care.
Many are now joining the NBA, threatening to move back to their original
villages. On 30 May, 1996, over 600 of these oustees came to Baroda and in
an aggressive but peaceful demonstration, occupied the foyer of the office
of the Nigam (the corporation building the dam). They only wanted the
officials to come and discuss their problems. The official Mr. Rajagopalan
came only after 2 hours. He was extremely rude and arrogant and refused to
talk to NBA activist and walked out of the gathering in 5 minutes, rudely
cutting short the people who were speaking. This has come as the last straw
to the people, who declared their intention to "empty their resettlement
sites and return to the original villages" and warned the Government that
they will not allow the dam to be filled.

NBA
B-13, Shivam Flats
Ellora Park
Baroda, Gujarat
India 390007

NB. The NBA's phone number has changed to: +91 265 382232


=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=
      Patrick McCully, Campaigns Director, International Rivers Network
              1847 Berkeley Way, Berkeley, California 94703, USA
                  Tel. (510) 848 1155 Fax (510) 848 1008
