<pre>
So: U-env
From: amrivers@igc.apc.org
Newsgroups: env.dams
Subject: Salt Caves Hydroproject-Dead at Las
Date: 13 Jun 1996 12:38:21 -0800 (PST)

 
AMERICAN RIVERS
NEWS RELEASE
 
 
For Release:                        Contact:
June 12, 1996                        Tom Cassidy,
                                American Rivers,
                                (202) 547-6900
 
 
SALT CAVES HYDROPROJECT -- DEAD AT LAST!
 
UPPER KLAMATH RIVER
RECEIVES FINAL LEGAL PROTECTION
 
 
In Washington today, the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission voted to dismiss the City of Klamath Falls' license application to construct the notorious Salt Caves Hydroelectric Project.   The project was proposed for construction on the Upper Klamath River in southern Oregon.
 
"This is the final nail in the coffin of one of the nation's most damaging proposed hydroprojects," said Tom Cassidy, General Counsel for American Rivers.   "This action is the final chapter in one of the great river conservation battles of the past decade."  
 
American Rivers and other organizations have fought to protect the Upper Klamath from this hydropower project since 1988.  In 1988, the citizens of Oregon added the Upper Klamath to the Oregon Scenic Rivers system by ballot initiative.  That same year, as part of the landmark Oregon Omnibus Wild and Scenic Rivers Act, the U.S. Congress authorized a study of whether the Upper Klamath should be included in the National Wild and Scenic Rivers system.  The federal study was completed in 1992 and found that the river was a suitable addition to the federal rivers system.
 
In 1992, Oregon Governor Barbara Roberts petitioned Secretary of the Interior Bruce Babbitt to add the river to the National Wild and Scenic Rivers System, pursuant to section 2(a)(ii) of the Wild and Scenic Rivers Act.  On September 23, 1994, Secretary Babbitt added the Upper Klamath to the national rivers system.
 
The City of Klamath Falls sued Secretary Babbitt to block protection of the river, however, in a May, 1996 decision, a federal court rejected the City's legal challenge.  American Rivers and other conservation groups, including the National Wildlife Federation, Oregon Natural Resources Council, Sierra Club and Save Our Klamath River intervened in that case, supporting the Wild and Scenic River designation.
 
In 1990, American Rivers identified the Upper Klamath as the nation's Most Endangered River because of the Salt Caves project.  
 
The Upper Klamath is known for its outstanding fisheries, whitewater, wildlife and historical values.  Diverse forests along the Klamath provide critical habitat for blacktail deer, wild turkey, bald eagle and other wildlife.  The Upper Klamath River Gorge has some of the best wild trout fishing in the state of Oregon, as well as exciting world-class whitewater.  No other river in the region offers such superb Class IV and V rapids for year-round rafting and kayaking, attracting boaters from all over America and generating over two million dollars a year in direct revenues for the rafting and fishing industries plus much more in indirect revenue.  The Klamath Gorge is also sacred land to the Shasta Indians.
 
If the project had been constructed, the last remaining free-flowing stretch of the river would have been severely degraded, thus threatening wild trout populations, whitewater recreational opportunities, wildlife habitat, and sacred Indian lands.  Moreover, the recreational resources of the Klamath River would no longer have been able to provide continued and considerable economic support to the Klamath Falls area by sustaining fishing and whitewater boating activities and tourism.
 
American Rivers is North America's leading river conservation organization.  For more information, contact American Rivers, 1025 Vermont Avenue, NW, Suite 720, Washington, D.C., 20005, phone: (202) 547-6900.
 
                               #  #  #
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 

