So: U-env
From: patrick@igc.apc.org
Newsgroups: env.dams
Subject: Argentinean NGO Letter on Parana Me
Date: 01 Jul 1996 11:11:00 -0800 (PST)

From: patrick@irn.org (Patrick McCully)
Subject: Argentinean NGO Letter on Parana Medio Dam

Provincial Council of Environmental Non-Governmental Organizations of Santa Fe

9 de julio 3563
3000 Santa Fe, Argentina
Tel: +54-42-56-26-09

Santa Fe, May 13, 1996

To: Mr. Jorge Obeid, Governor of Santa Fe Province
       Mr. Gualberto Venesia, Vice-Governor of Santa Fe and President of
the Chamber of Senators
       Mr. Jesus Gonzalez, Coordinator of the Comision of Evaluation and
Followup of the Project for Integrated Economic Development of the
MiddleParana
       Mr. Ruben Mehauod, President of the Chamber of Deputies of the
Province of Santa Fe

From: Provincial Council of Environmental Non-Governmental
Organizations of Santa Fe

We are writing to request more information regarding the proposal of a
consortium of foreign companies, promoted in our region by provincial
legislative representatives to construct a hydroelectric dam on the middle
Parana River.  We are aware that these decisions should be made according
to the genuine interests of their constituents, avoiding decisions behind
closed doors.

We think that society as a whole should be protagonists in determining
their own destiny and that they have the right to be informed, as well as
to take part in decision making.  For this reason, the social organizations
which have signed below solicit the following:

1.  We ask you to explain the reasons which led to the acceptance of the
proposal, and whether these include a deficit of electrical energy.  This
as a result of the fact that we are surprised that the national government,
legislators and technical organs are pushing this project, even though the
details of the project are not publicly known, nor its possible
consequences for our region.

2.  We request that a process of public participation be initiated with an
adequate timeframe, so that different sectors of society, universities,
social organizations, labor unions, professors, farmers, and other affected
populations can reeive objective information which will permit them to know
and to analyze for themselves the characteristics of the project and its
possible consequences.

3.  That public audiences of sufficient breadth and with a reasonable
timeframe are carried out following a process of informing the public,
which provide a real opportunity to propose alternatives to the project.

4.  That the debate must include an analysis of alternative proposals for
sustainable development of natural and human resources for the middle
Parana valley, based upon respect and support for the cultural-economic
model already existent: agro-forestry, cattle raising on the islands,
production of rice and other appropriate crops, commercial and sport
fishing, fishculture, tourism, and other possibilities for utilization and
creation of sources of labor and production.

5. That a thorough economic study and analysis be carried out to acheive a
balance between possibilities for sustainable development and the creation
of wealth and employment mentioned in the preceding point, and which looks
at the proposal to construct the dam, taking into account its negative
environmental and social impacts.

6. That in this sense it is clearly specified who will be responsible for
the economic compensation to farmers, land owners, and populations affected
by the project in terms of:  loss of income from a loss of current and
potential productive activities, impacts on land and property -- including
the eventual salinization and/or elevation of the water table west of
provincial highway no.1 -- loss of jobs and natural subsistence activities,
and the possible expansion of tropical diseases from surrounding areas,
among other impacts.

7. That throughout this process Article 41 and its accompanying provisions
of the National Constitution be respected, as well as national and
provincial laws, and international treaties signed by Argentina, such as
the Treaty of San Jose, Costa Rica, the International Agreement on
Protection of Biodiversity, recommendations of the U.N. Summit on Social
Development, and others.

8. That an objective and impartial analysis of the consequences of what
appears to be an "experiment" be guaranteed, including its impacts on the
balance of this enormous natural hydrological system, which top
international experts have declared to be difficult to predict based upon a
lack of sufficient studies and data.  This objectivity cannot come from
those connected with the project nor from those expecting to make money
from it.

Finally, from different sectors of the people of Santa Fe, we demand that
the public authorities act wisely and judiciously as this case requires,
without making hasty decisions based upon outside and mutual interests, but
rather based upon the needs of our people.  These decisions risk leaving
the country dependent for 50 years upon the interests of foreign companies
and governments and which are not based upon preserving those resources
which bond human development, our cultural identity, security, and quality
of life.

With distinguished consideration,

Susana Saz,
Coordinator of the Provincial Council of Environmental Non-Governmental
Organizations of Santa Fe

Centro de Proteccion a la Naturaleza
Fundacion Proteger
Taller Ecologista (Rosario)
Asociacion Amigos de la Vida (Rafaela)
Fundacion Linea Verde (Santo Tome)
Red Cavi Litoral Argentino
Asociacion de Medicos por el Medio Ambiente
Movimiento Ecologico Sancarlino Con Vida (San Carlos Centro)
Centro Ecologico del Parana (Coronda)
Comision de Ecologia de Romang
Asociacion Para la Proteccion de la Vida Silvestre (Santa Fe)
Fundacion Habitat y Desarrollo
Sociedad Naturista
Asociacion de Defensa del Consumidor
Grupo Ecologista Renacer (Lopez)
Centro de Defensa del Ambiente (Villa Ocampo)
Centro Ecologista Renacer (Villa Constitucion)
Grupo Ecologista Genesis (Rosario)
Fundacion Ecologica (Alejandra)
Asociacion Cooperadora de Ecologia (Reconquista y Avellaneda)


=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=*=
      Patrick McCully, Campaigns Director, International Rivers Network
              1847 Berkeley Way, Berkeley, California 94703, USA
                  Tel. (510) 848 1155 Fax (510) 848 1008
