<pre>
So: U-env
From: amacnow@igc.apc.org
Newsgroups: env.forum
Subject: HUMANE WHALE KILLING ISSUE
Date: 16 Jun 1996 08:04:48 -0800 (PST)


      FROM: Alan Macnow
            Consultant, Japan Whaling Association
               TEL: (212) 688-5580
               FAX: (212) 688-5857
               E-Mail: amacnow@igc.apc.org


          HUMANE WHALE KILLING ISSUE CREATED TO BLOCK SUSTAINABLE USE

                If the animal rights advocates have their way, sports
        fishing and duck hunting may soon meet the same fate as whaling.
        People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals (PETA) has just
        launched a major campaign against fishing with hook and line and
        Australian animal protection groups are now agitating world-wide
        to ban duck hunting on the grounds that it is not humane.
                Ironically, the commercial hunting of whales is more
        humane than all other forms of hunting, and probably more humane
        than the way these animals normally meet their end.  Whales are
        put to death faster, and with less suffering, than other animals
        or fish in the wild.
                But the anti-whaling activists at the International
        Whaling Committee meetings are using the issue as a means to
        delay or stop the sustainable use of whales.
                This year, the anti-whaling activists who dominate the
        delegations of New Zealand, Australia, the UK and the United
        States, are trying to ban the use of a device that ensures
        whales a relatively painless death.  Their objective: to curtail
        progress towards adoption of measures that will permit abundant
        whale populations to be harvested at levels well below their an-
        nual rates of increase through reproduction.
                The device, employed primarily by Japan, consists of a
        pair of electric lances used to electrocute whales not killed
        instantly by explosive harpoons.  The old method of whaling used
        a non-explosive harpoon and led to prolonged times to death.
        But the Japanese developed a penthrite explosive harpoon head
        which killed whales instantly or shocked them into insensibility
        until they could be dispatched with a secondary killing device,
        such as a gun, or a lance.  The next development was an electric
        lance, a secondary device to dispatch the whales faster and with
        less pain.
                A few years ago, a group of New Zealand anti-whaling ac-
        tivists set out to prove that the electric lance was ineffective
        as a fast killing method.  Using dead cetaceans washed up on
        shore, they produced voltage and amperage readings that enabled
        them to claim that the electric charge would be dissipated by
        the aqueous environment of the ocean and would not be strong
        enough to kill the whales quickly.  Though their theory fails to
        conform to reality, the other anti-whaling groups echoed it
        noisily, to the point where the major anti-whaling nations at
        the IWC proposed to ban the electric lance.
                The theory  and the flood of propaganda to the contrary,
        the fact remains that the electric lance has proved to be a fast
        and relatively painless secondary killing method.  From the time
        the lances are inserted near the heart to the time all signs of
        life cease averages a well documented 44 seconds.  Death would
        not come this fast if the electric lance was ineffective.
                But the anti-whaling activists continue to embrace the
        theory and ignore the facts, just as they have ignored all of
        the work done by the IWC Scientific Committee.  Several years
        ago, this prompted the Chairman of the Scientific Committee, Dr.
        Philip Hammond, to resign in disgust over IWC decisions that
        "are nothing to do with science".
                All of this concern over the humane killing of whales,
        strangely, is only directed at Japan.  Not a word is spoken
        about the 400 whales killed annually by "native" hunters such as
        the American Inuits of Alaska or the subsistence hunters of
        Greenland who catch whales with non-explosive harpoons.
                Whatever the killing methods, however, the death of a
        whale at the hands of today's whaler is much more humane than
        the way whales die in the wild: afflicted by disease, drowning
        when old age or infirmities impairs their swimming ability, torn
        apart and eaten by sharks and killer whales, or their vital
        organs crushed by their own weight when they get beached.
                At least the commercial whalers have tried to make their
        deaths as fast and painless as possible, to the point where it
        is more humane than most other forms of hunting.  Whaling today
        complies well with the U.S. Marine Mammal Protection Act, which
        states: "The term 'humane' in the context of the taking of a
        marine mammal means that method of taking which involves the
        least degree of pain and suffering practicable to the mammal in-
        volved." The operative word here is "practicable."
                                     -end-
.
