<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>DR16</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BACKGROUNDCOLOR="ffffff" TEXT="#000000"  background="http://www.knooppunt.be/~hit_run/caerts/logoback.gif">
<img align=right src="http://www.knooppunt.be/~hit_run/caerts/akai.gif">
<img align=top src="http://www.knooppunt.be/~hit_run/caerts/dr16.jpg">
<h1>DR16</h1>
<h2>16 track digital hard disk recorder/editor</h2>
<h5>Digital hard disk
recorder with
non-destructive editing
functions allowing near
instant data access,

and a 16 channel programmable mixer. It's
as easy to use as a conventional analogue
MTR machine but gives true 16 track
performance from a single hard disk at a
highly cost-effective price level per track.

Just what you would expect from Akai,
setting the standard in digital sound.</h5><hr>

<h3>Hard

disk

made
easy</h3>

With the Akai DR16, multi-track
recording and playback is as simple to
achieve as on a conventional MTR.
Familiar transport keys dominate the
front panel, and the DR16 punches in
and out of record on the fly just like
tape. Punches can be rehearsed and
repeated precisely using the Auto
Punch facility. The Take function can
store up to five trial recordings on one
track so allowing audition and selection
of the best performance or take. If you
make a mistake, the Undo function lets
you go back a step and try again. But
the DR16 does not stop at traditional
tape replacement alone. Proprietary LSI
chips developed for the Akai DD1500
dedicated post-production system allow
16 tracks of 16 bit linear digital audio
recording and playback from a single
SCSI hard disk.<p>

Disk size can be chosen by the user
with approximately 16 x 12 track
minutes at 44.1kHz available per 1Gbyte
disk memory. Connection to external
storage systems is easy and reliable; up
to six SCSI devices can be connected
via the SCSI interface including
magneto-optical disk drives, which allow
4 track recording and 8 track replay and
can also be used for data back-up. The
digital interface fitted as standard
makes data mixes directly to DAT.
Mixing is made particularly easy when
used in conjunction with the MT8. This
allows full control of the on-board
automated digital mixing without the
need for external sequencers, and can
be further enhanced by the EQ16 board
which provides 16 channels of three
band realtime EQ.
<hr>
<h3>Total
editing
with
zero loss</h3>

Editing functions have a logical and
familiar feel. But to benefit from the
possibilities of non-destructive hard disk
editing using the DR16 is a liberating
experience for the creative mind.
Random access to the disk means that
audio isn't copied physically as in
conventional systems, but can be
instantly played back in the edit
sequence on command from the
original audio data on the disk. You can
copy, repeat, move and insert or erase
phrases across multiple tracks without
using up any of the disk memory, and
play back the edit instantly with no loss
of original data.
<p>
Central to the system is the DR16's
Jog/Shuttle control for easy edit at any
speed determined by the operator
while monitoring playback; 9 locate
points and 100 stack points make the
edit point accessible directly.
<p>
The DR16 has a 16 channel
programmable mixer with on-board
snapshot and fade automation. Mix
mode allows the setting and recording
of level, pan, 2 x FX sends, bus on/off
and fade. The internal mix can be
recorded back to two tracks so
allowing sub-mixes and masters to be
recorded on the same disk drive.
<p>
Up to seven DR16s can be slaved to a
master unit using an ALX50 remote
cable giving a total track capacity of
128. Alternatively a mixture of DR16s
and DR8s can be used in any
combination, providing the user with an
extremely flexible expansion path.
<hr>
<h3>Solid
gains from
flexible
system</h3>

Any options required need only be fitted
to the master; the slave units will
automatically synchronise to the master
with sample accuracy. The IB801S
SCSI-B interface board option allows
connection to personal computers and
other peripherals, giving access to the
wide range of dedicated software
available.
<p>
The DR16 is the newest member of the
Akai hard disk recording family, sharing
its advanced component design with
the DD1500 digital audio post-
production workstation. It has high
density 18-bit 64-times oversampling
A/D converters and 20-bit 8-times
oversampling D/A converters for Master
and Send outs (18-bit 8-times
oversampling for Track 1-12 outs).
<hr>
<h3>Creative tool
of a musician</h3>

Drawing on Akai's extensive experience
with musical equipment, the DR16 is
able to integrate powerfully with the
musician's recording studio.<p>
Fitted with an IB803M MIDI
interface board, the DR16 can be
controlled via a MIDI sequencing
system. MIDI Machine Control from the
sequencer can be used to operate all
DR16 transport functions; realtime
dynamic digital mixing can be recorded
as part of the sequence and the DR16
transmits either MIDI Clock or MTC to
ensure everything stays perfectly in
sync. To make life easier, edits can be
displayed in Bars, Beats and Clocks.<p>
The IB804A Alesis ADAT digital
interface allows 8 channels of digital
audio to be copied in real time between
the DR16 and ADAT compatible
machines. It can also be used to make
a data back-up in ADAT format of all
16 tracks with edits.<p>
Not only is DR16 perfect for
multi-track recording, but the on-board
digital mixing can be enhanced by the
addition of the optional EQ 16 card to
provide real-time EQ. The mix can be
controlled via the dedicated MT8 Mixer
Controller, and two MT8s can be
connected to provide 16 faders if
required. All mixes can be mastered
directly to DAT with the AES/EBU and
SPDIF interfaces which are fitted as
standard.
<hr>
<h3>Pro Audio/Broadcast Application</h3>

Benefiting from the technology
developed for the DD1500 workstation
the DR16 provides unique
synchronisation and machine control
capabilities when fitted with the
appropriate optional interface boards.<p>
The IB802T SMPTE interface
board allows the DR16 to follow
external timecode formats backwards
and forwards even in slow motion,
maintaining phase lock accurate sync.
Add to this an IB805R RS422 interface
board and the DR16 can control any
standard type of professional VTR
providing integrated jog/shuttle of audio
and picture together from the DR16
front panel The IB805R also allows the
DR16 to be controlled remotely from
external edit controllers or synchronisers
using standard 9 pin protocols.<p>
Uniquely, Akai's experience in the
film industry has resulted in the
development of the IB805B Bi-Phase
interface board which allows the DR16
to integrate with film-based technology
and also enables conversion between
timecode and Bi-Phase.<p>
These interfaces are handled by
a multi-tasking operating system which
means it is possible for the DR16 to
control a VTR while in turn (when fitted
with an IB8Q3M MIDI interface board)
being controlled from a mixing desk
sending MIDI machine control (MMC).
All this and 16 channels of digital audio
and mixing as well!

<hr>
