<pre>
So: U-lam
From: lawg@igc.apc.org
Newsgroups: carnet.congres
Subject: LAWG Hotline June 4, 1996
Date: 06 Jun 1996 08:40:55 -0800 (PST)


You have reached the Latin America Working Group hotline, updated
June 4th.  Topics include the Ending of the Pastors for Peace Fast and
declassification on Guatemala and Honduras.

               Pastors End Fast, Computers Released

On May 24th the Pastors for Peace settled their dispute with the Treasury
Department regarding 395 impounded computers.  They also ended their 94-day fast.  In late February, Pastors had attempted to ship the computers to
Cuba where they were to be used in the Cuban health care system.  The
U.S. embargo on Cuba allows for the export of such humanitarian items,
but only if a license is granted.  Pastors, in protesting what they consider to
be an immoral law, had refused to apply for the license.  

Under the agreement, Treasury released the computers to the United
Methodist Church.  Pastors are continuing to ask for phone calls to ensure
that the computers are sent on to Cuba.  Call Secretary Rubin at Treasury:
202-622-1100.  Also call Leon Panetta at the White House: 202-456-6797.   
                          
        Declassification Begins on Guatemala

In response to Sister Dianna Ortiz's five week silent vigil and fast, and
hundreds of constituent calls drawing attention to the declassification issue,
which helped to inspire strong congressional interest, the State Department
declassified and made available to the public 5,874 U.S. government
documents on Guatemala.  These documents cover 17 cases of U.S. citizens
affected by violence in Guatemala, including the cases of Jennifer Harbury's
husband Efrain Bamaca, Sister Dianna Ortiz, Michael DeVine, Nicholas
Blake, Griffith Davis, and Fr. William Woods.   The case of CIA paid asset
Col. Julio Alpirez is also included.  The State Department did not explicitly
search out documents on cases of Guatemalan citizens but did make a
limited number available.  It is likely that there will not be much new and
revealing information found in these documents.

Other agencies, outside of the State Department, including the CIA and the
Department of Defense, are expected to declassify some documents only
after the completion of the Intelligence Oversight Board's investigation of
the Bamaca and DeVine cases, which is now estimated to be finalized at the
end of June.  The CIA, other intelligence agencies and the Department of
Defense would be more likely to know the deeper secrets such as, for
example, whether U.S. paid assets were involved in human rights abuses.  

You might want to write to the White House to:

     congratulate the State Department for releasing these documents but
     to ask the administration to ensure that the CIA and other intelligence
     agencies and the Defense Department declassify documents as fully
     as possible. 

     In addition, urge the administration to release to the public the full
     text of the Intelligence Oversight Board's report on Guatemala when
     it is completed in the near future.  President Clinton, 1600
     Pennsylvania Avenue NW, Washington DC 20500.

            Declassification on Honduras

On Honduras, the administration has also just begun the declassification
process.  The first significant papers just released were State Department
documents on the case of Father James Carney, an American priest who was
killed in Honduras in 1983.  An initial review of the 587 pages of documents,
unfortunately, reveals little new information about Father Carney's death.  

In regards to Honduras, as with Guatemala, the State Department should be
applauded for its response in declassification.  However, this is only a first
step.  The Carney case is but one small part of the Honduran Human Rights
Commissioner's original declassification request.  Other information is being
awaited from the State Department. 

You can access this hotline on peacenet at carnet.congress.  Thank you
for calling the Latin America Working Group hotline
.
