<pre>
So: U-lam
From: lawg@igc.apc.org
Newsgroups: carnet.congres
Subject: INITIAL THOUGHTS ON THE IOB REPORT
Date: 01 Jul 1996 07:00:16 -0800 (PST)

Latin America Legislative Hotline, 1 July 1996


On Friday, June 28, the President's advisory Intelligence Oversight Board released the public
version of its report on Guatemala, fruits of a more than year-long investigation.  Some U.S.
government documents were declassified at the same time, adding to the State Department
documents declassified in May.  The following are some first thoughts on the implications of this
report.     The public report in its entirety may be found on the home page of the Center for
International Policy.

Some initial thoughts on the Intelligence Oversight Board report on Guatemala

This does not evaluate the IOB's treatment of specific cases, which is being looked at carefully by
victims and relatives.  Nor does it assess the documents just declassified, which we have yet to
review.    These are some more general thoughts as we all begin to evaluate the report.

I.   While the Intelligence Oversight Board's report on Guatemala is
disappointing in its inconclusiveness and, especially, its failure to evaluate
appropriately overall U.S. policy in supporting the Guatemalan military and
intelligence services,  there are a number of recognitions and conclusions
within the report that should be emphasized.  These include the following:

A.  CIA assets were credibly alleged to be involved in serious human rights abuses, and the
CIA knew this.

"In the course of our review, we found that several CIA assets were credibly alleged to have
ordered, planned, or participated in serious human rights violations such as assassinations,
extrajudicial execution, torture, or kidnapping while they were assets--and that the CIA's
Directorate of Operations (DO) headquarters was aware at the time of the allegations." (p. 3) 

The asset validation system did not address human rights allegations.  "This validation system,
even if it had been functioning as intended, would not have highlighted human rights issues
because it had been designed to focus almost exclusively upon assets' vulnerability to
counterintelligence and upon dropping non-producing assets from the payroll."

Only in September 1994 did the CIA conduct a review of its assets throughout Latin America to
determine if any may have violated human rights.  We have no way of knowing how thorough this
review was.  Only in February 1996, "largely as a result of the inquiries related to Guatemala," (p.
4), did the CIA issue guidance for dealing with serious human rights violations or crimes of
violence by assets and liaison services.

B.  The CIA failed to inform relevant administration officials and Congress:

"Although National Security Council officials and State Department officials at the embassy and
in Washington were generally aware of the CIA's activities and liaison relationships in Guatemala,
the CIA did not inform these officials until the end of 1994 and early 1995 that any of its assets or
contacts were alleged to have committed human rights abuses.  These policy officials were thus
denied information relevant to their decision-making and lost any opportunity to express possible
concerns that such asset relationships undermined US policy on human rights." (p. 25)

"The IOB found the CIA's performance in notifying Congress to have been inadequate. 
Specifically, the IOB concluded that the CIA leadership violated its statutory obligation to keep
the Congressional oversight committees  fully and currently informed' under Section 413 of Title
50 of the US Code.  Though this statute is not criminal and the standard is too broad to be
fulfilled to the letter, CIA officers, particularly senior leaders at CIA headquarters, were derelict in
failing to provide information they should have provided under even the narrowest reading of the
statute."  (p. 26) The IOB credits this failure to inform Congress to the absence of a systematic
notification process and inadequate emphasis on the part of CIA leadership.

C.  The CIA station in Guatemala was not a rogue station.  

The IOB determined that the CIA station was not a rogue station, rather, "it generally kept the
DO headquarters well-informed of developments, negative or otherwise, including allegations
implicating CIA assets as each allegation surfaced."  (p. 4)  Therefore, the CIA station's actions
within Guatemala can be viewed as approved CIA policy and CIA policy judged accordingly.

D.  US policymakers knew of the "unsavory reputation" of the Guatemalan intelligence
service D-2 and the Department of Presidential Security (known as the "Archivos"), and
also knew of the CIA's liaison with these services.

Not only was the Guatemala station not a rogue station, but the CIA was not a rogue agency. 
This liaison relationship with institutions that systematically violated human rights was known by
US policy makers and should be judged as part of US policy.  

E.  The funds the CIA provided to the Guatemalan liaison services were vital to the D-2
and Archivos.  Relevant US policymakers knew that such funding flowed.

"The funds the CIA provided to the Guatemalan liaison services were vital to the D-2 and
Archivos.  This funding was seen as necessary to make these services more capable partners with
the station, particularly in pursuing anti-communist and counternarcotics objectives.  The CIA,
with the knowledge of ambassadors and other State Department and National Security Council
officials, as well as the Congress, continued this aid after the termination of overt military
assistance in 1990." (p. 20)

This is one of the most significant revelations within the IOB report, although it simply reconfirms
publicly what has been long known.  Despite knowing of the Archivos' and D-2's reputations, and
without acknowledging it to the U.S. public, the State Department and the U.S. Congress allowed
funding to the D-2 and (presumably) Archivos, not simply to pay assets to provide information,
but specifically to strengthen these services' capacity.    The IOB does not make the connection
regarding what effect such support would have on US policy goals to promote human rights and
democracy.   Nor is there discussion of the dilemmas of counternarcotics efforts done in
conjunction with a military some of whose members were/are involved in drug trafficking.

Unclear exactly who in Congress was informed of what; was it just the intelligence committees?

In the meantime, the U.S. public was simply informed that U.S. military aid had halted in 1990.

F.  The CIA consistently underemphasized human rights abuses by the Guatemalan
military and endeavored to put a positive spin in its human rights reports to Congress.

From 1989 to 1994, the CIA was required to provide semi-annual reports to Congress on how
programs in Guatemala had been used "to further the objective of greater respect for human rights
and what specific action will be taken in the ensuing period to further that objective."  The CIA's
reports "did not include information in the possession of the CIA concerning significant
allegations of human rights abuses by the D-2 and Archivos.  The omission of some of this
information in reports that repeatedly referred to the security services' roles in protecting human
rights painted an incomplete picture of the Guatemalan security services." (p. 31)

In briefings of congressional oversight committees, CIA briefers also failed to provide some
clearly relevant information.

G.  The IOB investigation turned up evidence, which was notified to Congress (but not to
the public), that the Department of Defense had found that the School of the Americas and
Southern Command used instructional materials in training Latin American officers,
including Guatemalans, from 1982-91, that appeared to condone practices such as
executions of guerrillas, extortion, physical abuse, coercion, and false imprisonment (p. 32).

This is a very significant finding.  These instructional materials were used throughout nearly the
entire Reagan and Bush administrations, only being replaced towards the very end of the Bush
Administration.  Moreover, these training materials were used considerably after the scandal
created by the  similar "CIA training manual for the contras" which was discovered and publicized
in the mid-80s and stirred considerable public outrage.

This adds one more argument to the case to close the School of the Americas.  Proponents of the
School deny anything unsavory has been taught at the school and discount graduates who commit
human rights abuses as "a few bad apples."  

H.  Cold War attitudes prevailed among CIA officers dealing with Guatemala, despite the
ending of the Cold War.

"The end of the Cold War gradually led to lower funding levels for the station, but had only a
limited effect upon the mechanics of how the CIA carried out its business and upon the mind-set
of the CIA officers dealing with Guatemala.  Station officers continued to view the communist
insurgents--who seemed to threaten a more democratic government--as the primary enemy, and
they viewed the Guatemalan government and security services as partners in the fight against this
common foe and against new threats such as narcotics and illegal alien smuggling." (p. 20)

I.  The CIA station and U.S. embassy in Guatemala requested assistance from the D-2,
because it was perceived as the most "elite" element of the Guatemalan military and
government.

"Because the D-2 was widely considered to be the elite within the Guatemalan military and
government, the station also often requested and received administrative and logistical assistance
from the D-2 on behalf of the embassy."  (p. 20)  The IOB quotes this approvingly as having
helped U.S. goals in combating narcotics, combating communist insurgents and rescuing an
American girl kidnapped in 1994.  However, we have to strongly question what the effect such
apparently direct appeals to one of the worst units of the Guatemalan military by U.S. officials
would have on the enormous problem of lack of civilian control over the Guatemalan military.

J.  Intelligence regarding cases was inadequately shared with families and victims.

"The Freedom of Information Act establishes the only legal requirement to provide such
information, yet that process is often an unsatisfactory way through which to communicate the
information to the families and victims."   (p. 8)  The IOB found that the administration should
provide families and victims with assessments of the reliability of the intelligence reports on their
cases, and should provide more information than it has in the past, whenever possible.  The IOB
identified a number of cases where intelligence reports with relevant information were not shared
with victims or families, or were shared only after much delay.  For example, despite Jennifer
Harbury's repeated requests since early 1993, the State Department did not request a search of
past intelligence on the case until October 1994.  In the Blake case, the National Security Agency
made an inadequate search of its database and provided the family with only 6 of 22 documents
available.


II.  In a number of areas, the Intelligence Oversight Board, in part responding to
its limited mandate, did not provide a sufficiently in-depth and independent
analysis.  These would include the following:

A.  Most significantly, the IOB report accepts at face value the US relationship with the
Guatemalan military and intelligence services.

The IOB discounts any inconsistency between the US goals to promote human rights and
democracy and the United States' close association with the Guatemalan military and funding of
the Guatemalan intelligence services.  The report simply echoes stated US policy goals, declares
that these were successful and declares that any negative aspect of association with the
Guatemalan intelligence services were outweighed by the positive benefits of intelligence received. 
However, we are given absolutely no indication of how the IOB arrived at these conclusions or
indeed if it made any systematic evaluation of US policy goals at all.

This is the real story.  Not who told who what when, but why the US government should be
associated with and funding Guatemalan institutions deeply implicated in gross human rights
violations.  What possible motives could justify this association?  

To those interested in exploring this association, this report, and very likely some of  the
declassified documents that accompany it, offer interesting and disturbing reading.

B.  The IOB report offers extremely inconclusive evidence on most cases.

The lack of conclusiveness on so many cases brings up several questions.  Did the IOB not have
access to all available evidence?  If it did have access to all available evidence, then clearly, not
only are our intelligence agencies "not all-knowing," but they did not seem very informed at all on
many important issues.   What was the point of such extensive paid assets if they could not
provide information about cases involving US citizens?  

The complete lack of information on Dianna Ortiz's case, pending the Justice Department's
investigation, is disappointing, as is the IOB's lack of information on the man with a US accent
that she identified as being present at her torture.

C.  The IOB report presents very limited recommendations.

The IOB recommendations are perhaps its weakest point, calling for fairly minor changes in CIA
guidance and State Department-CIA agreements; some of these changes have already been made
by the new CIA director.

The reliance on guidance and other non-legislative measures seems ingenuous, given the contents
of the report.  The Board recommends only that the CIA issue clear guidance on the recruitment
and retention of assets with human rights or criminal allegations..  Most of the other
recommendations also involve changes in guidance and procedures, rather than changes in
legislation.  Yet the report itself judges the CIA less severely because it is only following guidance
or regulations.  CIA officials cannot be held criminally liable for any of the dubious actions within
the report precisely because there is at best guidance, not legislation.  Moreover, the report itself
details how the CIA interpreted guidance and regulations in the most flexible way possible.   The
implications of the report, and the Oversight Board's relatively gentle treatment of the CIA, is
that legislation is essential to begin to hold the CIA and other agencies accountable to human
rights standards.

  One additional point:

 What we have learned to date from the IOB report and declassified documents, while
incomplete, still has advanced our knowledge of US policy and victims' fates.   We welcome
the Clinton Administration's efforts, even if limited and belated, to make information
public.     Yet none of this would have been possible without public and congressional
pressure.  The limited truth that comes to us today is due to the bravery and persistence of
victims and survivors like Dianna Ortiz and Jennifer Harbury and other members of
Coalition Missing; to the support they found among concerned members of the U.S. public;
to persistent advocates within Congress, such as Rep. John Porter, Rep. Constance
Morella, Senator Christopher Dodd and Rep. Robert Torricelli; and to the investigative
journalists who began to push the story farther.  Ongoing public and journalistic interest
will help us learn the truth.

For more information, contact: Lisa Haugaard, (202) 546-7010.


.
