So: U-lam
From: ncoord@igc.apc.org
Newsgroups: carnet.general
Subject: Guatemala Accompaniment Project Pos
Date: 05 Jul 1996 12:12:40

BEGIN -- Cut Here -- cut here
                      POSITION OPENING
                                    
                 GUATEMALA COORDINATOR

for the Guatemala Accompaniment Project of
NCOORD


Starting date: Sept 15 - October 1, 1996


The National Coordinating Office on Refugees and
Displaced of Guatemala (NCOORD),  is
seeking a qualified person, or couple, to work in
Guatemala as the coordinator(s) of the
Guatemala Accompaniment Project (G.A.P.). The
office is located in central Guatemala City, one
block from the national palace. Work is primarily in
the capital, but requires frequent travel to
rural communities.

The Guatemala Accompaniment Project currently
has six U.S. accompaniers living in Guatemalan
communities of refugees who have recently returned
to their country after over a decade of exile
in Mexico. Each accompanier is sponsored by a local
community in the U.S. and acts as a link
between that community and the Guatemalan
community.  G.A.P. is continuing to grow in
response to the increasing number of Guatemalan
refugee and displaced communities seeking
accompaniers.


JOB DUTIES INCLUDE:

Orientation of and travel with accompaniers to
Guatemalan communities;  on-going support of
and coordination for accompaniers in-country; 
facilitation of communication between
accompaniers and their sponsoring communities in
the U.S.;  acting as resource for accompaniers
as they establish work plans in the communities.

Facilitation of bi-monthly meetings of all
accompaniers in country;  maintain relationships
with G.A.P. regional coordinators in the support,
oversight, and evaluation of accompaniers.

Communication and coordination with the U.S.
office of NCOORD.

Contact with on-governmental and governmental
offices to gather information and facilitate the
accompaniment work.

Write reports and updates on the communities and
on G.A.P. work.

Give counsel on and channel material aid requests
from the Guatemalan communities to U.S.
funding sources; disburse funds appropriated.

                                 (over)

 

QUALIFICATIONS INCLUDE: 

Fluency in Spanish
Latin America, and preferably Guatemala,
experience
Experience working with group dynamics and
development of teamwork 
Ability to communicate well orally and in writing,
facilitate conflict resolution, and to take
initiative
Basic computer skills
Minimum one year commitment


BENEFITS:

Monthly stipend and health insurance
Yearly round trip ticket to U.S.


INTERESTED APPLICANTS:

Send a letter of interest, resume, and three
references to NCOORD

National Coordinating Office On Refugees and
Displaced of Guatemala (NCOORD)
59 E. Van Buren St., Suite 1400;   Chicago, IL
60605   U.S.A.
Tel: (312) 360-1705      Fax: (312) 939-3272     
email: ncoord@igc.apc.orgEND -- Cut Here -- cut here
.
