<pre>
So: U-lam
From: pbiusa@igc.apc.org
Newsgroups: dh.centroam
Subject: Central America Project Report 6/96
Date: 24 Jun 1996 13:27:31

From: "PBI USA"  pbiusa@igc.apc.org 

*** PEACE BRIGADES INTERNATIONAL ***
CENTRAL AMERICA PROJECT (GUATEMALA) 6/96 REPORT

As was foreseen, the Accord on Socioeconomic Aspects
and the Agrarian Situation was signed on May 6 in
Mexico City, leaving both negotiating parties, as well
as the international community, satisfied.=20

The 39 page document establishes a set of minimal and
basic reforms designed to instill long term changes in
the direction of State Modernisation.  The Accord
revolves around five main points: Democracy and
Participatory Development, Social Development, the
Agrarian Situation and Rural Development,
Modernisation of Public Policy and Fiscal Management,
and Final Arrangements.=20

The Agrarian Situation has provided a focal point in
the negotiation, being one of the main causes of the
escalation of armed conflict and one of the central
themes in Guatemalan politics today.  Amongst the
commitments agreed to by the government, of special
interest is the creation of a land bank which will
begin operation in 1997, as well as the promotion and
publication of a law which monitors the functioning of
it.=20

In 1999, the government will evaluate the functioning


of the project and compare it with its objectives.=20
Another promise was the development of a national land
registration project, in which the government promises
to initiate a survey of land distribution information,
starting in January of 1997.  In the finance
department, one of the more positive points was the
provision of legal reinforcement mechanisms to avoid
tax evasion, which, it is assumed will normalize the
fiscal debt (Inforpress, 9.5.96).  =20

As the penultimate accord of the substantive agenda
was signed, the National Revolutionary Union of
Guatemala (URNG) announced the immediate suspension of
the forced collection of the "war tax" from landowners
and business owners.  An investigation initiated by
the Ombuds Office for Human Rights (PDH) revealed the
existence of evidence proving that the "war tax"
collected by the URNG continues to be demanded in
various plantations in Santa Rosa and Jutiapa.=20

It is still to be determined if they are truly being
carried out by members of the insurgency.  The
president of the governmental Peace Commission
(COPAZ), Gustavo Porras, after contemplating the
situation, declared that those carrying out the
collection of this tax are not in fact members of the
URNG (La Republica, 21.5.96).  =20
Different Sectors, Distinct Reactions  =20

The Assembly of Civil Society, one of the sectors most
directly involved in the negotiation process,
requested the integration of a High Level Commission
to study what was signed.  An even more critical
viewpoint was offered by the National Coordination of
Campesino Organisations (CNOC), which brings together
various organisations which are struggling to obtain
land titles, including CONIC and CUC. =20

While valuing the accord because it provides
possibilities "to resolve in an integral way the
problematic of campesinos", CNOC established that "the
accord is incomplete and insufficient with regards to
concrete mechanisms to resolve land conflicts".  =20

In contrast to the critics, the satisfaction of the
business sector was evident as they were one of the
first to applaud the accord.  The Coordinating
Commission of Agricultural, Commercial, Industrial and
Finance Associations (CACIF) expressed their complete
backing of the accord and made an international call
to all businesses to continue investing in Guatemala.=20
Humberto Pretti, president of CACIF, highlighted the
planning of a national land registration project and
the development of a land bank, claiming that it will
legitimize property owners (Inforpress, 16.5.96).=20

Various political analysts agree that the accord,
deemed a strategic step in the negotiating process,
builds on elements which are already integral parts of
the constitution and the legal framework of the
country, and what it hopes to achieve is "to be not
only an announcement of good intentions but move on to
become the legal base of the capital development of
Guatemala" (El Grafico, 8.6.96).=20

In reality, as many sectors have pointed out, the
accord is based on good intentions, and opens more
political space for the URNG to insert itself into the
political and legal framework of the country.=20
Guerrilla Comandante Gaspar Ilom confirms this when he
says that he is working on "a transition from armed
struggle", adding that the URNG is looking to conform
into a national political project which will transcend
the peace negotiations (Inforpress, 16.5.96).  =20

On May 12th, the Guatemalan daily, Siglo Veintiuno,
reported that Luis Becker, Francisco Villagran, Luz
Mendez and possibly Pedro Palma Lau all retired from
the political-diplomatic team of the URNG, virtually
dissolving the advisor team to the URNG.  The general
command of the URNG have not confirmed nor denied this
information.  The reason for the retirement, according
to the paper, was their discontentment with the way
that the Socioeconomic and Agrarian Reforms were
negotiated.=20

The team leaves the URNG with only one more
substantive theme in the negotiations; Strengthening
Civil Power and the Role of the Army in a Democratic
Society.  =20

Special Delivery from the US: Conflictive Documents =20


During the month of May, Guatemala received more than
6,305 documents which were declassified by the U.S.
State Department regarding human rights violations
against United States citizens during the period
between 1984 and 1995.  The documentation contains
important information regarding, among others cases,
the assassination of United States citizen Michael
Devine by a military patrol in Guatemala's northern
department of El Peten; the kidnapping and subsequent
torture in 1989 of Ursulin nun Diana Ortiz, and the
capture and subsequent assassination of guerrilla
commander Efrain Bamaca.  =20

Of the information contained in the U.S. State
Department files, 8 per cent was not revealed to the
Guatemalan government, including information regarding
CIA involvement in Guatemala, claiming "security
reasons".  For more than forty years, the CIA has been
accused of having strong ties with repressive agents
of the Guatemalan state, which calls into question the
effectiveness of the documentation which has been
sent.=20

According to The New York Times, "documents which were
declassified could help in determining those
responsible for assassinations in Guatemala,
specifically that of guerrilla leader Efrain Bamaca,
known as Comandante Everaldo and that of North
American citizen Michael Devine."  According to the
well-respected daily newspaper, a member of the
Clinton Administration who was not in agreement with
the manner in which the case was handled by the US
government reported that "the Guatemalan Colonel and
CIA agent Roberto Alpirez is responsible for the
Bamaca and Devine assassinations" (Inforpress,
16.5.96).  =20

Upon their arrival to Guatemala, the documents were
brought to the Supreme Court of Justice, which,
corresponding to the penal legislation in effect, had
it sent to the Public Prosecutor's Office, which is in
charge of managing investigations of this sort.=20
The Office refused to open the documents, claiming
they were sent against legal norms (Prensa Libre,
16.5.96).  According to Ronalth Ochaeta, director of
the Archbishop's Human Rights Office (ODHA), the
Public Prosecutor's Office has demonstrated a lack of
goodwill and efficiency in investigating important
cases which extend to different State organisms and
could "burn their hands" with information which could
be very implicating (Prensa Libre, 21.5.96).  =20

Solidarity Tax and Anti-Strike Law  =20

With a majority of National Advance Party (PAN)
deputies and the opposition of the remaining political
parties, Congress approved the establishment of the
Extraordinary and Temporary Solidarity Tax which,
according to government forces, will permit the
strengthening of State structures, diminish the
internal debt and support the political economy in
1996 and 1997.=20

This tax affects all citizens who receive a net annual
income greater than 48,000 quetzales and, according to
the Centre for National Economic Investigations, the
determination of the tax paid on last year's declared
net income penalizes those who have declared their
incomes and paid their taxes, while it will be more
difficult to oblige those who still have not declared
to contribute the extraordinary tax (Siglo Veintiuno,
16.5.96).  =20

At the end of the month, Congress undertook a second
reading of the conflictive reforms to the State
Worker's Strike Regulation and Labour Law.  Part of
the objective of the reforms are to prohibit the right
to strike for a number of health, public sector and
social service workers.  It also aims to restrict
strikes in sectors providing such vital services as
water, transportation, electricity and other
combustibles, and other cases which gravely affect the
national economy and put the health of the population
at risk.=20

The reforms are based in the fact that State Workers
have not respected the Constitution when they have
paralysed essential services such as hospitals and
recently, the justice system.     Since the potential
reform was presented in Congress by a PAN
representative, it has provoked strong opposition on
the part of the majority of labour organisations, as
well as the parliamentary minorities.  During the
beginning of the discussion on this point, PAN
representatives prohibited the entrance of worker
representatives.=20

Representatives then entered by force in to the
Congress Chamber and a confrontation between these
representatives and the National Police or elements of
the Army was anticipated.  In spite of this tension,
the 43 representative PAN block approved the reforms
after almost 11 hours of debate in which the
opposition used all the parliamentary technicalities
possible to impede the reforms from being passed
(Siglo Veintiuno, 24.5.96).  =20

Representatives of the opposition declared the
Guatemalan constitution had been violated with the
military presence in the Legislative Palace and that
the presence constituted a violation of the official
duties of the Executive (Prensa Libre, 24.5.96).  They
expressed their outrage at the fact that it was the
president of the Republic, Alvaro Arz=A3 Irigoyen who
ordered the entrance of the military contingent into
Congress (La Republica, 29.5.96).  =20

TEAMWORK IN THE CAPITAL  =20

We continued with our regular visits and periodic
presences in the offices of popular organisations and
human rights groups in the capital.  We continued to
accompany the workers of the INEXPORT factory, who
continued their presence and labour struggle outside
the illegally closed factory - whose owners refuse to
pay their delayed salaries, and are now threatening to
remove all the machinery from the factory.=20

We also continued to accompany the Association of
Sellers of the Informal Economy in Zone 1 due to the
threats which they have refused for organising. =20

We have maintained a presence with Debora Guzman,
trade union worker form the MJ Modas factory and her
companion Felix Gonzalez  from Amatitl n.  =20

We began daily accompaniment to Blanca Rosa Ayala
Gutierrez, director of the Mirador II settlement in
the capital and leader from the Association of
Squatter Settlements of Guatemala.  Blanca Rosa
suffered an attempted assassination in which she was
shot three times and seriously injured, and is
currently recuperating in a hospital in the capital.=20
 =20

On the streets of the capital  =20
We recently accompanied a march organized by CONAVIGUA
to mark the International Day of Conscientious
Objection and demand the end to militarisation and
forced recruitment.=20

In conjunction with the political revindications
around labour issues, the month has contained a number
of accompaniments of various demonstrations organized
by UASP and other labour organizations which have
taken to the streets to reclaim their right to strike
before the recent approval to the reforms of the
Labour Law Regarding State Worker's Right to Strike.=20
 =20

We also carried out an orientation for the newly
arrived accompaniers from the Spanish Accompaniment
Organisation, Intermon, and saw them off with a dinner
as they left for the community of Aurora 8 of October
in Xaman, Chisec, Alta Verapaz.   =20

We met with Rosalina Tuyuc, director of the National
Coordinating Committee of Guatemalan Widows
(CONAVIGUA) and representative of the FDNG in
Congress.  We gratefully received Monse=A4or Julio
Cabrera, Bishop of the Diocese of Quiche, for an
enjoyable dinner in our home.  =20

IN THE INTERIOR  =20

Izabal: We returned to the communities of Rubelhu and
Rubelpec, in the township of El Estor, who continue to
receive threats and be pressured for their continued
struggle to reclaim their rights.  We also interviewed
Father Daniel Vogt, of the San Pedro Apostal parish,
who has been actively supportive of the communities.=20
=20

Suchitepequez: We travelled to Mazatenango to visit
the director of Radio Victoria, Carlos Orellana, who
was the victim of an assassination attempt when a bomb
exploded in his home.  We also met with the Assistant
in the Regional Ombuds Office for Human Rights (PDH).=20
=20

San Marcos: We again accompanied the lawyers from the
Human Rights Office and Pastoral Team on Land,
conducted appointments with members of the MINUGUA
regional office and the PDH and met with the Union of
State and Popular Sector Workers (UTESP) in the
neighbouring city of San Pedro Sacatepequez.   =20

Quiche: We accompanied the lawyers of CERJ in their
legal work which they continue in Santa Cruz.  In
particular, we accompanied them to a legal function of
"reconstruction of facts" which was carried out in San
Pedro Jocopilas, in an attempt to clarify the details
of an assassinated youth in july of last year.=20
Autodefense patrols as well as an ex-military
commissioner were alleged to be involved.  We also
accompanied members of CONIC on a visit to Lemoa in
Quiche.    =20

AN INTERVIEW WITH ALFONSO BAUER PAIZ:=20
"I HOPE THE POPULAR FORCES CAN REMAIN UNITED"  =20

Born in 1918, one of the activists who fought against
the dictatorship of Ubico, revolutionary of 1944,
holding public positions within the Arevalo and Arbenz
presidencies, twice exiled, and most recently an
esteemed legal advisor of the Guatemalan refugees in
Mexico and the displaced population in general,
Alfonso Bauer Paiz is one of the most well known
political personalities in Guatemala.  =20

>From an historical perspective, a history which you
have personally experienced, what is the greatest
possible advantage offered in the Socio-economic
accord (the most recent accord signed between the
government and the Guatemalan National Revolutionary
Unity (URNG) in May of this year) and what is its most
serious disadvantage?=20

The accord did not manage to fulfil the yearnings of
the Guatemalan people, in particular the peasant and
working class. =20

It is positive and legally important that in many of
the precepts of the accord the government acquired
commitments that are tied not only to the current
administration and executive, but to an agent of the
state.  Unfortunately, there is no guarantee that the
Congress of the Republic or the Supreme Court of
justice will uphold the accords.  Due to the political
instability of our country it can't be known whether
or not future governments will maintain the
commitments acquired by this administration.=20

However, the latest obligations agreed to by his
government have  consist in the realization of a
series of actions that take in to account the social
needs of the people.  This is the most significant,
and in these commitments one finds some resistance to
the current trends of globalization of the economy and
of neoliberalism.  =20

Now, as for the problematic land issue, the popular
sectors have the impression that very little was
gained.  There are no concrete commitments that attack
the problem of uneven land ownership.  Everything is
made to depend on a land survey that could possibly
take four years to be realized.  Certainly the land
survey could produce valuable information regarding
idle lands, but it will also show that the most
powerful land owners will have their holdings
inscribed in the registry.  And the form in which the
article in the constitution regarding private property
explains land as "inherent to the human personality"
will make expropriations legally difficult. =20

However, one positive note is the mention of a
revision of judgement of the Transversal Fringe of the
North and the Peten.   These lands could be
effectively put to use by awarding them to the peasant
class that have no land.  =20

Finally, I would say that its not possible to
undertake a strong campaign against the accords,
considering the as yet untouched power of the large
land holding class and entrepreneurs organized in the
Coordinating Committee of Agricultural, Commercial,
Industrial and Financial Sectors (CACIF).  There are
some people that would be pleased to see the popular
sectors totally discredit the government and the URNG.=20


The accord should be taken as a first step that
permits a revision of the actual agrarian situation.=20
But something positive will come out of it only if the
peasant population organizes itself, avoiding
divisions and fractures, and struggles in solidarity
with other sectors of the population, such as the
working class, the groups that form the petty
bourgeoisie, intellectuals and professionals to
reclaim its rights.  =20

In the process of the return of Guatemalan refugees,
especially in Mexico, and the resettlement of the
displaced populations in general, there seem to be
many obstacles.  What, essentially, is the problem,
and what possible solutions are there?  =20

In part these obstacles exist because, unfortunately,
there are divisions among the organizations that
represent the refugees, that is, the Permanent
Commission of Guatemalan Refugees in Mexico (CCPP).=20

The accord dealing with the resettlement of the
populations displaced by the internal conflict, signed
on June 27th of 1994, has not been adhered to, with
the exception of the Technical Commission which is in
charge of the diagnostics and profiles of the
projects. =20
The displaced populations - refugees and the
internally displaced - established the Consultative
Assembly of Displaced Populations (ACPD) in September
of 1994, formed by the CCPP, the Communities of
Populations in Resistance (CPR), the National Council
for Displaced Guatemalans (CONDEG), the National
Coordinating Body of Guatemalan Widows (CONAVIGUA),
the Group of Mutual Support for Families of
Disappeared and Detained Persons (GAM), refugees that
have returned from Honduras to Alpemech and refugees
in the USA associated with Atanasio Tzul and the
women's organizations Mama Maquin, Ixmucan=82 and Madre
Tierra (Mother Earth).=20

Regrettably the Northwestern Section of the CCPP as
well as the Southern Section do not attend the
meetings of the ACPD.  These two sections had been
negotiating revisions of the credit arrangement with
the government along side the Northern Section, but
new social realities have arisen, such as in the case
of some refugees in Mexico, members of the
Northwestern Section of the CCPP, who no longer feel
represented by the CCPP, therefore they organized
themselves in a new group called the Coordination of
Blocks for Return and Resettlement of Refugees (CBRR).


Additionaly, the Guatemalan Association of Dispersed
Refugees (ARDIGUA) has existed for several years, but
has been only  partially recognized by the Mexican
Commission for Refuge Aid (COMAR) and the United
Nations High Commission on Refugees (UNHCR) even
though there is no doubt that they are refugees.  So,
the authorities of the UNHCR and the National Peace
Fund (FONAPAZ) were exacting pressure so that the
Permanent Commission would endorse ARDIGUA.   =20

On the 24th and 25th of May the ACPD met with the
National Commission for Returnees, Refugees and
Displaced People (CEAR) and FONAPAZ in a "locked door
marathon meeting".  The meeting dealt with the problem
of the legal regulation of credits and the application
of the accords signed on the 8th of October, 1992;
that they should protect the refugees in Mexico,
whether or not they be organized with the CCPP.  The
ACPD emphatically communicated to the government that
they would have no objection to the government
continuing its negotiations with the Northwestern and
Southern Sections of the CCPP.=20

However, they also demanded that the government
negotiate with the ACPD to revise the provisions
regarding credits and the application of the October
accords with the Northern Section of the Permanent
Commission, ARDIGUA, and the CBRR.  To deal with this
problem and all problems of the internally displaced
populations, a permanent table of dialogue was created
under the coordination of a high level functionary of
the government and a representative of the ACPD.  This
is a very notable development.  In the end the ACPD
was left feeling very grateful for the attitude of the
authorities of CEAR and FONAPAZ.=20

They reiterated their proposal and accepted our
proposals with some modifications that we found
reasonable.  With this one can be quite optimistic
that the dialogue will facilitate a solution to the
problems.  =20

On the first day of May of this year the existence of
a new political group, was made known publicly.=20
Calling itself the "Democratic Alternative of the
People" (ADP), it mentioned your name, referring to
you as one of the founders...  =20

I do belong to an organization called the "Popular
Action Group" (GAP).  This group is made up of
politicians from various sectors, unitarians,
pluralists and politicians of the left, yes, but with
criteria sufficiently broad in nature so as to promote
in our country the uniting of all the forces of the
left and popular democratic forces, including
representatives of the economic sector who understand
the need for certain transformations and changes.  The
GAP participated along with other sectors in the
creation of the Democratic Front for a New Guatemala
(FDNG).=20

Other organizations such as those in the Indigenous
sector and the union movement also participated.=20
There had been a decision made by consensus which
proposed the following individuals as possible
presidential candidates for the FDNG: Oscar Clemente
Marroquin Godoy, Gert Rosenthal, Alfonso Fuente Soria,
Dr. Argueta Figueroa y Alfonso Bauer Paiz.  However,
it turned it out that on a given day, a fax arrived
from Mexico City, saying that the economist Jorge
Gonzalez del Valle was accepting the nomination as the
presidential candidate.  A nomination that had not
even been discussed here in Guatemala, not even once!=20

It was then that I understood that this came from
outside decisions, and I understood that there had
already been a specific (political) line, and I
resigned.  The GAP supported my decision, advising me
at no time do we want to cause divisions among the
FDNG.=20

We were a fundamental factor in its creation and we
remain committed to the FDNG in a moral way.  We did
not want to participate in the electoral event, but we
announced that if the moment arrives to revise the
Constitution of the Republic, yes we'll be there in
the struggle to elect deputies to the Constituent
Assembly.  This Assembly should demand new norms for
the true establishment of a democracy that is
pluralist, participatory and socially just.   =20

As far as my participation in the ADP I can only tell
you that this is absolutely false.  The day after the
notice was published in the Prensa Libre, Factor
Mendez and I sent a statement of explanation in which
we said that we are members of the GAP, that we
support the FDNG and declare our participation for
reasons that deal with hegemonic and hierarchical
attitudes that had been (present), but that we
continue struggling so that the Democratic Front might
strengthen the unity of the popular forces.  In no way
do we want to be divisive.  For us, despite its
limitations, the Democratic Front is the only popular
(political) expression. =20

The mention of our names was done with absolutely no
consultation and it is painful that the Prensa Libre
has not published the clarification.  =20

What is your vision of the political panorama in
Guatemala between the signing of the peace and the
year 2,000?   =20

It is very restless.  I am not a pessimistic fatalist,
in some way I have maintain a fairly utopian outlook
since my adolescence and youth, utopian in the sense
of Tomas Moro in the Middle Ages, and of Che Guevara
in recent times.  But given the concrete realities,
and the prospects that lie between now and the year
2000, I fear that upon signing the peace accords, the
organizations that form the URNG, might constitute a
volatile group, and that a reoccurrence of what
happened in El Salvador and in Nicaragua with the FMLN
and the Sandanistas, could result. In [these cases]
the great forces of economic power and the military
remain in tact.  I hope that all of this does not
occur [in Guatemala] and that the popular forces as
well as the political-military forces of the
insurgency maintain their unity.=20



