So: U-az
From: Carmel Budiardjo  tapol@gn.apc.org 
Newsgroups: reg.easttimor
Subject: Why Sub-Commission bid failed
Date: Tue, 28 May 1996 19:15:20 +0100 (BST)

Why Sub-Commission membership bid failed

Jakarta Post, 20 May 1996
Abridged

POOR RECORD SHUTS RI OUT OF UN RIGHTS 
COMMISSION

Indonesia's poor human rights record is one of the main 
reasons why its candidates were not elected to the UN Sub-
Commission on the Prevention of Discrimination and the 
Protection of Minorities, a candidate said.

Human rights campaigner Muladi told JP the country's poor 
human rights protection image was an obstacle to get an 
Indonesian on the Commission.

Last year, Jakarta nominated Charles Himawan to sit on the 
Commission with Muladi as his deputy. In Geneva earlier this 
month, the Indonesian candidates lost out to nominees from 
Japan and South Korea for one of the 16 seats.

Muladi, rector of Diponegoro University, Semarang, said it is 
important for the country to dispel the negative perception by 
working to improve human rights across the country. Apart 
from its notoriety, Jakarta's efforts were further obstructed by 
the international campaign against Indonesia being waged by 
East Timorese separatist leaders such as Ramos Horta.

Despite intensive lobbying by the Foreign Affairs Ministry's 
Director General of General and Political Affairs and 
Indonesia's permanent representative to the UN in Geneva, 
only 20 of the expected 38 supporting votes came in.

He also said the dominant role of the US in such proceedings 
was another negative factor. 'The US was very inflexible 
towards Indonesia,' charged Muladi, who is a member of the 
National Commission for Human Rights and has also sat on 
the UN Committee on  Crime Prevention of Criminal Justice.
.
