So: U-az
From: cnrmnt@pactok.peg.apc.org
Newsgroups: reg.easttimor
Subject: EAST TIMOR: Confessions of A Spy
Date: 28 May 1996 11:22:00

                           EAST TIMOR REPORT:
             an intelligence informant confesses.


                         28 May 1996


The flow of information on the oppressive conditions in East Timor
reaching the outside world has noticeably diminished in the recent
past.   The Indonesian military has taken increased repressive
measures aimed at preventing the world from following the true
situation in the illegally occupied territory. The prominent
international exposure in recent years of the barbaric conduct of the
Indonesian military in East Timor and Indonesia itself, has seriously
damaged the positive image the Suharto regime and its foreign
backers have tried to cultivate for so long. World wide attention on
East Timor has exposed the brutal nature of the Indonesian
occupation, the criminal character of the regime's military and its
corrupt and inefficient public administration.

After some blows in recent months, the East Timorese
Resistance information network is reorganising itself and
succeeding again in providing information to the outside world on
the worsening conditions in the oppressed territory.

The following  report on the confessions of a young East Timorese
spy has been just received. This case story is typical of the
experiences many young East Timorese, intimidated and coerced
to report on their fellows by the large numbers of
Indonesian military intelligence operatives stationed in the territory.

Through these pressures on the territory's youth to spy on their
people and report to the occupying forces, a very pernicious
climate of fear and division is maintained in East Timor, which
further exacerbates the sufferings of this traumatised society.


              I WAS FORCED TO SPY ON THE CHURCH

 (statement by Carlos da Conceicao(*), 20 years, of Baguia, East
                           Timor).

This  bright faced young man was among those attending the
inauguration ceremony of the Salesian Sisters convent in Laga
parish, on the evening of 29 April 96.  Rather than returning that
evening to his home village in Baguia, he stayed behind to monitor
the several hundred parishioners from the surrounding regions that
could not make it home and had to stay in Laga overnight.

The next day, on his way to Baguia he stopped at the village of
Lavateri, looking for the leader of the Catholic youth. Because the
people knew the visitor to be an Indonesian spy, they avoided
giving him the information he desired. Instead, some youngsters
chased him away. He was detained by other youths some 2
kilometres away, and brought back to Lavateri. On 1 May, the  local
Priest of Laga, Father Joao de Deus Pires,  came to see Carlos da
Conceicao, and seek information from him on his work as a spy for
the Indonesian military intelligence.

In front of the local military commander (Dan Pos) Muh-Arfa, the
Village Head, Deputy Sub-district Head, the Priest, and two Church
employees, Carlos stated that he was forced by the local
military commander to work as a spy. He was ordered to monitor
the activities of the Catholic Church, particularly its youth.  He had
to report the names of all young people participating in Church
activities, monitor the movements of the Catholic school teachers,
and take part in all Church gatherings involving large numbers of
people, reporting on them.  Carlos claimed that he disliked
performing this work, but was forced to do so by the Dan Pos Muh-
Arfa.

Hearing this statement, the embarrassed local military commander
Muh-Arfa claimed  in front of the Priest that he had never ordered
Carlos to work as a spy.  Father Pires replied to Muh-Arfa that he
had not come to judge anyone, but to hear a statement from Carlos
about his activities.  Therefore, the Priest added, Muh-Arfa's
statement was not relevant to him.  Father Pires felt the duty to
report  Carlos' statement to the Bishop, especially considering that
the priest had himself been aware of how he had been constantly
spied upon while performing his pastoral duties.

After a heated discussion, Muh-Arfa finally acknowledged that he
had indeed ordered Carlos to spy for the military.  Father Pires
asked him to avoid continuing to disturb the people of Baguia in
future with terror and intimidation.  The priest then left for Laga
taking Carlos da Conceicao with him, to bring him to the Bishop in
Dili.

At Laga, Carlos admitted to Church workers that he had been
spying for the military since 1990. He had for a long time dreamed
to be able to free himself from the situation he was trapped in, and
was very happy at what had happened that day. He now felt
relieved that it was all in the open.  His only concern was that the
military may try to kill him for exposing them. The Church workers
assured him that he would be protected.

END


(*) True name not used, for security reasons.
.
