So: U-az
From: jinglis@igc.apc.org
Newsgroups: reg.easttimor
Subject: Stop arms transfer!says Japan YWCA
Date: 28 May 1996 07:40:31 -0800 (PST)

Japan YWCA urges Sweden to stop arms export

The National Board of the YWCA of Japan, meeting
in Tokyo from May 25-7, adopted a resolution urging
the Swedish Government to reverse its decision to permit
the sale of naval cannons to Indonesia. 

Reiko Suzuki, Secretary General of the Japan YWCA,
conveyed the resolution in a letter to Foreign Minister
Lena Hjelm Wallen that said, in part,

"In the light of resolution adopted at the YWCA World Council
in July 1995 in Seoul, Korea, with respect to East Timor:

'.Recognizing that the 20-year old Indonesian occupation
and the horrendous systematic violations of human rights 
are in contradiction of the UN International Covenant on
Economic, Social and Cultural Rights,
be it resolved that all national associations mobilize to
advocate for an immediate prohibition on arms sales to
Indonesia, the immediate withdrawal of Indonesia from East Timor,
and the participation of East Timorese leaders in the current UN-sponsored
talks between the Indonesian and Portuguese governments.' 

and, with respect to the Resolution on the Discontinuation of
Munitions Trade which, inter alia,

'(Condemns) the continuation of the conventional munitions 
and chemical weapons trade and calls on all national associations
to work with other relevant organizations to ensure change
in government policies, practices and public opinion so that
this trade be discontinued globally.'

the National Board of the YWCA of Japan urges the Government
of Sweden to:

1) withdraw approval for the sale/export of naval cannons to Indonesia,
2) reaffirm the policy adopted by the Social Democratic Party not to
permit arms sales to Indonesia, and
3) to respect the rights of the East Timorese which have been reaffirmed
in resolutions of the United Nations Security Council and General Assembly
and to make utmost efforts in the diplomatic field to achieve a peaceful
resolution of the East Timor issue."

The letter was presented to the Swedish Embassy in Tokyo.
The YWCA delegation was informed by the counsellor that the Embassy
had received no information on the arms sale to date.
.
