So: U-az
From: fbp@igc.apc.org
Newsgroups: reg.easttimor
Subject: Austral to share radar intelligence
Date: 29 May 1996 07:38:14 -0800 (PST)

From: Foreign Bases Project  fbp@igc.apc.org 


                            AUSTRALIAN NEWS REPORTS
                              Volume 2, number 18

                        Week ending Sunday 26 May 1996

WEDNESDAY 22
____________


1/1     AUSTRALIA TO SHARE RADAR INTELLIGENCE WITH INDONESIA 

THE Australian Defence Force is set to share top secret intelligence
information with Indonesia as part of an effort to establish closer
military ties with Australia's giant norther neighbour.

The armed forces plan to share information from Australia's $1
billion Jindalee over-the-horizon radar network as part of a "joint
surveillence regime" of the air and sea gap between the two
countries. 

The move has been hailed as a significant step on top of last year's
defence cooperation treaty with Indonesia. Australian Defence Force
chief General John Baker said today the proposal had been raised in
talks with senior officers from Indonesia's military, ABRI. "If we
are going to cooperate in surveillence of the area between Australia
and the Indonesia archipelago you can't do it unless you see the
basic information on which your activities are generated," General
Baker said. "I think we will share some of the basic output from
Jindalee in future as we get into cooperative activities." Australia
already engages in joint surveillance with Malaysia using jets from
the RAAF base at Butterworth, near the northern Malaysian city of
Penang. General Baker said today both Australia and Indonesia
experienced problems with pirates, illegal fishers and other illegal
vessels. Meanwhile Prime Minister John Howard is expected to travel
to Jakarta in early August in what will be his first trip overseas as
Prime Minister. Sources said today that Howard was likely to travel
on to Japan after visiting Indonesia and holding talks with President
Suharto. His planned trips follows last month's visit by Foreign
Minister Alexander Downer, last week's trip by Deputy Prime Minister
Tim Fischer and a proposed visit by Defence Minister Ian McLachlan
in mid-June. His predecessor Paul Keating made six trips to Jakarta
in less than four years. 


.
