So: U-az
From: fbp@igc.apc.org
Newsgroups: reg.easttimor
Subject: Suharto: Indonesia never wanted ET
Date: 29 May 1996 07:39:50 -0800 (PST)

From: Foreign Bases Project  fbp@igc.apc.org 


Indonesia no intent to annex E. Timor

    JAKARTA, May 28 (UPI) -- Indonesia President Suharto on Tuesday
said his country has (sic) no intention of annexing the former
Portuguese colony of East Timor. 
    Instead, he told Burkina Faso President Blaise Compoare that 
"Indonesia has entirely no ambition to annex any other region
because our constitution is very clear...independence is the right
of all nations." 
    Indonesia state secretariate Murdiono told reporters that
Suharto also noted that in terms of territory, East Timor is only a
very small region compared to Indonesia's vast territory. 
    "Definitely, there is no logical reason for Indonesia to annex
such a small territory," Murdiono said. "It was the East Timorese
people who expressed their will of their own future to integrate
into Indonesia." 
    Indonesia, the world's most populous Muslim country, invaded
the predominantly Roman Catholic East Timor in December 1975 in the
wake of a civil war between left-wing and right-wing indigenous
forces that broke out after Portugal ended its colonial rule.
Jakarta declared East Timor its 27th province in 1976. 
    Twenty-years later, however, the East Timor issue remained a
political barb for Jakarta. The United Nations and many Western
countries refused to recognize the move, and regard Portugal as the
administrative power in the territory. 
.
