So: U-az
From: cnrmnt@pactok.peg.apc.org
Newsgroups: reg.easttimor
Subject: Indonesian letter to an East Timore
Date: 30 May 1996 12:26:00

Some days ago we published on email an address given by student activist
Cesarina Rocha, an East Timorese exile living in Darwin, who participated at
the Kawangju International Youth Camp for Human Rights and Peace, held in South
Korea from 14 to 20 May 96.

The following message written to Cesarina by an Indonesian person who read her
Kwangju adddress on email has just been received. It very clearly and
eloquently expresses the growing awareness of the people of Indonesia about the
reality in East Timor, and its links to their own suffering under the Suharto
dictatorship.

The letter (which has only been slighly edited to improve its english) shows
the growing understanding of the Indonesian people that the same regime which
oppresses them, and from whose grip they are longing to be freed, is
responsible for the ongoing East Timor tragedy.

It is interesting to note how Indonesians, such as the author of the letter,
hope that international awareness of the aspirations for freedom of the
Indonesian people may be heightened through greater exposure of the oppression
in East Timor.

*******************
Dear Cesarina,

        Thank you for your "very interesting & touchy" mail. It certainly
makes me realize what has become of life these days, especially with the
presence of military oppression, tortures etc ..

        It is time for you and your friends to be more & more aggressive in
telling the world (especially the people of Indonesia) about what has been
really happening in Timor Leste. I know that this is no easy work. But
somebody has to do it !

Perhaps if you could include some photos or even films that captured the
horrible events, the Indonesians will open their eyes and give more and more
support to you and your friends.

You mentioned about Max Stahl documentary, how can we get a copy of that ?
Can you please find out for me ? This type of "live evidence" will certainly
give firm assurance to us Indonesians.

I noticed that there is one prominent Indonesian 'politician-in-exile', Mr.
George Aditjondro, currently living in Newcastle (NSW) who  ocassionally
writes some articles regarding East Timor. It will be nice if you could also
get in touch with him. (I don't know him personally, but judging from his
writing, he is a  very knowledgable person in terms of Indonesian political
issues).

Right now, it's not just the Timor Leste people that are fighting for their
freedom, the Indonesians are too. We are fighting for a true democracy
(Not Democracy Pancasila !)

My prayer will always be with you. Keep in mind that God works in His
mysterious way....

cheers
(name suppressed)
.
