<pre>
So: U-az
From: Comissao para os Direitos povo Maubere  cdpm@gn.apc.org 
Newsgroups: reg.easttimor
Subject: Infant Mortality in Timor
Date: Mon, 03 Jun 1996 20:45:05 +0100 (BST)

Source : Publico 
Date : 30 May 1996 
Dateline : Lisbon 
Scope : Unabridged 
Original Language : Portuguese 
Headline : TIMOR'S BABIES AT HIGH RISK 
 
	East Timor has the highest infant mortality rate of all the 
sparsely populated territories and countries in the world, reported 
the UN yesterday. 
 
	According to a report by the UN's Population Fund, infant 
mortality in East Timor, occupied over 20 years ago by Indonesia, is 
135 deaths per 1,000 births.  This figure is three times higher than 
in Indonesia and infinitely higher than the rate in developed 
countries, which is 3 to 7 deaths per 1,000 births.   
 
	Furthermore, in a population of less than one million, life 
expectancy for men is only 46 years and 48 years for women.   
 
	In such a context, it was, therefore, not surprising that the 
UN Population Fund was unable to obtain from the Indonesian 
authorities figures for the following: maternal mortality, primary 
and secondary school registration, and access to basic health care.
.
