<pre>
So: U-az
From: Comissao para os Direitos povo Maubere  cdpm@gn.apc.org 
Newsgroups: reg.easttimor
Subject: Senator Pell Visits Dili
Date: Mon, 03 Jun 1996 20:46:20 +0100 (BST)

Source : Diario de Noticias 
Date : 30 May 1996 
Dateline : Washington 
Byline : Filipe Vieira 
Original Language : Portuguese 
Scope : Unabridged 
Headline : SENATOR VISITS DILI 
 
Reason for Senator's mission to Indonesia and Timor is human rights. 
 
	UN Senator Clairborne Pell is meeting today with President 
Suharto in Jakarta to discuss the human rights situation in East 
Timor.  Tomorrow, he will be travelling to Dili, and plans to stay 
there a few days for meetings, including one with Monsignor Ximenes 
Belo. 
 
	According to information from Bill Bryant, the Senator's press 
adviser, Pell will also be meeting with Indonesia's Foreign 
Minister, Ali Alatas, and with members of the Indonesian National 
Commission for Human Rights. 
 
	Clairborne Pell, who leaves the Senate in November after being 
the leader of the Foreign Relations Committee for several decades, 
is representative for the State of Rhode Island, where there is a 
considerable Portuguese-American electoral component.  In a 
statement issued  before departing for his visit - the first which 
the Indonesian Government has authorised for Clairborne Pell - the 
Senator's office emphasised the concerns of Rhode Island's 
Portuguese community about conditions of life for the Timorese. 
 
	The Senator always kept up to date on human rights throughout 
the world, and wanted to be sure "to express concern about the 
situation in East Timor" on his last official visit abroad, before 
retiring from politics. 
 
Monsignor Belo expresses gratitude 
 
	The Bishop of Dili, Monsignor Ximenes Belo, thanked Governor 
of Macao Rocha Vieira yesterday for the help extended by the 
Portuguese administration to the Timorese community.  Mnsgr. Belo 
referred especially to "job and study opportunities, and to the 
protection" given to the refugees who go to Macao. 
 
	The Apostolic Administrator of Dili revealed that during his 
meeting with the Governor, the situation of the Church in East Timor 
was discussed. 
 
	Macao has been a place of refuge for many escaping from Timor, 
but most of those who have passed through the territory since 1991 
have subsequently continued their journey to Portugal or Australia, 
with help from the local government. 
 
	There are currently about 70 refugees in Macao.
.
