So: U-az
From: janerik@forsberg.pp.se
Newsgroups: reg.easttimor
Subject: Sweden: Protest letter from Darwin
Date: 02 Jun 1996 11:49:05

From: Jan-Erik Forsberg  janerik@forsberg.pp.se 
Subject: Sweden: Protest letter from Darwin ET supporters
Date: Sun, 2 Jun 1996 20:42:29 +-200

16.5.96


Mr Hugh Bradley
Swedish Honorary Consul
7th Floor  NT House
Darwin   NT


Dear Mr Bradley

     The Swedish East Timor Committee has alerted AFFET to the fact that
the new Swedish government is changing its policy on arm sales to
Indonesia. The previous government had been very critical of the
occupation of East Timor and consequently banned any new arms sales
to Indonesia in 1994.

     We have been told that the Swedish government decided on the 18th of
April to issue an export permit to the arms manufacturer Bofors for 3
or 4 cannons for the Indonesian Navy.
This is a betrayal of the East Timorese,  who are still being killed by
the Indonesian military and being watched closely by the navy so that
no more people can escape by boat to Australia. Despite this the
Timorese  are still courageously refusing to accept the Indonesian
takeover of their country.

     AFFET calls on the Swedish Government to remain strong in support
of East Timor and continue with the ban on arms sales to Indonesia.
We find it disgraceful that the Swedish Government is acquiescing to
pressure from Bofors and economic greed to give more power to the
Indonesian military regime. Demonstrators in Indonesia are calling for
the military to step aside from their government involvement and for a
true democracy to be created in the country.

     We also call on the Swedish Government to support Portugal's
application to for one of the two places available on the United Nations
Security Council so that Portugal is in a strong position to work on the
issue of self-determination for East Timor. Sweden could urge countries
to give Portugal second preference after voting for Sweden's own
application.

     In Darwin we are very close to East Timor so know the situation there
thoroughly. Many of our supporters have visited the country in the last
year and we have constant contact with the East Timorese refugees
here. We hear regular reports of killings, torture and disappearances of
anyone suspected of antipathy towards the Indonesian occupiers. The
East Timorese have not accepted the takeover for 20 years and don't
look like changing their attitude. To think that the Swedish Government
which has such an impressive record on human rights is planning to
supply arms to the Indonesian navy is shameful. We urge the
government to withdraw their decision.

     If you Mr Bradley could pass this letter on to the Swedish Government
as soon as possible we would be appreciative.

     Yours sincerely




     Judith Conway
     Australians For A Free East Timor



.
