So: U-az
From: Carmel Budiardjo  tapol@gn.apc.org 
Newsgroups: reg.easttimor
Subject: UA: Police brutality in Jakarta
Date: Wed, 05 Jun 1996 17:13:26 +0100 (BST)

From: Carmel Budiardjo  tapol 

/* Written  5:12 PM  Jun  5, 1996 by tapol in gn:reg.indonesia */
/* ---------- "UA: Police brutality in Jakarta" ---------- */
UA: POLICE BRUTALITY AGAINST DEMONSTRATORS 
IN JAKARTA

[Based on a report and chronology from PIJAR.]

A number of protesters were injured and six people were 
arrested in Jakarta when troops and police used strong-arm 
tactics against their peaceful demonstration on 4 June. The 
people had gathered for a solemn remembrance to mark the 
fortieth day of the Bloody Makassar (Ujung Pandang) 
Tragedy when troops entered the UMI university campus, 
causing three people to die as they fled the oncoming soldiers.

A few hours later five of those arrested at the Jakarta rally 
were released. The sixth, an activist named Bahar who had 
been badly beaten by police, is still in detention and is likely 
to be charged.


Demonstration, prayers and anti-military protest
About two hundred students and youth, members and 
supporters of the INDONESIAN OPPOSITION, 
(OPSI).gathered outside the University of Indonesia Faculty 
of Medicine in Jakarta at 11am and were confronted by an 
array of army troops and police. Half an hour later, a rally 
organised by PIJAR joined forces with them. The large crowd 
dispersed for prayer: Muslims went to the Arif Rahman 
Mosque on campus, and Christians went to a nearby church.

At 12.30, they re-assembled, carrying two banners reading: 
'Smash military domination' and 'Uphold the Sovereignty of 
the People'. There were also many banners condemning army 
brutality in Makassar.

The protesters then tried to march through the army barricade 
but were prevented from doing so. Lt-Col Jul Effendi, in 
command of the troops, said they would not be allowed to 
proceed. As negotiations continued, troops started trying to 
push back the protesters which resulted in scuffles. At this 
point, no one was injured.

After some time, Jul Effendi proposed that the people gather 
in groups of ten, each guarded by troops but the organisers 
rejected the idea, saying that on a previous occasion, during 
the Sri-Bintang trial, such a tactic had led to people being 
beaten by the troops.

Suddenly, Jul Effendi pushed the front row of the police 
forward, bringing them into physical contact with the 
protesters. At this point, several people were forcibly 
removed by Jul Effendi and other soldiers and taken into 
custody, for allegedly being the ones who had pushed forward 
people on their side.

At 1.30, the police officer in command came forward and 
ordered the students 'not to disrupt public order'. Half an hour 
later, OPSI organisers managed to persuade the army officers 
to let them march to the LBH office on Jalan Diponegoro. 
They marched, holding hands, singing nationalist songs and 
shouting slogans.

After arriving at the LBH office at 2.45, an open-air meeting 
was held and a number of speeches were made on the street 
outside. The traffic was held up causing congestion for about 
an hour, as hundreds of passers-by stopped to watch.

Shortly after 3pm, the protesters went into the LBH office. 
When police tried to enter as well, the protesters objected and 
there was a lot of pushing and shuvving. Some people were 
beaten. Many protesters became enraged; there were more 
scuffles and some people started throwing stones. A number 
of people fell, wounded by flying missiles. A PIJAR member 
named Bahar was dragged along, trampled on, beaten and 
pulled along the ground for a hundred metres. A journalist 
covering the event was also hurt. Two members of the police 
were injured by stones.

URGENT ACTION:

Please address protests at the army and police brutality to:

General Hartono,
Chief-of-Staff of the Army,
Fax: +62-21 364 926
Your protest to General Hartono should also express 
abhorrence at army brutality against the students in Makassar 
during their three-day protests from 22 - 24 April 1996

Major-General Dibyo Widodo,
Chief of the Indonesian Police,
Fax: +62-21 361 471 


-------------------

The following is a statement issued on 4 June by OPOSISI 
INDONESIA, to mark the fortieth day of the Bloody 
Makassar Tragedy:

Statement by the INDONESIAN OPPOSITION / OPSI

4 June 1996

Today, 4 June 1996, it is forty days since we all heard and 
witnessed a shameful incident that is a black stain on the 
history of the New Order, the Bloody Makassar Tragedy. This 
follows a string of tragedies: Tanjung Priok, Lampung, Haur 
Koneng, Marsinah and Nipah. The Makassar Tragedy 
happened when students who are part of the common people, 
demonstrated in protest against a decision by the Mayor of 
Makassar to raise the fares on 'pete-pete', the most popular 
means of city transport. The increase was a great burden for 
everyone. The protest demonstration started off peacefully but 
turned into an onslaught of the military against the students. 
Ironically, this happened at several university campuses in 
Makassar (Ujung Pandang).

The way the military handled the Makassar Tragedy can only 
be described as despotic and brutal. They showed total 
disregard for democratic values and human rights. In addition, 
they used 'preman' (thugs). Gangs of these mercenaries have 
been formed and given protection in order to intimidate 
anyone who comes forward with aspirations. These thugs 
have been used against workers' demonstrations in Medan, at 
the time of the disorder in the Batak church and during the 
Sri-Bintang Pamungkas trial. These examples show that the 
military always justify and make use of such brutality. 

All this makes it crystal clear that the military are involved as 
the key player in a whole range of cases and that the military 
have become an instrument of repression. They can no longer 
pose as defenders of the people, which was the purpose when 
the armed forces (ABRI) first came into being.

Are we going to allow this to continue? NO! NEVER! It is 
our joint responsibility to reform and change this intolerable 
situation and in order to do this, people's sovereignty must be 
affirmed on Indonesian soil.

We, the INDONESIAN OPPOSITION, therefore demand:

Specific demands:

1.	That the Supreme Commander of ABRI [President 
Suharto] publicly accept responsibility and apologise for the 
Makassar Tragedy through the mass media.
2.	The resignation of the ABRI chief-of-staff for 
general affairs [Lt General Soeyono].
3.	The resignation of the commander [Major-General 
Sulatin] of the Wirabuana regional military command (South 
Sulawesi).
4.	The formation of a Military Honour Council to 
conduct a thorough-going, public investigation into the 
Makassar Tragedy.
5.	All military officers involved in the Makassar 
Tragedy should be put on trial.
6.	The Makassar trials should be transparent.

General demands:

7.	The dissolution of BAKORSTANAS (the 
Coordinating Agency for National Stability) because its 
existence is not in conformity with the Constitution.
8.	The repeal of the five political laws of 1985.
9.	The separation of the Police Force from ABRI.
10.	An end to the presence of an ABRI group in 
Parliament.
11.	An end to the use of 'preman' by the military. 

This statement is supprted by: PIJAR, SAFINA, FORMACI, 
HUMANIKA, HMI, PUSPIPAM, FKAM, FPPM Garut, 
FKKMT, PPBI, SMID, SRDJ, STN, FPPHR, MPKR, 
PIPHAM, FKPMJU, FPMD, SAPUHAMA.




.
