<pre>
So: U-az
From: ale@inf.fu-berlin.de
Newsgroups: reg.easttimor
Subject: Belo on the Italian Press
Date: 03 Jun 1996 12:56:26

From: ale@inf.fu-berlin.de (Alessandro Panconesi)



Several articles appeared recently in the Italian press.
In general, they were all very sympathetic to the cause of East Timor.
The ones I saw so far, however, do not say anything that
it is not already well-known to the reader of reg.easttimor,
for they introduced for the first time the
tragedy of the timorese to the Italian audience. 

I enclose below a translation from Italian of an article
containing a brief interview with Mons. Belo, which prompted an
official, outraged response from the Indoenesian Embassy in Rome.
The article (sympathetic but rather inaccurate and superficial, in my opinion)
appeared on Il Corriere della Sera, considered by many the
most prestigious Italian newspaper and enjoying wide circulation. 


	Cheers,

	Ale



------------------------- snip snip


Source: Corriere della Sera.   Apr 14, 1996

Title: "Timor, the eternal slave"
        But Bishop Belo is sure: indoensian rule will end

Author: Ettore Mo


Dili (East Timor) -- The night of Holy Friday a procession of three, perhaps
four thousand people brought a crucified Jesus to the
Santa Cruz cemetery. Hundreds of little lights were palpitating 
in the darkness above people's heads, who intensely celebrated
the liturgy of death [Note: Easter for the Catholics] 
But here, unlike in the rest of the world, the Week of Passion wouldn't end 
at the crack of dawn because the last time the bells celebrated
the Resurrection [Note: of Jesus Christ] in East Timor it was 20 years ago. 

Its burial goes back to December 7, 1975, when indonesian troups
invaded the eastern part of Timor (a portuguese colony until a few months
earlier), stripping away the newly proclaimed independence
and handing in the island to the governement of Jakarta
which hastily annexed it on July 17, 1976, and declared
it its 27th province.
The cost of the occupation is staggering: about 200 thousand deads, about a
third of the population. A genocide.

The United Nations never recognized the legitimacy of the invasion: but who 
could care about this remote earth fragment 
(14,600 square kilometers) in the midst of an archipelago
of 18,508 islands, only 6,000 of which have a name, and 1,000 of which
have never been inhabited?
Dili, the capital, raises its voice with indignation. It protests. But for
Jakarta, which answers with 190 milion people (the
fourth most populated nation in the world), it's only the cry of a
baby. 

With the same arrogance, president Suharto did what Saddamn Hussein
did 16 years later in the Gulf. But East Timor did not have its bowels full
of oil and the US did not run to the rescue unleashing a Desert Storm.
The timorese were alone. The armed struggle, immediately undertaken
and guided by Fretilin-- the group of the Resistance best prepared for it--
was never able to contain and repel the aggression.

Today however,  if you enter Dili you won't have the
feeling of being in an occupied city. There are few soldiers in the streets,
no armoured cars in front of governement offices, and few vehicles of the
indonesian army. An almost demilitarized and sleepy capital:
fish vendors along the seaside, a few tourists with a bewildered look,
a few motionless ships in the bay, and squaling children diving 
into the water.

But behind the walls, doors and windows there are no singers of
lullabys or flutes to control Fretilin
that back in 1974 displayed the red carnations of Lisbon 
and showed off its strong marxist connotations [Note:
I doubt this make sense, but the Italian version too is obscure.]
Jakarta sent to the former colony a dozen battallions:
12 thousand men trained in rapid deployment who can count, when needed,
on the support of armoured vehicles and aircrafts.
The enemy is not scaring: a few thousands
badly equipped guerrillas scattered over the mountains; legions of
students organized in semi-clandestine brotherhoods armed only with slogans;
and the crowd, the anonymous and silent crowd of farmers
and fishermen who, all of a sudden, went from an archaic slavery to a modern
one, more rational and cruel.

Having immediately destroyed the initial aspiration of the timorese to
independence, the major aim of Jakarta was to erect
a wall of silence around the country, to isolate it from the rest of
the world so that its army could consummate its misdeeds. 
Like tha Santa Cruz massacre (November 12 1991), when the military brutally
quashed a demonstration of youngsters. It was a massacre.
To this day it is not known how many youths died: some say
100, some 200, some even 400 or 500. It seems that they were buried
in a mass grave, fattened with bullets. But where?
Nobody really knows where to lay the flowers.

People who investigate foster suspicion. The presence of foreign journalists is
discouraged in all possible ways and one has to make a big effort,
which entails having too many "suspect" stamps on the passport,
to cross the border as a tourist.
Once "on the spot" one feels scrutinized, followed from afar,
surrounded by a net of informers. The full-time spies have a fixed-salary
of 12 dollar a month: occasional bloodhounds receive one or two
dollars per information. They are fastidious, nice,
cunning: some are not insensitive to the "theft" [Note: Italian too doesn't
make sense to me].

The Via Crucis of East Timor has as many stops as those of the Calvario
and the last one does not seem too far away. Alas, anguish is now gripping
even the most irreducible amongst the independentists. Illusions and hopes are
breaking apart. The charismatic and historical leader of Fretilin 
Xanana Gusmao is in jail in Jakarta since november 1993; since then
the movement, without leadership, is struggling to survive;
the armed struggle is dissolving for lack of weapons and links; 
the great powers continue to ignore Timor which,
as the indonesian secretary of state Ali Alatas jokingly remarks with cinicism,
"is only a small stone in our shoes"; and president Suharto is about
to celebrate, on July 17, the 20th anniversary of the annexation.
All flaunted in front of the United Nations, Amnesty International and
the entire world.

"Not so fast-- says Monsignor Carlos Ximenes Belo, bishop of Dili, 
waving his arms as if to stave off an unwelcome ghost -- let's not
sing the Requiem before we see the dead. True, it seems that 
there is no alternative to the integration; independence looks
unreachable and our identity is perhaps about
to be extinguished... No, no, I feel it is not like that"

48 years old, a bona fide timorese, studies in the seminary of 
Rome, this priest of simple manners, that seems to be more confortable in a 
gown without ornaments than in episcopal garments,
became in less than 15 years the only, authentic and authoritative
spokesperson of a people that could not otherwise express its anguish
and aspirations:
"But I am not a political leader-- he cautions-- my role is only moral:
this is imposed on me by my conscienze of citizen and man of the Church.
Oh, I am well aware: we are small people which count nothing. But my
roots are in this earth and I am the shepherd of these poor people.
We have the right to say the last word: write it, journalist".
[Note: this is ambiguous in Italian. "Right" might as well
be "Responsability". The meaning then changes completely]

In 1975, when the indonesians invaded the ex-colony trucidating also 5 
reporters of an australian TV, Carlos Ximenes Belo was not yet ordained
priest. He came to know of the mass murders abroad, where he was.
"Many people were brought to the harbour and murdered one by one,
like the Nazis used to do-- recounted Xanana during a recent clandestine
interview in jail-- and the churches were destroyed and left full of urine and
excrements". All of a sudden, East Timor became yet another example
of brutal colonization. But perhaps the portuguese of the XV century,
who were the first to spread siphilis and a crass, bigoted and
luxurious form of Catholicism, were less savage.

Monsignor Belo opens his arms: "But how? I asked myself when, in 1981,
I came back to Wailacalma, my village. My mother cried, everybody cried.
Portugal had just let us free and suddenly, before we could be timorese
again, we had become indonesians-- according to a document undersigned in 1976
in Balibo which gave it a juridical foundation. But who signed it?"

Holy Thursday. A solemn religious ceremony in the cathedral of
Dili, the biggest catholic church in the whole of South East Asia.
The bishop, dressed in shining robes, cleanses the feet of the poor,
as prescribed by the liturgy. A man only skin and bones remains on his knees
in front of the altar for hours, his arms open, the hands vibrating
like leaves for the effort. The bells sound for the deads.

"The victims of the invasion were more than 200 thousand-- confirms the
bishop-- and occurred for the most part during the first phase.
A good part of the population was decimated in the years '77, '78 and '79
by bombings, illnesses and starvation. At the time the portuguese left
we were about 650 thousands, in 1979 we were reduced to 350 thousands...
today in East Timor there are 850 thousands inhabitants but one must
consider that at least 100 thousand are indonesians, sent here by 
Jakarta's policy of readjustment".

"Indonesization" of East Timor is the final objective of Suharto and
his government: once this is attained the whole island will have
a homogeneous and harmoniuos culture,
given that the western part of the island (Timor Barat) was absorbed 
by Jakarta at the moment of independence without trauma.

In 20 years of occupation, Indonesia tried to impose (often succesfully)
its own life-style which is alien to timorese costumes.
"They made me drink fresh blood coming right from the cut throat of a chicken,
as it is in their tradition" laments a fisherman of Hera with a 
grimace of disgust. As a matter of fact,  it is precisely
the attainement of this cultural metamorphosis that is behind 
the "generosity" of Jakarta which claims to have done for Tim-Tim (East Timor)
more than what Portugal had done in 3 centuries: roads, schools, hospitals.

"Prosperity and progress cannot be measured by these things--
claims Monsignor Belo-- Let's look at schools for instance. A system of
total ``indonesization'' is applied, something similar to what must have
happened in Italy during the two decades of Fascism. Boys and girls leave 
the classrooms, faculties are empty. Students do not want to swallow 
their teachings any more.. They do not realize that they are
creating an anti-indoensian youth. These are the youngsters 
which in the mountains are joining Fretilin."

From Liquica to Los palos, from Bacau to Viqueue, repression is still
very harsh: one could not otherwise explain the attempted "suicides"
of many people that to this day choose to challenge 500 kilometers of high
seas on precarious boats to reach the australian coast. To feed the
desperation of the boat people of Timor is the conviction that
"the game is over" and nobody can delude himself believeing in an
ultimate military success of the Resistance. "By now they are very few--
admits the bishop-- divided into groups of fifteen or twenty scattered
on the mountains:
but their effectivness notwithstanding, Fretilin or Falentil (its
armed branch) continue to represent the spirit of a people who does not
want to give up."

Holy friday. The bells continue to sounds for the deads. 
It would exaggerated to see in the current conflict the signs of
of a religous war: but the fervor and intensity of the Easter atmosphere
confirmed that faith and nationalist sentiments, melted together, are an
explosive mixture.
With an overwhelming islamic majority (88 % of the population),
Indonesia is the greatest muslim country in the world and it would be all
too easy for Jakarta, Belo suggest, to make a populous islamic garden out
of Timor: "But to do this-- says the bishop-- they must extirpate our
community, where the catholics
comprise the 95%. No, on this terrain we are to strong, we run no risks."

Jakarta cannot escape the conclusion that Holy Friday procession, which took
place in the cemetery of Santa Cruz, represents a double hommage: to
the nationalist students ideologically marshalled behind the Fretilin flag,
and the youths of the diocese who, together, became martyrs in the
name of Faith. It is
obvious that the indoensian government has no interest in furthering this 
kind of conflict and it is not surprising that, on July 17, president Suharto 
cunningly announced that he will take part in the inauguration of a
statue of King Christ, which will dominate from above the bay of Dili.

The bishop smiles:
"Obviously I won't be there-- he says-- I declined the invitation. I do
not like it when religion becomes an instrument. I cannot tolerate that
Jesus be inconvenienced to make solemn the anniversary
of annexation and to benedict our slavery."

 




.
