So: U-az
From: nag-gunn@net.nagasaki-u.ac.jp
Newsgroups: reg.easttimor
Subject: Alatas threatens
Date: 04 Jun 1996 17:47:32

From: nag-gunn@net.nagasaki-u.ac.jp (Geoffrey C. Gunn)


Apropos the following report, perhaps Mr. Alatas could explain how such
blusters square with the consensus statements of the Indonesian and
Portuguese foreign ministers at, inter alia, New York (17 September 1993),
on the need to foster "an atmosphere propitious to addrressing the substance
of the question", or, statement by Sec-Gen's spokesman on East Timor of 6
May 1994 "on the need for continued restraint by both parties in the
interest of maintaining a favourable atmosphere for further progress towards
a comprehensive solution of the question of East Timor" (reinterated 9
January 1995). Indeed, what is the basis of the presumption to undermine the
mandated role of the Secretary-General in overseeing this process, and, for
that matter, the presumption to dismiss East Timorese interest in their own
destiny. Nevertheless, the following revelation of Indonesian attitudes and
tactics vis-a-vis the world body must be seen as saluatory.

Geoffrey C. Gunn    



Peter Montagnon and Manuela Saragosa in Jakarta, "Indonesia threatens
showdown on E. Timor" (Financial Times, Tokyo edition, 3 June 1996), p.6
[abbrieviated]

Indonesia has warned it will eventually force a showdown with Portugal in
the United Nations over the controversial question of East Timor unless
there is progress in bilateral discussions on the political status of
Lisbon's former colony.

The blunt statement from Mr. Alatas, foreign minister, at the weekend is
designed to put pressure on the new Portuguese foregin minister, Mr. Jaime
Gama. Mr. Alatas is due to meet his Portuguese counterpart for a second
round of talks in Geneva later this month.

...."We're ready for a showdown any time", Mr. Alatas said in an interview.
"If it's in the General Assembly we have the numbers, and they know that.
But we want a solution which is more or less durable and where no one feels
a loser". [What consummate irony, in what way are the East Timorese not
losers, in this logic?, G.C.G.]

....The mere fact that Indonesia feels able openly to consider such a move is
an indication of the growing international political weignt of the fast
growing south-east Asian region. Mr. Alatas said his message should not be
seen as an ultimatum.

"I don't think we should give ourselves or each other a deadline", he said...

But he pointed out that Portugal had refused on two occasions - in 1987 and
1991 - to adopt a UN suggestion of an independent fact-finding mission
followed by an open discussion and a vote among members... [Does Alatas wish
to sanction a UN-sponsored referendum or not?, G.C.G.]  

....Indonesia's view that most East Timorese have long accepted Indonesian
sovereignty has still not been accepted by the UN.

It is challenged not only by Portugal but also by leading human rights
organisations.

.
