<pre>
So: U-az
From: cscheiner@igc.apc.org
Newsgroups: reg.easttimor
Subject: No US Aid to Indon. Military!
Date: 04 Jun 1996 23:33:21 -0800 (PST)

From: Charles Scheiner  cscheiner@igc.apc.org 

ACTION ALERT: BAN FREE U.S. TRAINING FOR INDONESIAN MILITARY

On Wednesday, June 5, the House of Representatives debates H.R. 3540,
the Foreign Assistance Appropriations Act. If it passes unamended,
this bill will appropriate $800,000 in taxpayers' money to train
Indonesian soldiers.

ASK YOUR REPRESENTATIVE NOT TO FUND SUHARTO'S KILLERS.

Representative Barney Frank (D-Massachusetts) will introduce an
amendment to H.R.3540 to prohibit military aid for Indonesia under the
IMET (International Military Education and Training) program.

ALL Representatives will vote on this amendment today or tomorrow.

Call your Representative NOW and urge him or her to support the Frank
amendment banning IMET for Indonesia. They can be reached through the
Capitol switchboard at 202-225-3121.

Background

IMET brings foreign soldiers to the U.S. for training, and has been
provided to many countries, including Indonesia, for decades.
Thousands of the soldiers who maintain General Suharto's tight control
over the Indonesian and East Timorese people have been trained in the
USA.

Congress terminated IMET aid for Indonesia in 1992 after the Santa
Cruz massacre in East Timor, when Indonesian soldiers fired their
U.S.-supplied machine guns into a peaceful memorial procession,
killing over 250 unarmed people. The ban was reaffirmed in 1993 and
1994, although the Clinton administration circumvented Congressional
intent by selling military training to Indonesia.

After the 1994 Congressional elections, IMET for Indonesia was
partially restored, although limited to "Expanded IMET," (E-IMET)
which is ostensibly restricted to non-military subjects. The New York
Times editorialized ("No Scholarships for Indonesia's Soldiers," April
20, 1995): "By signaling to Indonesia's top commanders that American
taxpayers will pay for scholarships no matter how badly its soldiers
behave in East Timor, the Administration more than cancels out the
benefits of any new human rights training courses. Congress should
maintain the ban."

Congress did not. Led by Foreign Operations Subcommittee Chair Sonny
Callahan (R-AL), $600,000 was appropriated for E-IMET last year.
Callahan has been heavily lobbied by the Indonesian government, and
one of Suharto's top Ministers is building an aircraft factory in his
district in Mobile.

After this signal of U.S. support for the Indonesian military, the
human rights situation in East Timor deteriorated even further, with
hundreds of young East Timorese fleeing for their lives. The 1995
State Department Report on Human Rights, released last March, found
that "Reports of extrajudicial killings, disappearances, and torture
of those in custody by security forces increased."

Last month, Callahan upped Indonesia's grant to $800,000 (of $45
million worldwide) for 1997. Although his bill prohibits all IMET for
Zaire and Guatemala, Indonesia would receive E-IMET.

Talking Points

1. Continuing IMET rewards Indonesia's military regime for continuing
   unacceptable policies, sending precisely the wrong message. After
   last year's restoration, the situation in East Timor has become
   more repressive than at any time since early 1992.

2. Human rights violations in East Timor are intrinsic to the military
   occupation, and represent policy determined at the highest levels.
   There have been so many violations (200,000 killings) during the
   past 21 years that it inconceivable that these are not officially
   sanctioned. No amount of "human rights" training for individual
   soldiers will change the situation.

3. "Expanded" IMET purports to train low-level soldiers in civilian
   control of the military. The Indonesian government is a military
   dictatorship which usurped control in 1965. There is no semblance
   of civilian control at any level -- even the economy is permeated
   by the military, especially in East Timor.

4. IMET is used by the Indonesian government to signify that they have
   solved the situation in East Timor. "Look," they say, "even the
   U.S. Congress finally understands that there is no problem in East
   Timor. They have given us a vote of confidence by restoring IMET."

5. The Frank amendment does not call for limitations on the U.S.-
   Indonesia economic relationship, and would have no effect on such
   ties, which benefit both the U.S. and Indonesia.

6. In this time of fiscal scarcity, here is an easy way to save
   $800,000 of taxpayers' money.

Please let ETAN know of any responses you receive. Thank you.

---------------------------------
East Timor Action Network / United States
P.O. Box 1182, White Plains, New York 10602
Tel. 914-428-7299  fax: 914-428-7383  email: etan-us@igc.apc.org

June 5, 1996


.
