So: U-az
From: calliope@ihug.co.nz
Newsgroups: reg.easttimor
Subject: NZH: Dunn calls for ET war crime in
Date: 05 Jun 1996 15:05:19

From: calliope@ihug.co.nz (calliope)
Subject: NZH: Dunn calls for ET war crime inquiry

The New Zealand Herald
6 June 1996
"Call for inquiry into East Timor killings"

MELBOURNE (AAP) - A former diplomat has called for an international inquiry on
Indonesian war crimes in East Timor, comparing wartime brutality there to that
in Bosnia.

Mr James Dunn, a foreign affairs correspondent and former diplomat to East
Timor, said military leaders responsible for mass killings in East Timor must
face an international tribunal such as the court of justice at The Hague.

"There have been at least three or four mass killings along the lines of some
of those perpetrated in Bosnia," Mr Dunn said in a lecture to the Australian
Institute of International Affairs.

"In Italy they are trying a man who was responsible for war crimes on a
smaller scale compared to those in East Timor.

"We badly need an ivestigation. Where are these people who did this?" he
asked.

Mr Dunn said Indonesian people wanted answers as well.

"I think it's a great thing for Indonesia to identify who were the killers
responsible - the generals or whatever - in East Timor so we can absolve the
Indonesian people of blame," Mr Dunn said.

"It often worries me when I give lectures and people stand up and say 'I never
did trust those Indonesians.' Not all Indonesians are like that. I have a
great love of Indonesians.

"The people I have a fear of are the people who have the guns."

Any talk of reconciliation was impossible for East Timor while war criminals
went unpunished, he said.

"Even if the military or the regime responsible stops killing people, the
psychological presence of the same uniform, the same arrogance, leaves it the
same.

"It doesn't matter where it is; gross violations must be brought to account if
we're going to get justice to the victims."

Indonesia has occupied the formerly Portugugese colony of East Timor since a
military invasion in 1975.

-ENDS

.
