<pre>
So: U-az
From: Ray Mitchell  rmitchellai@gn.apc.org 
Newsgroups: reg.easttimor
Subject: AI UA136/96 INDONESIA Torture fear
Date: Thu, 06 Jun 1996 19:29:18 +0100 (BST)

From: Ray Mitchell  rmitchellai 

/* Written  7:28 PM  Jun  6, 1996 by rmitchellai in gn:ai.uan */
/* ---------- "AI UA136/96 INDONESIA Torture fear" ---------- */
+------------------------------------------------------+
+ Paper reprints authorised. Electronic redistributors +
+ must request permission from Amnesty International.  +
+ Contact:   rmitchellai@gn.apc.org (UK)               +
+            sharrison@igc.apc.org (USA)               +
+            ggabriel@amnesty.cl.sub.de (Germany)      +
+------------------------------------------------------+
 
EXTERNAL                                   AI Index: ASA 21/33/96
                                           6 June 1996
 
UA 136/96               Fear of torture                      
 
INDONESIA               Two men (names unknown)
 
Amnesty International is concerned for the safety of two men
arrested by the Indonesian Armed Forces during a military operation
to free 11 hostages held for three months by the Free Papua Movement
(Organisasi Papua Merdeka - OPM) in the Indonesian province of Irian
Jaya.
 
According to the military, the two men, thought to be members of the
OPM, were captured when troops from Indonesia's special forces known
as Kopassus launched a rescue operation on 15 May 1996 to free the
hostages who had been held since 8 January. The names of the two
were not given and there has been no information on their
whereabouts since their arrest. In view of serious human rights
violations in Irian Jaya including extrajudicial executions,
"disappearance" and torture Amnesty International fears that the two
may be subjected to torture during interrogation. Amnesty
International is also concerned that the two may not have had access
to independent lawyers. 
 
A human rights manual produced by the Irian Jaya regional military
command in December 1995 prohibits the use of torture to obtain
confessions or information and stresses the right of captured
members of the armed resistance to a trial in accordance with the
law. It also states that the arresting authority - in this case
Kopassus - must record the identity of the persons arrested, the
reason for the arrest and detention and that direct visit by family
members of detainees must be permitted.
 
The exact circumstances surrounding the release of the hostages
remains unclear with attempts to verify conflicting reports made
difficult by the heavy military presence in the area and
restrictions on access to independent monitors. Two Indonesian
hostages were killed during the rescue operation and, according to
the military, six to eight hostage-takers were also killed. There
are also unconfirmed reports of retaliations, including killings and
house burning, against local people by the military both before and
after the rescue. 
 
BACKGROUND INFORMATION
 
De facto authority over Irian Jaya was transferred from the
Netherlands to Indonesia in 1963. This was followed by a plebiscite
in 1969 to determine the territory's political status which resulted
in a vote for integration.
 
Opposition to integration with Indonesia has continued since 1963.
The OPM is among the most prominent groups advocating independence.
The OPM advocates armed struggle, but many supporters of
independence have employed peaceful means, including demonstrations,
flag-raising ceremonies, political discussion groups, and appeals
to the UN and other international bodies.
 
In recent years the issue of land and resources has generated
particular discontent, focused mainly on the PT Freeport Indonesia
Mine at Tembagapura. Since July 1994 both peaceful and violent
opposition to the mine from local people has intensified. In April
1995, allegations of serious human rights violations in response to
these protests began to emerge. The allegations which included
extrajudicial executions, "disappearances", torture and arbitrary
arrests, were later investigated and confirmed by Indonesia's
National Commission on Human Rights, Komisi Nasional Hak Asasi
Manusia (Komnas Ham).
 
RECOMMENDED ACTION: Please send
telegrams/telexes/faxes/express/airmail letters in Bahasa Indonesia,
English or your own language: 
 
- urging the authorities to provide details of the names and
whereabouts of the two people arrested during the operation on 15
May 1996 to release the hostages in Irian Jaya; 
 
- seeking assurances that the detainees are not being subjected to
any form of torture or ill-treatment; 
 
- calling for the detainees to be granted access to lawyers of their
own choice, members of the International Committee of the Red Cross,
family members and adequate medical care; 
 
- referring to the obligations on the detaining authority under the
December 1995 human rights manual produced by the Irian Jaya
regional military command. 
 
APPEALS TO:
 
COMMANDER OF SPECIAL FORCES COMMAND (KOPASSUS):
 
Brig. Gen. Prabowo Subianto
[Salutation: Dear Brig. Gen. Prabowo Subianto]
Panglima Kopassus
Markas Besar ABRI
Cilangkap
Jakarta Timur, Indonesia
Telegrams:       Panglima Kopassus, Jakarta, Indonesia
 
MILITARY COMMANDER REGION VIII/TRIKORA (covers Irian Jaya):
 
Major-General Dunidja D
[Salutation: Dear Major-General Dunidja]
Pangdam VIII/Trikora
Markas Besar KODAM VIII/Trikora
Jayapura
Irian Jaya, Indonesia
Telegrams:       Pangdam VIII/Trikora, Jayapura, Irian Jaya, Indonesia
 
PLEASE SEND COPIES OF YOUR APPEALS TO:  His Excellency Mr Junus
Effendy Habibie, Embassy of Indonesia, 38 Grosvenor Square, London
W1X 9AD. Fax: 0171 491 4993
 
AND, IF POSSIBLE, TO THE FOLLOWING:
 
MINISTER OF FOREIGN AFFAIRS:
 
Ali Alatas S.H.
Menteri Luar Negeri
Jl. Medan Taman Pejambon No.6
Jakarta, Indonesia
Fax:             +62 21360 517/380 5511/345 7782/360 541
 
PLEASE SEND APPEALS IMMEDIATELY. Please do not send appeals after
31 July 1996.
 
+-----------------------------------------------------------+
+ If you have any queries about this Urgent Action or about +
+ the UA scheme in general, please contact:                 +
+   Ray Mitchell                                            +
+   Amnesty International UK Section                        +
+   99 - 119 Rosebery Avenue                                +
+   London EC1R 4RE      email: rmitchellai@gn.apc.org      +
+-----------------------------------------------------------+
