<pre>
So: U-az
From: fbp@igc.apc.org
Newsgroups: reg.easttimor
Subject: House to vote on IMET for Indonesia
Date: 07 Jun 1996 10:12:05 -0800 (PST)

From: Foreign Bases Project  fbp@igc.apc.org 

East Timor Action Network/US

MEDIA
RELEASE


For Immediate Release                          Contact:
                                         John M. Miller
                                          (718)788-6071

       East Timor Action Network Urges Congress 
       to End Military Training Aid to Indonesia

The East Timor Action Network (ETAN) today urged the House of
Representatives to support an amendment to delete funding for IMET
military training aid to Indonesia. The House is scheduled to vote
on the amendment, introduced by Barney Frank (D-MA) on Tuesday,
June 11, when it resumes consideration of HR 3540, the Foreign
Assistance Appropriations Act. 

According to ETAN National Coordinator Charlie Scheiner, "ETAN
believes that providing IMET only rewards Indonesia's military
regime for continuing its destructive policies in East Timor."

Last year, Congress voted to restore IMET (International Military
Education and Training). It had cut it off in 1992 in response to
the massacre of over 250 peaceful protesters in Dili, East Timor,
on November 12, 1991. Although Congress passed a restricted form of
IMET (known as Expanded IMET), Indonesia saw it as a signal of
lessened Congressional concern about abuses in East Timor. 

Since then, the human rights situation in East Timor has
deteriorated with hundreds of young East Timorese attempting to
flee East Timor and Indonesia by entering embassies in Jakarta. The
1995 State Department Report on Human Rights, released in March,
found that "Reports of extrajudicial killings, disappearances, and
torture of those in custody by security forces increased." 

Expanded IMET (E-IMET) is confined to non-weapons training in areas
like human rights and civilian control of the military.

"The problem with the Indonesian military is not a lack of awareness
of human rights, but there deliberate violation on orders from
above," said Scheiner. "There have been so many deaths and other
human rights violations during the past 21 years that it is
inconceivable that these are not officially sanctioned. No amount
of 'human rights' training for individual  soldiers will change the
situation. 

"While E-IMET purports to soldiers in civilian  control
of the military," added Scheiner, "the Indonesian government is a
military dictatorship." 

If passed unamended, HR 3540 will appropriate $800,000 for
International Military Education and Training (IMET) for Indonesia.
This is $200,000 more than this year's appropriation.

Indonesia invaded East Timor over twenty years ago on December 7,
1975. It annexed East Timor the following July in a move not
recognized by the United Nations. According to human rights groups
and the Catholic Church over 200,000 people, one-third of the
population, have been  killed by fighting, executions, and famine
and disease. 

The East Timor Action Network/US was founded following the November
1991 massacre. ETAN/US supports genuine self-determination and human
rights for the people of East Timor in accordance with the UN
Charter and pertinent General Assembly and Security Council
resolutions. ETAN/US currently  have a dozen local chapters around
the country. 

                        --30--
.
