BALTIC SEA REGION NEWS

RIGA-VILNIUS -- NEGOTIATIONS  OVER  THE  LATVIA-LITHUANIA  SEA
BORDER DISPUTE SHOW PROGRESS,  according to the State Minister
of Foreign Affairs,  Juris Sinka,  who is leading the  Latvian
delegation at the sea border talks with Lithuania, in Vilnius,
Lithuania.  Mr.  Sinka said on April 23 that he  is  satisfied
with  the  talks  and  considers that another step froward has
been taken.  Delegations from Lithuania and Latvia  had  taken
the  1927 Latvia-Lithuania agreement as the starting point for
negotiations.  Latvia had agreed that part of  the  Lithuanian
coast  line  includes the Kursu Joma (Kursu Strait) from which
the Latvia-Lithuania sea border extends into the  Baltic  Sea.
The talks were devoted entirely to the border issue.  The next
round of negotiations will take place in Riga on May  7,  when
Lithuania's President Algirdas Brazauskas visits Latvia.  Both
sides have expressed their desire to settle the dispute  in  a
timely fashion. (LETA)

TARTU-PSKOV -- ESTONIAN MINISTRIES OF FINANCE AND OF TRANSPORT
AND  COMMUNICATIONS  have  publicly  disagreed  on  a  highway
project to connect Tallinn,  through Tartu and Voru,  with the
existing St.  Petersburg-Kiev Highway.  Ministry of  Transport
representative  Lembit  Kiviloo  stated  that  the  project is
without perspective for Estonia. The Via Russica project would
include  upgrading  the  existing  Tallinn-Tartu  road  into a
highway, connecting Tartu with Voru via Petseri (Pechora), and
renovating  the  railway  link  from  Valga to Pihkva (Pskov).
Southeastern Estonia would in this way become a transit  point
from   Russia   to  Scandinavia.  The  Ministry  of  Transport
representative  believes  that  the  development  of  railways
should  be the sole main priority,  as today only five percent
of cargo traffic goes by highway. (ETA, 26 Apr.)

April 26, VILNIUS -- LITHUANIA'S IGNALINA NUCLEAR POWER PLANT,
the  home  of  two  Chernobyl-type  reactors,  remains a major
source of concern to  the  Baltic  state's  Nordic  neighbors,
stated  one  Scandinavian  diplomat  in  Vilnius.  "There is a
general level of concern in the  Nordic  countries  about  the
possibility  of  an  accident at Ignalina," he said.  Ignalina
supplies about 80 percent of Lithuania's  electricity,  making
Lithuania  the  most  nuclear-power  dependent  country in the
world. Four reactors were originally planned for Ignalina, but
construction on the third was halted in 1987 by massive public
protests in the wake of the 1986 Chernobyl disaster.

RIGA -- POLICE  IN  LITHUANIA  HAVE  SEIZED  10  KILOGRAMS  OF
CAESIUM133  and  arrested  two men who were trying to sell it,
the country's prosecutor's office said.  Lithuania and  Baltic
neighbors  Latvia  and  Estonia  are  suspected  of  being key
gateways for the smuggling to the West of radioactive and rare
metals  pilfered  from the former Soviet bloc.  Caesium can be
produced as a deadly by-product of  nuclear  fission  but  the
prosecutor's  office  said  the  caesium-133  variety  is  not
radioactive.  It is, however, very poisonous. The two men were
arrested  in  Kaunas  after  they  tried to sell the metal,  a
prosecution statement said.


SVETOGORSK, KARELIA  --  THE GIANT SVETOGORSK PAPER PROCESSING
PLANT is being converted by its new Swedish owners to  operate
on  natural  gas  rather than oil.  The gas energy source will
produce less air pollution and  is  more  economical  for  the
plant than oil today,  due to the high transportation costs of
oil within Russia.  The plant produces much of  the  cardboard
used  in  Tetra  packaging  throughout  Russia  and the C.I.S.
Improvements are also planned at the plant in future in  order
to  make the present bleaching process of cardboard stock more
environmentally safe. (Vesti)


RIGA --   LATVIA   SPENT   SIGNIFICANTLY  LESS  LAST  YEAR  ON
ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION than in the previous year,  according
to the Central Statistical Bureau of Latvia.  About 36 million
U.S.  dollars were spent on environmental protection  and  the
rational  utilization  of natural resources in Latvia in 1995,
which represents a decrease of 45 percent in  comparison  with
1994, according to the Statistical Bureau. (LETA)


ST PETERSBURG -- ESTONIAN DEFENSE MINISTER ANDRUS  OOVEL  TOOK
PART  in  the international conference "Security in the Baltic
Sea Region" 27-28,  according to the Defense Ministry's  press
service.  Mr.  Oovel  made  a  report  at the first day of the
conference,  which was chaired by Danish Defense Minister Hans
Haekkerup.  Mr. Oovel devoted his attention to Russia's aim of
changing the Baltic Sea's legal status to a mare clausum.  The
conference  was  attended  by  Russian Deputy Foreign Minister
Sergei Krylov,  Finnish Foreign Minister Tarja Halonen,  Mayor
of St.  Petersburg Anatoly Sobchak, and Norwegian Secretary of
State Siri Bjerke. (ETA).

BALTIC SEA  REGION  --  More  cargo passed through the Latvian
port of Ventspils in 1995 than through any other port  of  the
Baltic Sea. Cargo Handled (in millions of tons in 1995):
Ventspils 29.6,  Kotka 8.4,  Gdansk 18,  Gdynia 7.6,  Szczecin
15.5, Riga 7.4,  Tallinn 13,  Hamina 5.3, Klaipeda 12.7, Turku
3.5, Helsinki  10.2,  Kaliningrad  3.5,  St.  Petersburg   10,
Liepaja 1.4, (SEnumileht)

Resources: Transboundary news bulletin
_______________________________________________________________

BALTIC SEA STATES WRAP UP SUMMIT ON COOPERATION

VISBY/SWEDEN
Government leaders  of  the  11  Baltic  Sea nations concluded
their first ever summit here today with a declaration  calling
for stability, prosperity and solidarity in the region.

In the  declaration,  member  countries  of the Council of the
Baltic Sea States (CBSS) agreed on a range of  initiatives  to
bring about cooperation and integration in the region.

The countries  are  facing  a  unique  opportunity to make the
Baltic Sea region prosperous, stable and safe, it said.

Government leaders called on business  and  industry  to  help
bring   about  an  economic  boom  in  the  region  and  urged
international financial institutions to step up  participation
in funding infrastructure and economic development.

They agreed  to reinforce cooperation between police,  border,
customs,  immigration and coast guard  authorities  to  ensure
citizens' security and combat organized crime.

The leaders  also  agreed  to  intensify cooperation on energy
supply,  nuclear  safety,  nuclear  waste  disposal  and   the
environment. The Baltic Sea is one of the most polluted in the
world.

The summit  also  added  its  support  for  Estonia,   Latvia,
Lithuania and Poland's membership of the European Union (EU).

A wide  range  of issues from the environment to democracy and
international cooperation  were  covered  during  the  two-day
summit  held  on the island of Gotland off the southeast coast
of Sweden.

The CBSS,  set up  in  Copenhagen,  Denmark  in  1992,  groups
Sweden,  Finland,  Russia, Estonia, Latvia, Lithuania, Poland,
Germany,  Denmark,  Norway and Iceland. It has close relations
with the European Union.

May 5, 1996
_______________________________________________________________

GERMANS OFFICIALS BRACE FOR VIOLENCE OVER NUCLEAR SHIPMENT

* EDITORIAL: we disagree with Reuters, but that's whats  offi-
cials says. Useful to know. Some of people prepared this issue
are supporting german anti-nuke protests completely.

BONN, Reuters

German officials on Monday appealed for calm  but  braced  for
more  violence from anti-nuclear activists ahead of a shipment
of nuclear waste due to arrive by rail from France this week.

The train,  the first of some 110  due  to  carry  radioactive
waste  from  a  French reprocessing plant back to Germany over
the next eight years,  is  expected  to  reach  a  medium-term
storage unit in northern Germany on Wednesday.

Its impending  arrival  has  galvanised  opponents  of nuclear
energy who have sabotaged rail lines and clashed with police.

"I ask all citizens  to  distance  themselves...from  criminal
activity  and  to  show  understanding  for  the police," said
Ulrike Wolff-Gebhardt,  who heads the local government in  the
northern town of Lueneburg, near the Gorleben storage depot.

A Greenpeace spokeswoman in Germany said French officials were
apparently about to load the train with special containers for
the 1,500-km (900-mile) trip from the reprocessing plant in La
Hague to the storage site in Gorleben.

The environmentalist group was expecting the load to arrive in
Lower  Saxony  state  where  the  site  is  located  early  on
Wednesday, she added.

There was no official confirmation of  this,  but  the  German
government has said the shipment will arrive within days.

An administrative  court  in Lueneburg reinstated an immediate
ban on protests around the Gorleben depot that a  lower  court
had curbed as too restrictive last week.

Around 3,000  police  officers  and border guards clashed with
hundreds of protesters near Gorleben overnight.

Lueneburg police said they detained 89 people after about  300
militants,  some of them masked, attacked officers with stones
and flares near the depot,  120 km (75 miles) east of Hanover.
They may be charged with breach of the peace.

Two policemen  were  slightly injured and four police vehicles
were damaged.

In the eastern state of Brandenburg,  two  locomotives  pulled
down  overhead  power cables along a two-km (one-mile) stretch
when  they  ploughed  into  grappling  hooks  and  lines  that
activists had draped over the wires, police said.

Anti-nuclear leaflets were found scattered nearby.

The incidents  were the latest in a series of protests against
the shipment.  Anti-nuclear activists have  sabotaged  railway
lines  by sawing through rails,  setting fire to signal boxes,
toppling a power line and making bomb threats.

Thousands of protesters demonstrated peacefully near the depot
on  Saturday  but  police  stepped  up security after speakers
called for campaigners to use  "all  means"  to  hold  up  the
container carrying the waste.

Hans-Ruediger Hesse, spokesman for the anti-extremist watchdog
agency in Lower Saxony state,  told German radio that militant
leftists,  in  search of a theme to win more supporters,  were
exploiting the anti-nuclear protests.

"Militant leftist extremists in Germany have taken on the  job
of preventing the castor transport," he said, referring to the
containers that hold the nuclear waste.

He said extremists had not only called for sabotage  but  also
provided  instructions  on how to build and lay bombs to wreck
the rails.

"This makes the scene extremely dangerous," he said.

Last year  14,000  police  were  deployed  when  thousands  of
anti-nuclear  demonstrators  and  residents held mass protests
when the first consignment of nuclear waste was  delivered  to
the Gorleben depot in April from a German reactor. (May 6)
