CONTENTS
     
BALTIC NEWS
     
Publication
ANTINUCLEAR CAMPAIGN   PUBLISHES  THE  MOST  SUCCEESSFULL  AND
UNIQUE BOOK OF PRESENT DAYS ABOUT "MAYAK" NUCLEAR FACILITY
     
Campaign
RUSSIAN CITIZENS   ARE  FIGHTING  A  US  CO-FOUNDED  PLANT  TO
REPROCESS LIQUID ROCKET FUEL
_______________________________________________________________

RUSSIA-BALTICS-POLAND -- THE HIGHWAY PROJECT  "VIA  HANSEATIC"
between  St.  Petersburg and Gdansk,  which would link several
former Hanseatic cities,  is to be supported by funds from the
European  Union.  More than 900 million ECU are expected to be
invested in project before 1999. This project would complement
"Via Baltica", which is to lead between Helsinki, Tallinn, and
Warsaw. (Vecher. Peterburg)

TALLINN - CORRUPTION CHARGES AGAINST THE ESTONIAN MINISTER  OF
ENVIRONMENT  VILLU  REILJAN  have  been dropped after a failed
vote of no-confidence by the Estonian Riigikogu on May 13. The
charges  came  as a result of the state Audit Office's release
of information that Mr. Reiljan conducted a business deal with
a  company  in  which  he  owned stock while he was working as
director  of  Luua  Higher  Forestry  School.  Besides   being
illegal,  the  deal  also concerned live trees sold as timber.
The KMU faction described the vote as political  and  declared
its  intent  to oppose it.  The Reform Party faction supported
the vote,  explaining is as a matter of conscience rather then
a political issue. (Postimees)

LENINGRAD OBLAST  --  A  NEW  LEGISLATIVE  BILL "ON THE USE OF
FOREST IN LENINGRAD OBLAST" represents  a  serious  threat  to
forest  in the region,  argued members of Greenpeace and local
non-government  environmental   organizations   at   a   press
conference  in  St.  Petersburg.  Acceptance of the bill would
result in the liquidation of control over the territory by the
Federal  Agency  of Timber and therefore the introduction of a
monopolistic right of commercial access to that timber by  the
oblast administration. (Nevskoe Vremiia, 14 May)

ST. PETERSBURG  --  FINES  FOR  POLLUTION  IN  THE  CITY  HAVE
RECENTLY BEEN INCREASED BY 10O PERCENT.  The increase  is  the
result   of  the  necessity  to  increase  revenues  for  city
construction projects to protect the environment, according to
the  Direction of Environmental Protection in St.  Petersburg.
The increase in fines are aimed  at  those  enterprises  which
pollute the atmosphere and groundwater. (Delovoi Peterburg, 14
May)

SOSNOVY BOR,  RUSSIA -- A  RESTRICTED  SAFETY  ZONE  has  been
established  at  the  distance of one kilometer in the Gulf of
Finland from the water outlet from the  nuclear  power  plant.
Boats, including pleasure and fishing, will now be banned from
entry into this restricted area.  Fishermen in  the  area  are
reported  to have made particularly large catches in this area
in the past due to the warm water discharged  from  the  plant
into the Gulf in this location. (SPb Vedomosti, May)

DAUGVPILS, LATVIA  --  CONSTRUCTION  OF  A  NEW HYDRO ELECTRIC
POWER PLANT on the Daugava River in the vicinity of Daugavpils
is   under   consideration.   Scientists   from   the  Latvian
Environmental Protection center,  members of the  organization
Daugavas  Loki,  and  local  farmers  are  all  opposed to the
project.  They argue that environmental damage will exceed any
economic  advantage  gained  from  the new power plant.  Local
government  and  business  interests  are  in  favor  of   the
construction  to provide relatively inexpensive electric power
and to create new job opportunities in the region.  (LETA,  14
May)

STOCKHOLM --  The  first  BALLERINA (BALtic Sea Region On-line
Environmental  Information  Resources  for  INternet   Access)
workshop  will be held 13-14 June.  The aim of the workshop is
to discuss and provide guidelines on how to make the BALLERINA
initiative  the  gateway  for environmental information on the
Baltic Sea region on the Internet. BALLERINA will be developed
as a cooperative effort among agencies and organizations which
produce and disseminate environmental  information  about  the
Baltic  Sea  and its drainage area.  Contact Sindre Langaas at
langaas@grida.no,  or Camilla Wahlman for practical  questions
about the workshop at cwa@environ.se,  tel. +46-8-6981426, fax
+46-8-6981584. (BALLERINA, May)

PARNU, ESTONIA - A MEETING OF ESTONIAN, LATVIAN AND LITHUANIAN
PRIME MINISTERS is to take place in Parnu on May 22.  The main
issues to be tackled are free trade agreements in  the  Baltic
area and Via Baltica highway project. The prime ministers have
agreed that the free trade agreement  should  be  extended  to
agricultural produce. (ETA, May 13)
_______________________________________________________________

ANTINUCLEAR CAMPAIGN PUBLISHES THE MOST SUCCESSFULL AND UNIQUE
BOOK OF PRESENT DAYS ABOUT "MAYAK" NUCLEAR FACILITY

MOSCOW,- There  is  just  published  the  most informative and
unique book about  "Mayak"  nuclear  facility  is  located  in
Chelyabinsk. "Mayak"  was  working  for  a years to produce as
plutonium as the nuclear fuel for USSR defensive complex.  The
book is  published by the anti-nuclear campaign in ex-USSR (PO
Box 211,  121019 Moscow,  Russia,  tel/fax  298-3087,  e-mail:
ed@cci.glasnet.ru). The  author  of the book is a Moscow based
scientist and journalist Vladislav Larin.

The book of Vladislav Larin is devoted to the first enterprise
of  military  nuclear-industrial  complex,  where nuclear bomb
plutonium production took place.  The author had made  it  his
aim  to  collect together all accessible information about the
Mayak enterprise: about its history, technological scheme, the
essence and the consequences of the accidents which took place
at  the  combine,  about the levels of radiation contamination
and the  consequences of the accidents for people health - for
both he personnel of the combine and the  inhabitants  of  the
region...  This  book  can  fully serve as a reference book on
this problem for today.  (L.Popova - director of the Centre of
nuclear  ecology and energy policy of the Social-Environmental
Union).

....the books like this one are important - they don't allow to
forget  about the bygone mistakes.  The tragedy of the "Mayak"
is our common misfortune and we will be able  to  improve  the
situation  only  in  case if we profoundly realize the sources
and the  details of this problem.  (A.Yablokov - corresponding
member of the Academy of Sciences of Russia,  chairman of  the
Joint Commission  on Ecological Safety of the Security Council
of Russia.)

The book is written on the basis of a large number of recently
declassified literary sources and personal impressions of  the
author from visiting the "Mayak" enterprise. The volume of the
book is 175 pages,  it consists of the spacious  introduction,
five  chapters,  supplements and the list of literature of 109
titles.  The introduction is devoted  to  examination  of  the
peculiarities of location and functioning of the "Mayak", here
its technological scheme is considered in detail. The question
of the first chapter is the causes and the consequences of the
three large t catastrophes at the "Mayak".  The second chapter
is  devoted  to  radiation situation after the accidents.  The
third - to the health problems of personnel  of  the  combine.
The  fourth  - to the medical consequences of the "Mayak" work
for the population f the region.  The fifth - to an  influence
of  the irradiation of parents on posterior generations health
condition.
_______________________________________________________________

RUSSIAN CITIZENS   ARE  FIGHTING  A  US  CO-FOUNDED  PLANT  TO
REPROCESS LIQUID ROCKET FUEL

Citizens of  the  Russian  town of Sergei Posad are fighting a
government plan to build a U.S.  co-funded plant in their town
to  reprocess  thousands  of  tons  of heptyl,  a highly toxic
chemical used as liquid rocket fuel.
There are unwanted stocks  of  heptyl  (dimethylhydrazine)  at
various  military  installations  around Russia where missiles
and rockets are made and launched.  Russia  continued  to  use
liquid  rocket fuel long after America switched to solid fuel,
largely because it was cheaper.
   However, heptyl   is  highly  toxic,  carcinogenic,  easily
soluble in water (which means in the event of a  leak  it  can
spread quickly and easily) and, of course, very volatile.
   Estimates of how much heptyl is stored in  Russia's  former
"closed  cities,"  the  Soviet-era  secret  towns  like Sergei
Posad, in Soviet days known as Zagorsk, range from 50,000 tons
to 150,000 tons.
   At the  Scientific  Research  Institute  of  Chemical   and
Construction  Machines  (SRICCM) based in Sergei Posad,  there
are over 100 tons  of  heptyl  in  storage.  And  if  the  new
reprocessing  facility  is installed,  at least another 10,000
tons will be brought there from the other sites in Russia.
   Hundreds of  signatures  have  been  collected on petitions
protesting about the plans.
   "The people of this town object to these plans, and rightly
<a name=L10001></a><a href=#L10002>so</a>," says the mayor of Sergei Posad,  Vasili Goncharov, who is
leading  the  protests.  "We  already  have enough problems to
contend with in this area,  including a radon depository and a
testing site for storage of pesticides and household waste."

Heptyl disposal is not just a Russian problem. Other countries
with missile and space  programmes  also  have  problems  with
ageing  stocks  of  heptyl  since  <a name=L10002></a><a href=#L10003>so</a>  far  no  technology for
reprocessing has proved to be  environmentally  friendly.  The
facility to be built in Sergei Posad,  some 70 kilometers from
Moscow,  will  be  constructed  with  U.S.   aid   under   the
Congress-backed Nunn-Lugar technical assistance program.  This
has raised fears that foreign heptyl will also be  brought  in
for treatment.
   "The reprocessing project is tied to deliveries  of  heptyl
from  abroad,  especially  from  the  United  States," alleges
Goncharov.  "This  is  part  of  a  wider  policy  of  dumping
dangerous  and  harmful  production  processes  on  us here in
Russia."
   Henryk Matysyak,  Director  of  SRICCM,  absolutely  denies
this. "Only Russian heptyl will be processed in Sergei Posad,"
he  insists.  He  points  out  that  there  are plans to build
similar facilities in two other Russian towns where heptyl  is
stored.
   "This is part of a five-year project and a special place in
the  plans is given to ecological safety," he says.  He points
out that his institute has been working with heptyl  for  many
years and is well aware of all the precautions that need to be
taken.
   "We have  been  dealing  with  this chemical since the days
when it was carried about in buckets," he says. He is proud of
the reservoir that the Institute has built for the town, which
contains water that is originally contaminated by heptyl.
   "All the   water   is  filtered  through  our  purification
installations and is <a name=L10003></a><a href=#L10004>so</a> clean that our children can  bathe  in
it. My grandchildren and I myself swim in it and crayfish live
there."
   Matysyak is  certain that the town's people will eventually
accept the facility.  He cited earlier  protests  against  the
dismantling of naval missiles, which rapidly abated.
   "Given the high level of unemployment today  and  the  fact
that the reprocessing project will create good jobs,  I do not
expect  the  opposition  to  last  long,"  he  explains.  "The
facility  will  give  workers the opportunity of earning up to
500,000 rubles  ($100)  a  month  with  no  payment  arrears."
Average    wages   paid   by   cash-strapped   employers   are
significantly lower than this in Russia.
   There has  been no protest at all from Institute employees,
said Matysyak.  "Workers here are not concerned.  They have  a
sensible view of the project and understand the realities."
   Viewed in  the  wider  context,  however,  the  project  is
causing  concern to environmentalists who fear that Russia may
rapidly be becoming the world's toxic waste dump.
   Last year the environmental commission of Russia's Security
Council found that over 2,000 tons of  dangerous  wastes  from
abroad were being brought into the country every day.  In many
cases  the  imports  were  carried  out  on  the  pretext   of
recycling, the commission warned.
   As to the reprocessed heptyl,  there are plans to use it in
the manufacture of dyes.
