<a name=L10000></a><a href=#L10001>So</a>: U-eeu
From: V.THURN@LINK-K.comlink.apc.org
Newsgroups: reg.eeurope
Subject: Osteuropa Rundbrief BUND Teil 1, east west newsletter part 1
Date: 03 Jun 1996 14:47:00

East-West-Newsletter BUND, part 1
Rundbrief Osteuropa BUND, Teil 1

Bund fr Umwelt- und Naturschutz Deutschland
11. Rundbrief des Arbeitskreises Osteuropa, 15. Juni 1996
Redaktion: Erdmuthe Arnold, Valentin Thurn, David Oberhuber.


SITZUNG DES ARBEITSKREISES OSTEUROPA
am 3.Februar 1996 in Koeln von 11 bis 17 Uhr

Wie angekuendigt veroeffentlichen wir im Folgenden die Referate
der letzten Sitzung des BUND-Arbeitskreises Osteuropa in Koeln,
die aus Platzgruenden in Rundbrief Nr. 10 noch nicht erschienen
sind. Im letzten Rundbrief erschienen bereits die Referate von
Astrid Sahm ueber die neuen staatlichen Tschernobyl-Programme
von Belarus, Russland und der Ukraine (S.10), von Manfred Sapper
zu den internationalen Aktivitaeten der russischen Atomindustrie
(S. 28), von Karl Kerschgens ueber humanitaere Massnahmen nach
Tschernobyl aus Deutschland (S. 13), von Valentin Thurn ueber
eine PR-Reise der Atomwirtschaft nach Tschernobyl (S. 4).

Hier nun die Zusammenfassung des Referats von Mara Silina ueber
die Taetigkeit des Bruesseler Bueros von "Friends of the Earth
International" und des Vortrags von Michael Meyer ueber die
Taetigkeit von ECEAT, das "European Center for Eco Agro
Tourism", in Osteuropa. Die schriftliche Fassung des Berichts
von HEIKE DRILLISCH UND JOHANNES ROHR ueber die AUSWIRKUNGEN DER
OEL- UND GASFOERDERUNG IN SIBIRIEN AUF DIE IN DIESER REGION
LEBENDEN INDIGENEN VOELKER befindet sich im Russland-Teil dieses
Rundbriefs auf Seite 20.

Mara Silina: Friends Of the Earth Europe East-West Programme:

Plans 1996 (draft version for discussions during the FOEE Annual
Meeting in Ohrid, FYRo Macedonia and emended for the BUND
working groups's meeting in Cologne)

Introduction

In 1988 Friends of the Earth International (FOEI) started a
special programme on Central and Eastern Europe (CCE). Its
purpose was to give support to and cooperate with the newly
emerging independent CEE environmental movements. The programme
was initiated by FOE-Italy, but since 1990 the coordination is
done by FOE-Europe (FOEE). Since then FOEE had a staff for this
purpose of two persons, one (John Hontelez) working from the
Brussels office, the other (Mara Silina) was working from an
office in Bratislava (Slovakia), specially set up for this
programme. Following the decision of FOEE Annual General Meeting
(AGM) in FRankfurt 1993 we have closed FOE East office in
Bratislava since June 1994 and Mara Silina is now working from
FOEE office in Brussels. Furthermore, John Hontelez has become a
policy coordinator of FOEE since August 1st, 1994, and has
stopped working for the East-West Programme.

FOEE has ten members in the following CEE and New Independent
States (NIS) (fruehere Sowjetunion) countries:

Bulgaria				National Movement of Ecoglasnost;

Czech Republic			Hnuti Duha / Rainbow Movement;

Estonia				Estonian Green Movement;

Georgia				Green Movement of Georgia;

Hungary				National Society of Conservationists;

Latvia				VAK / Environmental Protection Club of Latvia;

Lithuania				Lithuanian Green Movement;

Macedonia, Former Yug. Rep. of	DEM / Ecological Movement of
Macedonia;

Poland				PKE / Polish Ecological Club;

Ukraine				Zelenyi Svit / Green World.

The objectives of the programme are as follows:

General Support and strengthening of the environmental movement
in CEE;

Stimulation and development of East-East and East-West
cooperation especially leading to campaigns;

Liaison - political lobbying on the European level with special
emphasis on CEE environment;

Financial clearinghouse to identify potential funding for
projects and campaigns.

This programme should be seen as evolving plan on necessities
and opportunities elements may be changed, added, deleted
throughout the year in close cooperation with FOE groups in the
region. 

Programme 1996: (Final version will be produced after the
workshop on the programme in Ohrid)

1.A.	General Support and strengthening of the environmental
movement:

1.A.1	PHARE/TACIS Democracy Projects (in progress):

Phare and Tacis are the programmes of the European Union (EU) to
support the CEE and NIS countries. Two projects in the frame of
Phare Democracy Projects will go on till July 1996 for Lithuania
and till September 1996 for Poland. FOEE is the EU partner for
both of them which means that we have a role to advise our
groups on the implementation of projects and organise a
western-groups' participation where needed as well as to
communicate with EU about these projects. Until March 1996 FOEE
is involved in the Tacis Democracy Programme for Green Movement
in Georgia.

1.A.2	PHARE/TACIS Democracy Projects (new ones):

During the year there will be another opportunity (ies) to
introduce projects for Phare/Tacis Democracy Projects (the first
deadline will be April 30th) and therefore the first ideas from
the groups have been collected and wherever possible will be
discussed during the Annual meeting. For developing these
projects I can think about two different things at the same time:

follow up proposals for the groups involved in the past. This
could include expanding the existing programme or choosing a
special campaigns focus, like the introduction of principles of
"Sustainable Europe" Programme.

similar projects as before for our members which didn't manage
to be involved in the previous ones.

Phare/Tacis Democracy Programme is only one programme we have
used <a name=L10001></a><a href=#L10002>so</a> far. But there certainly will be an opportunity to
participate in Phare Partnership Programme (deadline 29th,
1996), LIEN (deadline April 30th, 1996), RTD (Research and
Technological Development - deadline February29th, 1996)
programme and may be some more. More information will be
provided. Groups which have expressed their interest to develop
projects in the frame of Phare/Tacis Democracy and Phare
Partnership Programmes are FOE Hungary, FOE Bulgaria, FOE
Macedonia and FOE Ukraine.

1.B.	Information / Education:

"New items for East and Central Europe":

New Items II will be finished by the end of March 1996. But as I
have an indication that the project has been and is very useful
I am allready thinking about the new series of similar
publications. This means work on two things: issues for the next
publications and fundraising for these issues. Issues, which
have been mentioned by some of our groups include: WB activities
in CEE; Enlargement of the EU towards CEE and the consequences
of this integration; Environmental Action Plan for CEE (EAP) and
NEAP's and how to use these things in environmental policy
making; Sustainable Europe - experience from CEE; Sustainable
agriculture; Western assistance to the environment of CEE;
Environmental consumerism; Hazardous waste; Sustainable
transport; Sustainable use of water; Sustainable energy.

Like the first series of "New Items", the booklets would be
practical and instrumental for further reading as well as
campaining and will be published in seven languages. This might
change depending from funding. <a name=L10002></a><a href=#L10003>So</a> far we have had six issues in
one Year's time (or close to that). What I feel while manageing
the project is that it's too much of a burden to you and me and
we may be can reduce it to four issues a year. Concerning
fundraising - we might get some money from the EC, Charity Know
How or someone else and I can start doing this part of the work
as soon as we agree on the issues.

2.	Stimulation and development of East-East and East-West
cooperation:

I am just listing some things which are ongoing (agriculture,
sustainable Europe), some where we have done something but did
not go further with our joint activities (Black Sea). Some
things have been mentioned during our meetings (Baltic Sea) and
somewhere we have to define FOEE's role more precisely (MDB).

2.1 Agriculture: For two years we are working together with
Georgian Greens on a sustinable agriculture project supported by
the European Commission (Phare). The projects are focussed on
the promotion and practical implementation on ecological
agriculture and raising of awareness of the public about the
advantages of its products. (The project descriptions, for which
at least 20% of the funds need to come from other sources than
the EC, are available.)

2.2 Baltic Sea: Needs further discussions with FOEI Ocean
Foundation and FOE groups concerned.

2.3 Black Sea: We will build upon our inititiatives and the
contacts developed with UNDP and TACIS for the following
activities:

Regular distribution of relevant information to NGOs around the
Black Sea and in the Danube River Basin;

possible reviving the Black sea coalition we initiated in 1992
(if needed);

application with the Black Sea Convention Secretariat in
Istanbul for observer status with the convention after agreement
with the relevant FOEI-groups;

Assisting in monitoring and influencing the GEF programme on the
Black Sea, the implementation of the Black sea Convention and
Economical Cooperation of Black sea countries, raising funds for
this purpose with UNDP and TACIS;

Stimulating cooperation, public awareness and clean up campaigns
around the Blaclk Sea, again with funds of UNDP and TACIS.

2.4 Sustainable Europe in CEE: Needs to be dicussed with the
groups as they should start campaigning in their own countries.

2.5 MDB campaign / network in CEE: The initiative to start
campaign on MDBs in CEE has been brought up by several FOE
groups in the region which had their meeting in Brno,
mid-December 1994. A proposal for regular netwokring and
fundraising is under preperation. FOEE East-west programme is
prepared to assist.

2.6 Chernobyl Ten Years Anniversary.

2.7 Balkan Cooperation.

3.	Liaison - political lobbying on the European level:

3.1 EAP for Central and Eastern Europe: (see a seperate document
by Mara silina and John hontelez "the Sofia Conference and
beyond"). This is an issue where FOEE (joint project with
Milieukontakt Oost-Europa) has been involved as an international
organisation and had its political role play. And we also have
tried to involve our memebr-groups more actively. We will have a
half-day workshop in Ohrid just before FOEE AGM where we can
discuss all major issues in this respect. Briefly, the Sofia
follow-up activities will include:

Implementation of the EAP and development of NEAP's;

Focus on policy reforms and integration of environmental
concerns into economic / social policies;

Environmental financing - further work on mechanisms to be used
in CEEC;

Negotiations with NGOs/EAP TF/PPC on project development(s);

Quality of the assistance programmes (could be linked with the
New Items booklet);

Our Sustainable Europe to be linked with the integrated policies
and post Sofia;

New Items booklet on these issues.

3.2 Enlargement of the EU: This will become an issue very soon
in all associate countries, therefore we should be prepared for
broader debates. Just a few things to be mentioned to start
working with:

Working with the documents from the EU and provoking debates in
the countries. Introducing these agreements to environmental
organisations (debates in countries, workshop(s), New Items
booklet, international workshop etc.);

May be to organise a workshop in Brussels for CEE
environmentalists on the enlargement;

Comments on the documents - issue by issue on the main areas -
environment, transport, agriculture, energy etc.

Setting up a project and raising funbds collectively for itto
have a research unit for White Paper for CEEC environment;

Working closely with the Technical Assistance Information
Exchange office in the Commission.

Concerning the last objective for East-West programme about the
fundraising clearinghouse - some small things have happened but
not on regular basis and not much outside the EU. <a name=L10003></a><a href=#L10004>So</a>, there is
still a space to improve and I would like to spend some time on
that.

Annex: Concrete activities from 1990:

Support to Greenway, the CEE environmental activists network;

Visit to Brussels (Nov 1990): a nine day seminar in Brussels
about the European Community for CEE activists;

EBRD-seminars and discussions with the management of the
European Bank for Reconstr. and Develop. (EBRD) (Nov 1990 -
March 1992): to influence the general character of the
operations of this new Multilateral Bank.

Activities to influence the policy of EBRD by disseminating
information and initiating campaigns for concrete (changes of)
desicions by the EBRD (ongoin): This work is mainly done by FOE
England/Wales/Northern Ireland;

A conference about Nuclear Energy and Energy conservation (June
1991), followed by a vast document with the speeches in six
languages.

Waste Workhop (June 1991) and follow up activities, concentrated
on protecting and improving existing systems of re-use and
re-cycling in CEE.

Substantial input in the debate about "Guiding Principles On The
Environment, Industry and Investment Decisions in Central and
Eastern Europe" coordinated by the European Commission.

West Goes East (January 1992): A major conference about western
investments and how to prevent possible negative environmental
effects in CEE. This project included eleven CEE country reports
about western investments.

Stimulating the involvement of CEE-groups in the EC-oriented
campaign for a good Packaging-Directive (ongoin): This is mainly
done by FOE Netherlands.

Initiatives to coordinate and stimulate activities to protect
and clean up the Black Sea (ongoing).

New Items (ongoing): publications of booklets about new,
relevant items for environmentalists in CEE in their own
languages.

The co-production of "Russisn Roulette" (1992-1993):a document
to protect against the western investments in the continuation
of the nuclear option in CEE and to present energy conservation
alernatives.

Co-organisation of the Vienna conference on the Ecological
Reconstruction of CEE (Nov 1992).

Coordination of a project to stregthen the local groups
structure of five of our CEE-members in cooperation with five of
our Westeuropean members in the Framework of the Phare Democracy
Programme (1993-1994).

Active involvement in the NGOactivities in the preperations of
the Environmental Action Plan for CEE, adopted at the
Pan-European Environmental Ministers Conference in Luzern,
Switzerland, Apr. 1993.

Organisation and preperation in governmental and NGO activities
towards the next Pan-European Environmental ministers Conference
in Sofia, 1995.

Preperation and organisation (together with Milieukontakt
Oost-Europa) of the NGO consultation "NGO Involvement in
Environmental Policy Making in CEE" in Leszno (Poland), June
1994.

Preperation and organization (together with Milieukontakt
Oosteuropa) of the meeting of resource persons/experts for Sofia
'95 preperations, May 1995.

Preperation and organization of the NGO Strategy meeting in
Groznjan (Croatia) June 1995.

Preperation and organization (together with Milieukontakt
Oosteuropa) of the meeting on financial instruments in Brussels,
July 1995.

Active involvement and participation in organisation of the NGO
Parallel Conference and participation in Ministerial Conference
in Sofia, October 1995.

Friends of the Earth Coordination Group Europe (FOE Europe),
Mara Silina, Min. Elandstraat 27, NL-6523 CS Nijmegen, T
0031-80/236512, F 0031-80/604361, e-mail: mkontakt@gn.apc.org

Michael Meyer, ECEAT - das European Center for Eco Agro Tourism.

Das nachstehend becshrieben Projekt ist besser bekannt unter dem
Namen STEF-Projekt (Sustainable Tourism on Ecological Farms).
Mit dieser Initiative soll eine lanfristige Unterstuetzung der
oekologisch wirtschaftenden Landwirte durch nachhaltigen
Tourismus gewaehrleistet werden. Die Ziele des Projekts sind:

Foerderung des oekologischen Landbaus durch nachhaltigen
Tourismus;

Aktiver Umwelt- und Naturschutz in Europa;

Oeko-Sensibilisierung der Landwirte sowie der Touristen;

Schaffung eines europaeischen Netzwerks;

Training der involvierten Landwirte und der nationalen
ECEAT-Vertreter;

Entwicklung von entsprechenden Marketingstrategien.

Das Instrument zur erreichung der Ziele liegt im praktischen
Ansatz. Durch die Foerderung von Eigeninitiativen der Landwirte
und deren Erfolg in ihrer Region wird ein Schneeballeffekt
erzielt. Die Existenzsicherung durch den Nebenerwerb mit
Tourismus ist zwar nicht in allen Faellen erfolgversprechend,
aber falls doch finden sich in der Region viele Nachahmer. Die
Arbeitsschritte sind zumindest in den osteuropaeischen Laendern
gleich:

Aufbau einer unabhaenigen nationalen Koordinierungsstelle;

Training der meist ehrenamtlichen Nationalkoordinatoren;

Aufbau von regionalen Kontaktbueros;

Unterstuetzung der Landwirte durch Information, Training und der
Beschaffung von oeffentlichen Mitteln zum Ausbau der Hoefe;

Entwicklung eines Marketingkonzepts fuer die Region und
europaweit;

Ergebnissicherung, Erfolgskontrolle und Korrektur.

In den weteuropaeischen Laendern bestehen meist schon relativ
starke Initiativen, auch wenn sie nicht oekologisch ausgerichtet
sind. In diesem Falle gilt es erst recht, eine positive Politik
zu betreiben, die Existenz der Oeko-Landwirte zu sichern und die
entsprechende Lobbyarbeit zu ermoeglichen. Das Projekt begann
vor vier Jahren in Polen mit ein paar Hoefen, mittlerweile haben
sich in 15 Laendern Europas ueber 600 Biohoefe zu dieser
Initiative ziusammengechlossen. Fuer jedes Land wird in den
Niderlanden eine Broschuere mit einer Beschreibung des Landes,
der Gegebenheiten und der einzelnen Hoefe gedruckt. Im Jahr 1994
wurden 5.000 dieser Broschueren verkauft und etwa 4.000
Touristen besuchten die Hoefe mit 10.000 Uebernachtungen. Fuer
1996 wird eine Kooperation mit Reiseveranstaltern angestrebt, da
mittlerweile ganze Doerfer in den Broschueren anbieten. fuer die
Zukunft wird in Erwaegung gezogen, die Projektidee auf den
gesamten Bereich der laendlichen Region auszuweiten, die dann
unter anderem kleinere Hotels, Angebote von Naturschutzgebieten
und oeffentlichen Einrichtungen, wie Jugendherbergen umfasst.
Die Vorbedingungen ist bei allen jedoch die oekologische
Ausrichtung. Deshalb arbeitet die ECEAT seit diesem Jahr an
Umweltqualitaetskriterien fuer ein nachhaltiges Tourismusangebot.

ECEAT - European Centre for Eco Agro Tourism, Deutschland;
Michael Meyer, Nationaler Koordinator, Kochstrasse 15a, 50354
Huerth.

ARMENIEN

Die Union der Gruenen Armeniens wird in ihrer Arbeit behindert.

von Sylvia Gressier, Februar 1996 - Infolge der widrigen
Lebensbedingungen (kein Strom, kein Wasser und keine Heizung),
mit denen die Armenier zur Zeit zu kaempfen haben, ist das Thema
Umweltschutz bei der Bevoelkerung natuerlich kleingeschrieben.
Die Nachricht von der Reparatur und dem Wiederanschluss des
Blocks Nr. 11 im Atomkraftwerk Medzamor unweit von Jerewan im
Herbst vergangenen Jahres wurde von grossen Teilen der
Bevoelkerung in Armenien mit der Hoffnung auf Strom und damit
auf die Normalisierung der Lebenssituation nach fast acht Jahren
ohne bzw. nur mit stundenweiser Elektrizitaetsversorgung
verbunden.

Die schwierige oekonomische Situation, in der das Land steckt,
tut das Seinige, die Bevoelkerung fuer Fragen des Umweltschutzes
voellig unsensibel zu machen. Die einzige NGO, die sich zur Zeit
diesem Thema widmet, firmiert unter der Bezeichnung Union der
Gruenen Armeniens. Sie existiert bereits seit 1930 als Bewegung
einiger Einzelpersonen, die auf die Austrocknung des Sewan-Sees
aufgrund eines Wasserkraftwerkes hinwiesen. In der Zeit der
Glasnost fanden sich mehrere aktive Gruppierungen, die im
Bereich Umweltschutz in Armenien aktiv waren und auf die
Freveltaten des sowjetischen Regimes aufmerksam machten.
Armeniens Wirtschaft bestand hauptsaechlich aus verarbeitender
Industrie. Chemiewerke und vor allem ein riesiges Kautschukwerk
in Jerewan verschmutzten die Luft in der Stadt stark, bevor die
Energieblockade einsetzte. Die armenischen Umweltschuetzer
schlossen sich 1989 zur Union der Gruenen Armeniens zusammen.

In einem Interview im Oktober 1995 berichtete der Praesident
dieser NGO, Hakop A. Sanarsajan, dass man sich zur Zeit vor
allem mit der Ausarbeitung eines Lebensmittelkontrollgesetzes
beschaeftige. Diese Arbeit sei jedoch ins Stocken geraten, da
das Geld fuer die Entlohnung der Fachleute, die an dem
Gesetzesentwurf gearbeitet haetten, ausgegangen sei. Auch fuer
den Bereich Abwasser und Abgase wolle die armenische Regierung
ein entsprechendes Gesetz einfuehren. Bei der Untersuchung
vergleichbarer Gesetze europaeischer Staaten sei die schwedische
Variante als Vorbild fuer Armenien als die geeigneteste erkannt
worden.

Ein Projekt, das von den USA mit 30.000 USD finanziert wird, ist
der Aufbau einer Biogasfabrik. Die Union der Gruenen Armeniens
hat sich u.a. der Verteilung von Informationsmaterial in Form
von Broschueren ueber diese Art der Energiegewinnung mit einer
Auflagenhoehe von 4.000 Exemplare angenommen.

Das Thema Nr. 1 der Umweltschuetzer Armeniens sei jedoch immer
noch der Kampf gegen den Wiederanschluss des Atomkraftwerkes
Medzamor, sagte Hakop Sanarsajan Diese Arbeit wird durch
offizielle Stellen behindert. <a name=L10004></a><a href=#L10005>So</a> haetten im Radio keine
Stellungnahmen gegen die Wiederherstellung des AKWs in Armenien
gesendet werden duerfen.

In diesem Zusammenhang beklagte sich der Leiter dieser NGO auch
allgemein ueber die Methoden der Regierung, die Arbeit der
Gruenen in der oeffentlichkeit Armeniens zu diskreditieren. In
den Zeitungen seien Artikel von Journalisten erschienen, denen
er zwar ein Interview gegeben haette, deren Inhalt aber
keineswegs mit dem Inhalt der Publikationen uebereinstimmte. In
ihnen beschuldige die Regierung die Gruenen, dass sie den Anlass
fuer die Schliessung von Fabriken gegeben haetten. Die Fabriken
stuenden jedoch in Wirklichkeit wegen der Energieblockade, dem
Mangel an Rohmaterial und aufgrund der allgemeinen
Wirtschaftskrise im Land still. Die Umweltschutz-NGO habe keine
Moeglichkeit, sich gegen diese Art von Anschuldigungen zur Wehr
zu setzen. Die Bevoelkerung wuerde <a name=L10005></a><a href=#L10006>so</a> jedoch gegen die Arbeit
die Gruenen aufgehetzt.

Diese unguenstige Einstellung gegenueber Umweltschuetzern in der
armenischen Bevoelkerung gepaart mit chronischem Geldmangel
lassen die Arbeit der Union der Gruenen Armeniens zu einem kaum
spuerbaren Element in der oeffentlichkeit dieses
Transkaukasus-Staates schrumpfen.

Uebrigens arbeitet zwar seit Dezember 1995 der Block Nr. 11 des
Atomkraftwerks Medzemor mit voller Kapazitaet, doch die
Situation in bezug auf die Stromversorgung in Jerewan hat sich
keinesfalls verbessert. Nach wie vor werden die Wohnungen der
Stadt nur nachts und das auch nicht durchgaengig und
regelmaessig mit Strom versorgt. Es kursieren Geruechte, dass
der armenische Staat die in Medzamor gewonnene Elektroenergie an
Georgien verkauft.

Kontakt: Friedrich-Ebert-Stiftung FES Armenien; Tumanjan Str.
38, Whg. 47; 375002 Jerewan; Republik Armenien; Tel. und Fax:
3742 - 532895; root@feaarm.arminco.com - Vertreterin der FES
Armenien: Naira Geworkjan

Water Level In Sevan Getting Stabilized

YEREVAN - The level of water in lake Sevan decreased by 6 cm
this year. Head of the Water resources department of the
Ministry of Environment Protection O.Kirakosian believes this is
a significant progress which shows that the level of water in
the lake is getting stabilized. The level has dropped by over
100 cm during the last two years. Stabilization of water level
is a result of virtually six times decrease of water drainage
from the lake this year. Mr. Kirakosian hoped that with full
operation of ANPP in 1996, drainage of water for power
production will completely stop. A corresponding decision has
been accepted by the government, and affirmed by the National
Council. Head of Water Resources department believes that the
level of water will gradually increase. It will probably grow by
150-200 cm when hydrotechnical constructions are built on the
river of Vorotan, to connect it with Arpa. Mr. Kirakosian added
that the World Bank allocated $ 485 thousands for the
development of ecological project for the lake.

Aragil Electronic News, Editor in Chief: V.Ganapetyan, tel:
+374-2-221296, E-mail: VAHE@ARMINCO.COM; VAHE@ARAGIL.ARMINCO.COM

BALTIKUM

New Road Through Baltic States

A 1,000-kilometre road linking Helsinki to Warsaw via the Baltic
states' capitals will be improved through a $180 million
project, the Nordic Investment Bank said on Monday. "The
Governments of the countries concerner are backing a $180
million investment programme, which in turn is closely connected
with the European Commission's commitment to faster and smoother
border crossing," the Nordic Investment Bank said. The
investments will allow the road link, called the Via Baltica, to
be upgraded over a five-year period into a smooth inyternational
link from its current status as separate national roads within
the five countries it crosses. Travellers in Estonia, Latvia and
Lithuania - which only emerged as independent states five years
ago - say roads linking the countries are dangerous and
unreliable. "For the first time, it's being treated as a
continuous transport route, with a single, intercountry
development programme", Nordic Investment Bank said in a
statement. A working party comprised of Estonian, Latvian,
Lithuanian, Finnish and Polish governments, the European
Commission, the World Bank, The European Investment Bank and the
European Bank for Reconstruction and Development set up the
programme. Money will be used to widen and upgrade 445
kilometres of the road and its bridges, improve city links and
place international road signs along the route. Border crossing
times will be greatly reduced, the bank said. Roadside services
such as hotels and restaurants will improve, mainly due to
private investments, the Bank said. Some 5,000 cars per day use
the road in the four adjacent countries, according to 1995
estimates, the working group said. The countries are linked to
Finland across the Gulf of Finland by a ferry link.

