<pre>SO: U-eeu
From: V.THURN@LINK-K.comlink.apc.org
Newsgroups: reg.eeurope
- - - -
by Victor Lukarevsky, Syunt Khasardagsky Nature Reserve - In
terms of numbers of large predator species, Turkmenistan
probably ranks first among Central Asian countries. Even in the
not-SO-DISTANT past, in the 1950s, there were eight species of
large predators, including two brown bear subspecies and two
lynx subspecies. In an instant, two species and two subspecies
- - - -
completely ceased. Instead, the major sources of food were
mountain sheep and boars, whose populations had increased to
approximately 250-270 and 170-200 individuals respectively.
Thus, as prey populations increased, SO did the leopard
population. This correlation is explained by the fact that the
leopard preys upon sick, injured, old, young, or otherwise unfit
- - - -
Soroki, but this new construction had to be frozen because of
the lack of means."

SO, did the whole story come to the end? But, where is the way
out? As scientists think, there is a way out. Firstly, one
should try and find subsidies for construction of modern group
- - - -
ecologically incompetent natural resources use, ignoring their
natural regeneration, primarily of seeds. All these factors
taken together caused the changes in green huge tracts of
forest, SO that the main forest forming species- oak- occupy now
only 51 per cent of the state forest fund area (for comparison
in 1964 it was 64 per cent). In addition, some tree species, not
- - - -
beginning, and with it, the forest fire season. It is the same
every year. There are a few notices in the 'highlights' section
of the newspaper, we all go ooohhhh!, take a bit of pause at the
figures, say "... and why is it that there are SO many forests
burning ..." and then forget the whole thing. Summer is in
general a difficult period. Summer is the season for forest
- - - -
pests that multiply at frightening rates. Last year there were
SO many moths that foresters simply shook their heads. As soon
as a pest took to 'working' the woods in Krasnoyarskii Krai,
700,000 hectares were lost. There is a need to fight forest
- - - -
all of 45 billion has been budgeted. Forest problems are the
same year in and year out, but the impact of modern economic
change on the forest is especially severe. For example, timber
sector enterprises are being SO ruthlessly privatized that many
of the controlling interests are being gobbled up by foreign
corporations. Take for example the Svetlorogskii, Balakhninskii,
- - - -
harvest of ash is out of control. Large volumes of timber are
being exported abroad. Employment conditions for those charged
with protecting the forest were also discussed. Criminal
activities in the forest are increasing, SO what can be said of
the 150,000 rouble salary of foresters who, in fact, don't see
any wages for months at a time. In addition, there is a
