East-West-Newsletter BUND, part 2
Rundbrief Osteuropa BUND, Teil 2

Bund fr Umwelt- und Naturschutz Deutschland
11. Rundbrief des Arbeitskreises Osteuropa, 15. Juni 1996
Redaktion: Erdmuthe Arnold, Valentin Thurn, David Oberhuber.


Turkmenistan
SILENCE IS NOT CONSENT 

by Bairam Allabaev - In independent (and now even neutral)
Turkmenistan, it is not safe to voice one's discontent with the
present order and the incompetence of the bureaucrats and
employees of the law enforcement agencies. In this former Soviet
republic, where the personality cult has attained its most
colorful incarnation with regard to President Saparmurat
Niyazov, those who are unhappy and those who hold divergent
viewpoints can easily be sent to a psychiatric hospital, be
announced criminal, or be declaimed with a variety of shameful
labels. All of the participants of last year's youth uprising in
the streets of Ashgabad found themselves detained and small
packages of narcotics stuck into their pockets. Such narcotics
possessions proved sufficient grounds for serious indictments
and detentions. Moreover, this mass demonstration was distorted
by the government-controlled media as nothing more than "an act
of hooliganistic drug addicts and alcoholics." These reports
only drew snickers from a population perfectly able to read
between the lines. (...) A resident of Dashkhovuz also recently
paid for his activity and openness. Khudaishukur Kalandarov, an
executive in a construction firm, could not remain silent any
longer in the face of Turkmenistan's lawlessness. He literally
buried the President's and the Regional Attorney's offices in
telegrams documenting the illegality of methods used with regard
to a fellow citizen, Tursun Matyazov, charged with felonies. He
waited for explanations in vain. They threw him into a holding
cell and charged him with committing two felonies, slander and
interfering with the work of a law enforcement agency. Even the
Constitution of Turkmenistan, which Kalandarov cited in his own
defense in the courtroom, was ignored by the judge. It could not
have been otherwise. After all, such important figures as
Regional Attorney Ataev and Regional Governor Motaev were
personally interested in the outcome of the trial against the
indefatigable and awkward Kalandarov. Kalandarov's endless
telegrams to Ashgabad had stuck very painfully in the throats of
these officials. Having pronounced the guilt of Kalandarov and
having sentenced him to 30 months in jail, the court freed him
on the authority of a presidential amnesty decree. With their
conviction, the regional officials achieved their goal, they
officially made an honest and principled man a recognized felon.
No one will listen to or respect a recognized felon. Many
residents of Dashkhovuz who know Kalandarov and what happened to
him were only reaffirmed in their belief that there is no
justice in Turkmenistan; unless you want your back broken, be
quiet. However, silence is not necessarily a sign of consent ...

SAVING THE LEOPARD - SYMBOL OF TURKMENISTAN'S MOUNTAINS

by Victor Lukarevsky, Syunt Khasardagsky Nature Reserve - In
terms of numbers of large predator species, Turkmenistan
probably ranks first among Central Asian countries. Even in the
not-so-distant past, in the 1950s, there were eight species of
large predators, including two brown bear subspecies and two
lynx subspecies. In an instant, two species and two subspecies
disappeared; the Turan tiger, Asian cheetah, Syrian brown bear,
and an absolutely unstudied lynx are now extinct. Of the species
that remain, the leopard is the most endangered; it could also
become extinct by the next decade. Only five years ago, the
leopard population in Turkmenistan numbered between 130-150
individuals and seemed relatively stable and hopeful. Leopards
inhabited all the mountain ranges of the country, and in each
range there were several communities of leopards which
contributed to the stability of the entire population. However,
the social and economic changes in Turkmenistan negatively
effected every part of the leopard's habitat, especially in the
various parks and reserves of the country. Since the leopard is
at the top of the food chain in its habitat, these changes had
an immediate affect on the population. At the present time, the
Asian leopard may be the most endangered large cat in the world.
Our research over the past two years has shown that in many
areas, even in protected areas, leopard has either disappeared
entirely (as in the Kugitang-tau Mountains) or has had its
population cut roughly in half (as in the Syunt Khasardagsky
Nature Reserve). (...) From time immemorial, the leopard has
lived with man in the south of Turkmenistan, and conflicts
between the two have been infrequent, for the most part only
occurring during hunts for common, indeed swarming, ungulate
prey. Yet, in the past five years the mountains, even in the
areas of protected reserves, have become nearly devoid of this
prey. During the 1980s, some preserved areas had literally
hundreds of thousands of mountain goats and boars; now there may
be a few dozen left. Under these conditions, the leopard is
forced to descend outside the boundaries of his usual mountain
habitat and hunt domestic animals. Sadly, these rogue leopards
are, sooner or later, killed by bullets or baited poisonous
traps shot. (...) Even in the 1984-1985 season, the number of
leopards in the central part of the Syunt Khasardagsky Nature
Reserve was no more than three adults and one or two young, who,
as in the present day, wandered far outside the boundaries of
the reserve during their hunts since the population of mountain
sheep barely reached 100 individuals and the population of boars
barely reached 150 individuals. Remains of leopard meals
contained most evidence of boars, porcupine, and domestic
animals. Only in 20% of the finds was there evidence of mountain
sheep. However, within five years the situation changed for the
better. The leopard population increased to four adults and
three or four young, and attacks on domestic livestock almost
completely ceased. Instead, the major sources of food were
mountain sheep and boars, whose populations had increased to
approximately 250-270 and 170-200 individuals respectively.
Thus, as prey populations increased, <a name=L10001></a><a href=#L10002>so</a> did the leopard
population. This correlation is explained by the fact that the
leopard preys upon sick, injured, old, young, or otherwise unfit
individuals. (...) Because of unregulated poaching in protected
lands, over the past five years, ungulate populations in the
Syunt Khasardagsky Mountain Range have plummeted to critical
lows and probably do not exceed more than a few dozen
individuals. Accordingly, leopard populations dropped from seven
to eight individuals in 1990-91 to three to four individuals
now. Wild prey now constitutes less than 25% of the leopards'
diet, and the leopard is again forced to wander far from the
nature reserve's boundaries in search of prey. Sometimes,
however, it is also able to find prey within the reserve's
boundaries as cattle grazing is, in the new regime, an allowed
use of the nature reserve's resources. It is obvious, that the
leopard is not guilty for its attacks on domesticated animals.
Rather, it is man's fault, an obvious fact if we can move
ourselves far enough to accept that the leopard also has a right
to life. Moreover, as public policy, the leopard is not a
significant threat, and shepherds are in actuality harming
themselves when they shoot leopards. In the areas where hunger
or guns extirpate the leopard, the wolf appears, a predator that
poses a much more salient threat to domestic animals. And if it
were possible to also extirpate the wolf, since nature does not
approve of empty niches, it is likely that feral dogs would
appear, only increasing the problem as these animals are
exclusively reliant on domestic prey and much more comfortable
around settlements. World practice is showing the need for
developed and interconnected systems of nature reserves and
hunting reserves. Ironically, Turkmenistan was a leader in
nature conservation in the 1980s; it's park system of nature
reserves was a model not only for the Soviet Union, but also for
the rest of the world. However, it's system of hunting reserves
was not as developed. This disparity was addressed a few years
ago in a unique way by the Ministry of Nature Use through the
efforts of Oraz Geldiev, an infamous former deputy minister.
Geldiev's solution was to turn nature reserves into hunting
areas, inviting rich foreigners to the country to pay for hunts
on endangered animals. His slogan, "the only science I need is
the one which pays," buried not only conservation biology, but
also the nature reserves themselves, sending nature protection
back a half century in Turkmenistan. While the nature reserves
operated, they offered total protection, a mandate respected not
only by the scientific community, but also by the local
populations. The appearance of such hunts only inspired locals
to take up arms themselves and initiated an explosions of
poaching that decimated the leopard's prey populations. 

This work was conducted with financial support from the John D.
and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation.

THE DEGRADATION OF THE CHELEKEN PENINSULA 

by Timur Berkeliev, Ashgabad Ecological Club CATENA - The
Cheleken Peninsula (now actually an island connected to the
mainland only by a pontoon crossing) has suffered more than
other regions of Turkmenistan as a result of the rising waters
of the Caspian. The lower part of the town of Cheleken is
flooded, and the main road to Nebitdag, upon which residents
rely for trade an fuel, is threatened with destruction. All of
this exacerbates the difficult environmental conditions caused
by large amounts of particulate pollution (bitumen and heavy
metals) from a nearby technical carbon factory. Until the
beginning of industrialization in the region, the Cheleken area
contained natural springs of mineral water and bitumen, traces
of which are clearly manifested in khir sand (native bitumen
cemented sands), ozokerite residues sulfide carbonates, mineral
deposits, and radium bearing anomalies. Since the 1930s, iodine
has been captured from these underground pools at such a rate
that in the 1960s the natural springs disappeared. The
concentrations of elements in the local mineral water varies,
with cadmium, tin, and silver reaching up to 1 mg/l, zinc, lead,
and copper reaching up to 10 mg/l, and iron, strontium, barium,
iodine, and bromine reaching up to 100 mg/l. At one time, the
production of all the iodine-bromine springs reached nearly
40,000 cubic meters/day. At the present time, the actual number
is much lower because of outdated and worn-out equipment for
which spare parts cannot be found. Because of all this, for
natural and anthropogenic reasons, there are constant increases
in the concentrations of toxic heavy metals such as radium,
cadmium, and thallium, and valuable metals such as lithium,
rubidium, and strontium. To illustrate this phenomenon with some
specific examples, springs G-39 and E-188 exhibit
characteristically high deposits of radiobarite. Spring G-39,
drilled in 1961 to a depth of 1007 meters will be filled with
barites within three years. Even by 1966, the pumping pipes had
become filled with several tens of thousands of tons of barites,
which contained three times the amount of radium typical during
such operations. The total radiation carried to the surface is
estimated at approximately ten million bekkerels. In 1935, Dr.
Scherbakov estimated the daily incidental production of radium
from the iodine springs to be roughly 1.5 mg. Of course, the
present daily output is much higher. Nevertheless, we can use
this figure as a minimum estimate and calculate that over the
past 60 years, 36.5 grams of radium have been brought to the
surface, the equivalent of 1.35 trillion bekkerels. Moreover,
the activated coal used in the filtering process absorbs a
significant quantity of radium. At the same time, the question
of how and where to store waste materials has not been resolved.
After the powdered coal has dried, it is usually simply carried
away by the wind. The effect is easily viewed by radioactive
mapping, and the most disturbing consequences are viewed near
the territory of the carbon factory and the settlements of
Sary-Kai. Of course, other elements can also be trapped within
this coal, most notably very high concentrations of thallium.
Another serious environmental and health problem resulting from
the creation of radioactive coal is the production of radon as
radium decays. Technogenic processes are currently strongly
influencing earlier formed concentrations of rare elements.
Thus, sulfide minerals at the surface are exposed to oxidation
and the resulting compounds are often spread by wind causing
health hazards as these chemicals mix into the soil and water
supply. Moreover, no one has yet studied the concentrations of
thallium and similar elements in the dust around Cheleken. Thus,
the mineral waters of Cheleken which have been used as sources
of iodine and bromine, and could in the future be used to
produce other valuable elements, are a serious environmental
problem because of several heavy metals. More quantitative
research must be done to further elucidate the problem. It does
not seem possible to suggest closing down the iodine-bromine
factory since it is one of only three industrial sources of
income for the town. The other two are the technical carbon
factory and oil refinery (which is also far from being innocent
in the environmental sense). The closing of any one of these
enterprises would lead to significant unemployment and a danger
to the further existence of the town and nearby settlements.
Further, at the present time, it also does not appear to be
feasible to talk about remediation of the local soils and
restoration of local biodiversity. One interesting
characteristic of life on Cheleken is that the usual trophic
relationship between people and the land does not exist. The
usual soil-plant-animal-man chain is inapplicable since all the
drinking water and almost all food products (except fish and
some meat) are imported to Cheleken. Therefore, of primary
importance is cataloguing the transport venues of solid and
liquid wastes and preventing their concentration near
residential areas. Later, it will be necessary to do risk
assessments of these industrial wastes and determine
possibilities for recycling or containment. Concurrently, it
will be necessary to seek alternative technologies capable of
minimizing environmental damage.

This work was completed with financial support from the John D.
and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation.

Tadschikistan

THE PAMIR ECOCENTER

The Pamir EcoCenter is a nongovernmental nonprofit private
voluntary organization formed to preserve human habitat, wild
nature, landscapes, and also to disseminate environmental
education to local people. The Pamir EcoCenter was registered in
1994 through the Executive Committee of the Gorno-Badakhshan
Region of Tajikistan.

The current projects of the EcoCenter include conducting a
biological inventory of the Gunt Valley, in cooperation with
Khorog University, and the running of an active environmental
education center, partially funded through a grant from
ISAR/USAID. This educational center is located in the village of
Djelondy at an altitude of 3600 meters, 125 kilometers from
Khorog, and offers youth, university, and adult education
classes. The site was chosen because it is a striking example of
a high altitude ecosystem containing typical flora and fauna as
well as many thermal springs.

TAJIKISTAN NGO/GOVERNMENT COMMITTEE 

by Yuri Skochilov and Muazama Burkhanova, Foundation in Support
of Citizen Initiatives - On March 5 and 6 in Dushanbe, under the
auspices of the Foundation in Support of Citizen Initiatives, a
unique seminar was held: Solving Environmental Problems Through
NGO/Government Cooperation. Over 40 Tajikistan NGOs and foreign
organizations were represented at this seminar, as well as
representatives of the government and parliament. (...) In order
to more effectively realize social-environmental projects, we
intend to form an Independent Citizen Environmental Council
consisting of representatives of environmental NGOs. The
composition of this council was proposed and confirmed at a
general meeting of NGOs on March 14, 1996. (...) List of members
of the Independent Citizen Environmental Council is to develop
