Kurzmeldungen Mittelasien:

The 5 December OMRI Daily Digest reported that seven Uzbekistan
newspapers have ceased publication and that the quantity of
radioactive waste accumulating in Kazakstan's uranium mining and
processing plants, 219 million tons, is reaching "alarming
proportions."

The 29 February OMRI Daily Digest reported that wolves are
threatening humans in northwestern Kazakstan and that "the
Kazakhstani government has set aside 3 million tenge ($46,000)
to organize special brigades of hunters and offer bounties to
deal with an increasing number of attacks on humans by a growing
wolf population." It also reported a biologist's estimate that
there are now 60,000 wolves in Kazakstan, an increase due to the
cessation of government bounties several years ago, and that in
Eastern Kazakstan, a bounty for wolf is equal to $74.

Dushanbe's parks are being destroyed. Despite a spring
presidential decree, citizens are continuing to cut trees in the
city parks. 25,000 saplings were planted in March 1995, most of
which are now gone. 20% of the main park is now cleared of
vegetation.

The NGO Information Center, in partnership with Save the
Children United States, and with financial assistance from
Counterpart Consortium, has opened an NGO Resource Center in
Dushanbe.

Poaching continues in the Pamirs. This year, authorities
detained smugglers attempting to export 10 Snow Leopard pelts.
These skins sell for $1000 on the local Dushanbe market and from
$10,000 to $25,000 on the world market. However, in the remote
Pamirs, such a pelt or a rack of Marco Polo sheep horns can be
traded for a pair of durable military boots. The official ban on
such exports to Western countries and the active measures of
local law enforcement agencies have led to falling prices on the
local black market for Snow Leopard, Tien-Shan bear, and other
rare species.

The Eighth International Snow Leopard Conservation Symposium was
held in the middle of November in Islamabad, Pakistan and
contained a special working session on the biodiversity of
Central Asia. Snow leopard habitat countries such as
Afghanistan, Bhutan, China, Kazakstan, Mongolia, Nepal,
Pakistan, Russia, Tajikistan, and Uzbekistan were in attendance,
as well as representatives from the United States, Canada,
Turkmenistan, World Wildlife Federation, and the World
Conservation Union. Representatives from Central Asian NGOs
participated in both the snow leopard and biodiversity
discussions thanks to a grant from ISAR to the International
Snow Leopard Trust (USA) and Ecolog (Uzbekistan). Unfortunately,
due to unforeseeable circumstances, NGO representatives from
Kazakstan and Kyrgyzstan could not attend. (...) There was one
particularly interesting moment at the symposium. Several years
ago, WWF International gave WWF Pakistan responsibility for
addressing the problems of Central Asia. While WWF Pakistan
representatives visited the Central Asia republics a few times,
nothing at all ever came of it. Thus, recently the coordinating
role was shifted to the Russian Program Office of WWF. Having
lost the formal right to represent WWF in the Central Asian
republics, our southern neighbors finally opened their eyes and
began to open up real communications with us. (...) (by Oleg
Tsaruk, tashkent@glas.apc.org)

Conference Announcement: On June 1-2, the Union in Defense of
the Aral Sea and Amu Darya and the Netherlands Foundation NOVIB
will sponsor the Second Central Asian NGO conference in
Tashkent. This conference was originally scheduled for late May
and only recently rescheduled. The goal of the organizers is to
facilitate the development of a region-wide NGO coalition. In
contrast to the first conference, held 10-12 November in Nukus
with the goal of acquainting NGOs with each other, the Tashkent
conference anticipates more concrete action. NOVIB hopes that
each of the invited organizations will dedicate itself to
practical results. This dedication should be demonstrated
through both past work, as well as through the presentation of
future projects, in English, to be considered for financial
support from NOVIB. NOVIB plans to provide financial support for
projects addressing ecology, environmental education, health,
water management, women's issues, and technology. The maximum
size of a grant will be $3000-$4000.

