MOLDOVA

State Ecological Inspection: Often From Misfortune Blessings Flow

According to the data given in the report of the State
Ecological Inspection by I. Buchinsky, Director, it could be
said that in the republic there was an invisible opposition in
"three spheres" (in the air, on the land and in the water)
between nature defenders and various economic agents who make
harm to nature by their activities. A considerable lowering of
the atmosphere pollution level belongs to the cheerful figures
mentioned at the 1995 report meeting of the Board of the State
Department for the Environmental Protection and Natural
Resources. Last year the general index of harmful particles
found in the air was reduced to 1.5 tons less than the previous
year's index, however, here it is appropriate to recall a folk
proverb: often from misfortune blessings flow. Regretfully, the
qualitative improvement of the atmospheric conditions could not
be explained by more careful attitude towards nature but by a
forced closing of the majority of the harmful productions caused
by economic confusions. Undoubtedly, liquidation of nearly 50
per cent of small boilerhouses or their remodeling to natural
gas stations has played a certain positive role in the whole
situation. Along with that, as it was mentioned in the report,
the index of sulphatanhydride presence in the air is kept at the
same level. It is connected with the use of high rate sulphur
fuel. Industrial wastes to be buried in the ground also present
a difficult problem to solve. Nearly 11 million tons of such
wastes were produced last year, 18.5 thousand of which are
considered to be toxic, while 3.5 thousand are extra-toxic. A
hopeful sign is that the use of pesticides was considerably
reduced for the last five years. The 1995 index is thrice less
than the one five years ago: 5.1 thousand tons against 14.5
thousand tons in 1990, though it also has negative impact on
soil. Besides the ever-application of chemicals the soil is also
subjected to other troubles. Particularly, as before,
considerable areas of fertile soil are excluded from the
turnover only because they are either used in insignificant
purposes or not used at all, because of landslides and wind
erosion. Various commercial groups, purchasing plots of land,
which are actually agricultural farm properties, do not care for
preservation of the fertile stratum of soil destroying it
instead of providing its disposal to some other place. The main
source of landslides and wind erosion is mass destruction of
forests and protective forest zones. The woods of Vulcanesti
region, which have suffered most of all from such disasters
during the current ten years, still are subjected to regular
tree felling. 29 hectares of forests were cut illegally in the
village of Brinza, despite it being the property of the local
authority, while 12 hectares of forest belonging to the local
agrofarm "Moldova" were cut in the village of Slobozeia Mare. As
to the water (...) the river Prut has suffered most of all. On
August 28, a heavy pollution of the river's section took place
in the confluence area of its tributary Bahlui as a result of an
accident during the purification works in the city of Yasi
(Roumania). The economic agents of the village of Yargara, in
Leovo region, added negative impacts to the situation when there
was a huge fuel leakage from containers of the local elevator
with oil escaping into the river. Last year 8,213 enterprises
and organizations influencing the environment were checked for
ecological standards by the State Ecological Inspection of
Moldova - an institution realizing special control over
environmental conditions. The inspectors have made 5,049
protocols, on the basis of which the economic agents were
subjected to sanctions. 112 cases were passed on to the
Ecological Prosecutor's office for investigation, while 720
cases of ecological legislation infringement were considered by
public courts and 14 cases by arbitration.

WHAT IS IN A GLASS OF WATER?

by Valentina Malikova, IEA "ALTAIR" - According to the
calculations of the international experts more than 60 per cent
of human diseases are connected with bad water quality. (...)
Meanwhile, in the Republic of Moldova there are more than 39.5
per cent of central water supply sources which do not meet the
requirements of (...) "Drinking water". Then, perhaps, wells and
springs are less dangerous? Unfortunately, the situation with
them is even more complicated, especially in the countryside. It
seems as if pure drinking water here is becoming an exceptional
rarity. As a matter of fact, now the main cause for drinking
water pollution in the countryside is private stock breeding.
Many villagers keep the animals in their back yards, without
paying much attention to waste utilization, namely manure and
sewer. Wastes saturating the yard's ground by themselves turn
into sulphates, nitrates and other organic pollutants. Then the
pollutants penetrate wells. Nothing of the kind could ever
happen if the owners would dispose their animals' wastes in the
fields, for agricultural lands fertilizing, promoting natural
nitrogen recycling. However, manure piles at the private back
yards continue to grow. Simultaneously the indices of drinking
water quality and those of villagers' health, especially the
health of children, are getting worse. The research testifies
that the children's sick rate level is 3-4 times higher in the
regions with the most polluted water sources. These children are
behind their peers in physical development, they get sick more
often and slower recover from illness. "The reasons for
children's and adults' poor health could not be, of course,
limited by the nitrate pollution of drinking water", - N.I.
Opopol, Professor of the State Medical University and First
Assistant General Director of the State Hygiene and Epidemiology
Scientific Center of Moldova, said. "Undoubtedly, the importance
of heredity should not be underestimated. Do not forget either
about bitter 'fruit' of intensive over-application of chemicals
in agriculture. I mean the statistics on liver cirrhosis, other
chronic diseases and, of course, the population death rate,
which was more than doubled in the last decade. It were village
residents, who are the leaders in the sad statistics.We have
worked out special recommendations on how to provide villagers
with pure drinking water and passed them on to the Ministry of
Public Health and the Government of Moldova. We believe that the
countryside populated areas need group water pipelines. The
project for their construction has been approved. The building
of such a pipeline has been started from the area of the town of
Soroki, but this new construction had to be frozen because of
the lack of means."

<a name=L10002></a><a href=#L10003>So</a>, did the whole story come to the end? But, where is the way
out? As scientists think, there is a way out. Firstly, one
should try and find subsidies for construction of modern group
water pipelines, evidently at the expense of local budgets.
Secondly, it is necessary to take care of drinking water quality
in order not to allow its further pollution. Who should take
this responsibility? Apparently the local authorities! It is in
their power to prosecute the environmental protection law
breakers. At their disposal also are regional centers of hygiene
and epidemiology, whose specialists could reveal safe wells and
springs in villages to be used instead of polluted ones. Lastly,
the industry produces water purification filters. Professor
Opopol informed us about inculcation of such appliances of
collective use in Moldova. They are able to purify 300 liters of
water daily, which is quite enough to meet the needs of a
village school, kindergarten or several families. The efficiency
of such collective filters has been proved during the tests in
Hincesti, Orhei and Straseni regions of Moldova. (...)

Forests in Moldova:

Valentina Malikova, IEA "ALTAIR" - (...) In former times Moldova
was famous for its marvellous kodry forests. Now it is among the
poorest of the European countries in woods. Today forests occupy
less than 400 hectares in the republic. As a result, there is
only 0.06 hectares of woods per capita. However, even this
scanty index will turn to be less if one does not take into
account plantings along railways and freeways. In this case the
woods area will make only 6 per cent of the regions territory,
which is simply dangerous. Furthermore, the forest fund is split
to more than 800 units with an area of 0.5 to 1.500 hectares,
which is far from being sufficient to provide wild animals with
normal life conditions. The State Forest Fund comprises 325
thousand hectares, while the remaining part of the woods belongs
to the municipalities and collective farms. The state fund is
relatively fine as far as it gets necessary care, but the woods
of the collective farms are exploited rudely-unwarranted,
tree-felling is very common here. The local authorities choose
to ignore this and even take part themselves in these ruinous
actions. Unfortunately, the Ecological Inspection cannot
counteract with well-equipped and armed law breakers. As a
result, the collective forest fund has lost 738.8 thousand cubic
metres of wood for the last five years. While the state forest
fund lost 10 thousand cubic metres. The present crisis, affected
the forest resources of Moldova, is conditioned to many reasons.
The most important of these are illegal tree felling,
ecologically incompetent natural resources use, ignoring their
natural regeneration, primarily of seeds. All these factors
taken together caused the changes in green huge tracts of
forest, <a name=L10003></a><a href=#L10004>so</a> that the main forest forming species- oak- occupy now
only 51 per cent of the state forest fund area (for comparison
in 1964 it was 64 per cent). In addition, some tree species, not
typical for this region, had been introduced in the republic.
Among them is white acacia, planted over a quarter of the forest
funds' area. White acacia has had a tragic lot. Its planting is
just perishing, simply drying up. By this time Moldova has a
weakend, badly regenerating forest, the existance of which is
under a serious threat of extinction. A deplorable condition of
woods, of course, had a negative effect on the state reserve
fund too. Presently, there are five reserves of an exceptionally
scientific character (the total area is 19,418 hectares).
However, their ecosystem's preservation appeares to be a
difficult task. To this end there is not any legislative basis,
which could account the new realia. The reserves are not
provided by a proper guard. The best highskilled specialists
leave their jobs, because of financial problems, while reserve
regieme breakers are becoming more numerous. Particularly, the
cases of poaching and herding of domestic cattle are becoming
more frequent along with the placing of trash heaps. (...)

STUDY AND PROTECTION OF BATS IN NOTHERN AND CENTRAL MOLDOVA

Andrey Vasilyev, Doctor of Biology, "Fauna" group Director -
Under this name the project, carried out by "Fauna" group
belonging to the Association of Young Ecologists of Moldova
"Campul Ecologic", has been closed on February 15, 1996. The
project was 85 per cent financed by the World Nature Association
(Maryland, USA). There have been carried out 16 expeditions to
study fauna of bats living in the caves of the republic, 32
lectures read to school students and mine workers, 5 articles
published in press and 3 scientific reports presented at the
conferences on temporary conditions and protection of these
animals. The hand-winged animals have wonderful abilities, such
as flying, ultra sound orientation in darkness and winter
hibernation. Bats bring much aid by eating lots of night
insects, including harmful ones. Of 18 species of the animals
living in our republic only 3 are quite common, the rest of them
are considered to be rare ones. All of them are protected by the
state, but no active measures on their real protection is being
taken. The "Fauna" group prepared a report "Bats' Contemporary
Condition in Moldova and Necessary Measures for Their
Protection", which is supposed to be presented to the State
Department for the Environmental Protection and Natural
Resources and Parliamentary Subcommission on Ecology. "Fauna"
group will continue the campaign on rare species of animals of
Moldova protection, including the hand-winged ones, during the
project realization "In the Search of Salamandra", financed by
ISAR Kiev Regional Office in 1996. 

News from Moldova, #2, February 1996, Published by ALTAIR
International Ecological Agency (Chisinau, Moldova) with
financial support from USAID through Eurasia Foundation in
association with the Royal Netherlands Embassy in Kiev.
