VLADIMIR PETRENKO BEGAN A HUNGER STRIKE

In Protest of the extreme human rights violations against him
the last several months Vladimir Petrenko (Shikhany, Saratov
Oblast) began a hunger strike on January 22nd.

BACKGROUND INFO (by The Center for Assistance to Environmental
Initiatives): Vladimir Petrenko served in the Soviet Army in the
early 1980s in Shikhany where he became a victim of chemical
weapons experiments. This led to a series of chronic illnesses
including lung and intestinal disorders, and also thyroid
disease. He received occupational disability status due to
having been sent to Chernobyl as part of a clean-up team. In
1991, the Command of Deputy and Environmental Activity illegally
laid off Petrenko for political reasons. He received no
compensation and was essentially blacklisted in Shikhany and
Volsk, making it difficult to feed his two small children. The
military officials refused to recognize that Petrenkos illnesses
were connected with his service. Only after two and a half
years, with the interference of the Supreme Council of Russia,
the Central Military-Physicians Commission granted Petrenko
invalid status. Petrenkos treatment was prevented by the
blockade on all information on the tests conducted on him. At
age 34, he was named an invalid with 25 chronic disorders.
Despite this, Petrenko was denied by the Court the admission of
the fact that the experiments had been conducted on him, and
thus he was denied compensation for emotional harm as well as
physical and psychological suffering, caused and subjected upon
him by the Command of the Shikhany Institute. Earlier Vladimir
Petrenko made known to the public the fact that experiments were
being conducted on people for the purpose of testing new classes
of chemical weapons. Because of this, he has experienced
numerous repressions on the part of the military. In the Centers
opinion, the fabricated evidence against Petrenko is now being
used as an attempt to discredit him in the eyes of the public.
The drawn-out investigation plus denying him his right to leave
the country, are both tactics to deprive Vladimir Petrenko the
opportunity to continue his environmental activity and to seek
assistance from human-rights organizations.

July 1995. Vladimir Petrenko filed a lawsuit against the
Shikhany Military Institute where he worked for many years and
where he was subjected to the chemical weapons experiments. A
decision was made on the federal level to grant Vladimir
financial compensation for the harm done to his health when sent
to Chernobyl to do clean-up. The Oblast Court refused to convict
the Institute of conducting inhuman tests using new chemical
weapons on Petrenko in 1982.

July 30, 1995. Vladimir's former colleague in the Shikhany
Institute insulted him and then came to blows. In defending
himself, Vladimir tryed to hold the man back, and the other guy
ended up with some bruises. Vladimir was convicted for
misbehavior and for committing bodily harm.

Oct 3, 1995. The Military Division 61469, where Vladimir
Petrenkos wife, Svetlana, has worked for the last 13 years,
demoted her for the third time in one year. Despite the pleas of
human rights organizations the Institute has announced that she
will be laid off as of March 1st, 1996.

Nov 4, 1995. Captain Kulev from Volsk-17 denied Petrenko his
right to leave the country. This was done in the absence of a
lawyer. Petrenko turns to the Volsk Special Prosecutor with
complaints about the violations being committed against him.

Dec 25, 1995. Petrenko receives a response stating that there
are ten days to complete a preliminary investigation of the
incriminated Petrenko, but nothing was mentioned of the other
violations.

Jan 19, 1996. Petrenko announced to Captain Kulev and sent
letters to the General Prosecutor of Russia, the Chair of the
Presidential Commission on Human Rights, Sergei Kovalev, and
other organizations, stating that if his petition stating his
objection to the preliminary investigation will not be satisfied
by 9:00 a.m. on January 22nd, he will start a hunger strike.

Jan 22, 1996. Kulev summoned Petrenko. Petrenko began a hunger
strike.

Today, Febr 1996, Vladimir is in the Saratov occupational
diseases clynic for a check-up holding on hunger strike. He
won't stop the hunger strike until his requests be satisfied.

