"Vladimir Petrenko's Hunger Strike"

[From Express-Chronicle Newspaper, No. 5, February 2, 1996]
VOLSK-17 (SARATOV REGION). - Vladimir Petrenko's hunger strike
has continued into the tenth day. In the early 1980s Petrenko
served in Shikhany in the army, where he was the victim of
experiments with poisonous substances [chemical weapons]. On
July 3, 1995, a lawsuit on Petrenko's behalf was launched in
Saratov Regional Court against the Ministry of Defense, to
compensate him for damages to his health. At the conclusion of
the court investigation, a representative of the Ministry of
Defense insulted and struck Petrenko several times. Petrenko's
actions to defend himself (he restrained the officer's hands)
were ruled as "hooliganism", instigating a criminal case against
him under Article 206 of the Russian Criminal Code. Later he was
indicted under Article 112 ("Deliberate infliction of light
bodily injury") as well. As Petrenko's lawyer Vitalina Dmitrieva
reported in the January 31 issue of Express-Chronicle, his blood
pressure has badly fallen. In the past Petrenko participated in
military chemical experiments; he has status as a third-group
disabled person, and his lawyers fear that continuation of the
hunger strike could lead to irreversible consequences. Petrenko
began his hunger strike on January 22, demanding the removal of
a Mr. Kulev, an investigator with the local special police. The
investigator was not replaced, but in the course of several days
Petrenko's investigation was completed and the case transferred
to the Procurator [prosecutor], who must sign the indictment and
transfer the case back to court. Petrenko altered the terms of
his hunger strike, and is now demanding that the Saratov
Regional Procurator assume supervision of the case. (Since
Petrenko lives in Volsk-17, next to the Shikhansky military
site, supervision over his case is assigned to a Special
Procurator's Office. Petrenko considers the existence of the
Special Procurator's Office unconstitutional.) The lawyer V.
Dmitrieva reported that Petrenko is in no mood to compromise:
"He believes that unless he can bring himself back to good
health, no one will pay attention to his case." Translation:
Lisa Tracy

"The Hunger Strike Protest Has Ended"

[From Zemlya Saratovskaya newspaper, February 16, 1996] - On
February 13 Vladimir Petrenko, co-chair of the regional Union
for Chemical Safety and the Russian Green Cross, ended his
hunger strike, begun on January 22 as a symbol of his protest
against the lack of legal limits observed by the Military
Special Procurator [Prosecutor] of the village of Shikhany.
Petrenko ended his hunger strike after a press conference in the
Russian-American Press Center organized by Greenpeace, Ecojuris,
the "Memorial" human rights center, the Socio-Ecological Union,
and the Moscow Legal Defense Center, on the topic of persecution
of environmentalists by the Russian authorities. One example of
this persecution is the Petrenko case. Representatives of
organizations taking part in the press conference sent a
telegram to Petrenko, persuading him to stop his hunger strike
(the telegram from Ecojuris in particular asserts that
Petrenko's health and strength will come in useful not only for
him but also for other people). Note: Ecojuris lawyers are
defending Vladimir Petrenko's case in Russian court.
Translation: Lisa Tracy

Pacific Environment and Resources Center, perc@igc.apc.org,
18.03.96

Kurzmeldungen

Jedinaja Energetitscheskaja Sistema Rossii (AO) - EES Rossii

verkauft auf dem internationalen Markt 4,5% der Aktien mit einem
Nennwert von je 500 Rubeln. Das Grundkapital betraegt 21,558
Mrd. Rubel. Die Gesellschaft besitzt Mehrheitsbeteiligungen an
60 regionalen Energiewirtschaftsgesellschaften, 35 Kraftwerken
und Forschungsinstituten. Sie kontrollert 70% der
Stromproduktion in Russland. Das Register der Aktieninhaber
fuehrt das Moskauer Zentraldepot. Informationen bei der
Foederalen Wertpapierkorporation, 103704 Moskau, Kitajskij
projesd 9, 007-095-139 69 26, 132 69 70; Fax: 132 69 18, 132 68
43.

Auf einer Tagung im Oktober in Moskau erklaerten Vertreter von
Jedinaja Energetitscheskaja Sistema Rossii (AO), dass die
Jahresleistung der russichen Kraftwerke bis zum Jahr 2000 um 12
Gigawatt auf 200 sinken werde, da 25% der technischen Anlagen
von Waermekraftwerken im Jahr 2000 veraltet sein wird. Sie
produzieren 70% der Elektrizitaet und 50% der Waermeenergie.

Im Dezember legte EES Rossii ein Investitionsprogramm fuer die
naechsten sechs bis acht Jahre vor. Es sieht den Bau von 44
Waerme- und Wasserkraftwerken vor (Kapazitaet: insgesamt 45 Mio
kW), von 45 Umspannwerken und von der Verlegung von ueber 9.600
km Stromleitungen vor. Der Investitionsbeadrf der russischen
Stromindustrie wird auf 40 bis 72 Mrd US $ geschaetzt, von denen
der Sektor selbst 70% investieren will, 10-12% aus
Aktienverkaeufen kommen sollen und 20% als Kredite aufgenommen
werden sollen. Da wahrscheinlich noch weiteres Auslandskapital
noetig sein wird sollen Auslandsinvetitionen angezogen werden:
<a name=L10006></a><a href=#L10007>So</a> ist eine "Ost-West-Energieschiene" mit einer Kapazitaet von 4
Mio kW geplant, die auf Initiative von deutschen Firmen zusemmen
mit Belarus und Polen vorbereitet wird. Ausserdem sollen ein
Schwarzmeer-und ein Baltikumsverbund geschaffen werden. 1996 -
1998 soll mit 90 Mio US $ von der Europaeischen Bank fuer
Wiederaufbau und Entwicklung (EBRD), London, westliche
Technologie gekauft werden.

OSTinvest, 43/95, 27.10.1995, S. 17/18; 45/95, 10.11.1995, S.
25; 49/95, 8.12.1995, S. 17.

Umweltprogramm fuer Wolgabecken:

Am 10.11.1995 hat die russische Regierung ein Umweltprogramm
fuer das Wolgabecken beschlossen, das bis 2010 die Wolga
wiederbeleben soll. Ziele sind die Saeuberung des Flussbettes,
des Ufers und der umgebung des Flusses. 38 regionale
Verwaltungseinheiten sind an dem Programm beteiligt. Die Kosten
der ersten Projektphase sollen 8 Bio Rubel betragen

OSTinvest, 46/95, 17.11.1995, S. 7.

Pollution in Pskov

PSKOV - The greatest source of pollution in the city is the
heavy metal spread from the smokestack of the Pskov factory of
radio components, according to a two-year investigation of the
environmental quality of life in Pskov completed in September.
Heavy metals were also found in high concentration in the city
dump. Auto and rail transport are most responsible for oil-based
pollution. An ecological map of Pskov and a computer database
are to be established based on the results. (Novosti Pskova, 27
Dec.)

"ECODEFENSE!" Moskovsky prospekt 120-34 236006
Kaliningrad/Koenigsberg Russia telephone/fax +7 0112 437286
