AID FOR NUCLEAR SAFETY DECLINING
Moscow, -  Western  aid  for nuclear plant safety in Russia is
down 20 per cent this year despite problems at  the  country's
old nuclear facilities,  a news report said Wednesday.
Gennady Nefyodov, deputy chief of the Atomic Energy Ministry's
foreign relations department,  said the decline in funds would
affect  research  as  well  as  projects  already  under  way.
Russia has  received  some  $500  million  for  upgrading  and
repairing its nuclear plants in the past  five  years  (Russia
have spent  at  least  $500  million  own money for same goals
during last 5 years,  - EDI) , Nefyodov told the Interfax news
agency. The  amount  slated for 1996 is 20 per cent lower than
last year.
     
BELARUS COMPILANCE
Minsk, - Belarus on Tuesday denied Russian allegations that it
is undertermining  agreements  on  the  withdrawal  of  former
Soviet nuclear missiles to Russia.
Belarusian Deefense  Minister  Leonid Maltsev said Belarus was
determined to adhere to a shedule approved  by  both  nations,
and to  coplete the pullout of the 18 remaining strategic,  or
long-range, missiles by the end of the  year.  Maltsev  called
"factless" Monday's   accusations  by  the  russian  strategic
missile forces' command  that  Belarus  had  filed  to  ensure
timely removal of the weapons.
"Half a year lies ahead  yet,  and  <a name=L10001></a><a href=#L10002>so</a>  a  disruption  of  the
shedule ...  is  out  of the question," he said,  according to
Interfax.
     
DYSENTERY OUTBREAK
Noscow, - Sewage seeping into tap water in the central Russian
city of Vladimir has caused an outbreak of dysentery that sent
more than 60 people to the hospital.
Few of the victims had drunk  the  water  without  boiling  it
first, but  had  used  it  to  wash fruit and vegetables or to
brush their teeth,  Itar-Tass reported Monday, citing a doctor
with the  city  sanitation department.  All those hospitalized
live in the same neighborhood of Vladimir, about 160 kilometrs
east of Moscow.
Breaks in sewage pipes near a new shoe factory  caused  sewage
to seep into water mains, the report said.
_______________________________________________________________
     
      CHERNOBYL: NO PROBLEMS SINCE 1986, OFFICIALS TOLD

by David Stickney

Introduction

Here is the official press release from the Chernobyl  Nuclear
Power Plant Regarding the 10 year anniversary of the Chernobyl
Disaster.  It was given to me by the  Public  Relations  staff
during  my  visit  to  the  station.  This document speaks for
itself regarding the station's attitude towards  its  history.
Below, also my "NOTE"


IN CONNECTION WITH THE 10-TH YEAR  ANNINVERSARY  OF  CHERNOBYL
ACCIDENT For 10 years since the accident, Chernobyl NNP's life
has been complicated and controversial. After the heroic phase
liquidating the aftermath,  of constructing the sacophagus, of
restoration and restart of the undamaged units,  of making the
new  town,  there followed the phase of personnel replacement.
Eight times the decision was taken and revoked to shutdown the
station.   They  compelled  the  staff  to  leave  their  Kiev
apartments and to move to Slavutich,  which was built,  as  it
was found out, on a caesium patch.

To profile  themselves,  many  of  today's  famous  public and
political figures,  mass media were particularly  stigmatizing
Chernobyl  NPP and were demonstrating negative attitude to the
nuclear   industry   in   general,   calling   for   immediate
renunciation of nuclear power.

Nevertheless the station kept on working.  The collective body
of staff was formed,  safety and  reliability  were  improved.
Slavutich   was  developed  and  equipped  with  services  and
utilities.

Since the accident,  Chernobyl NPP has generated more than 127
billion kWh of electricity of over US 5.5 billion total worth.

To enhance  safety,  chenges  were  made  to  the RBMK reactor
design and to  physical  characterristics  of  all  opperating
units,  which rules out the possibility of the particular type
of accident  to  recur.  More  than  $300  million  have  been
invested in Chernobyl NPP's safety.  Safe opperation is in the
hands of skilled personnel.  In 1995 Chernobyl NPP produced 10
percent  more  electricity than in 1994,  and it had the least
number of malfunctions - two per one unit - the  best  showing
in Ukraine and the CIS.

Last year  17.5  thousand square meters of dwelling space were
commisioned in Slavutich as  well  as  the  main  building  of
health care day center.  Actually,  Slavutich is a modern town
of  25,000  inhabitants.  It  has   developed   infrastruture:
telephone communication and cable television are availible for
every family.

The station's staff is committed to their duty  ensuring  safe
operation  of  the  and  producing  electricity.  The  workers
strongly believe in good sense of leadership  of  the  country
and are confident of the future.

***

IMPORTANT NOTE:  The PR rep at the station stated that he felt
that people  should  not have been evacuated from local towns,
and they should return,  as this is a greater  injustice  than
the accident itself.

They constantly  repeated  that  the  area  was a safe working
place.  Our readings outside the  reactor  from  our  personal
equipment showed more than 660 Roentgen (Gomel 10).

Slavutich is the newest town in Ukraine, food is imported, and
the standard of living is of a western standard.

The staff continually related station  situations  with  there
high standard of living as a sign of progress at the station.

In fact,  the  "spokesman"  in  a private conversation with me
stated " I don't care if the EU gave 3.1 billion to shut  down
the plant, if it reduced my standard of living, I would take a
machine gun to the  council  and  say  'up  against  the  wall
guys'.......  Well  I'm Just kidding".  The was heard by Julie
Denesha of the KS Star I don't believe he was kidding,  as  he
only said this after seeing our reaction.

When I  asked about the future plans for disposal of the waste
of reactor 4,  I was told " This isn't our work,  we  are  not
responsible".

When I asked about the status of the sarcophagus,  they stated
it was completely safe

In the document,  or any  publications,  the  results  on  the
population are not mentioned
_______________________________________________________________
     
                 BELARUS: WHAT REPRESSION?

Clintonites ignore  Soviet-style  stifling   of   dissent   in
Belarus'.

Yury Khadyka,  a veteran freedom fighter in Belarus', has been
imprisoned   since  April  27  for  protesting  his  country's
re-integration with Russia.  The U.S. government's reactionhas
been  embarrassed  silence-  certainly  no  protest- about the
conduct of the Belarusian regime it is subsidizing.

Khadyka, 58,  a distinguished art historian,  was an  activist
against Communist tyranny when Belarus (White Russia) was part
of the Soviet Union. A vice chairman of the Belarusian Popular
Front,  he  as continued the fight against President Aleksandr
Lukashenko's increasingly repressive rule over Belarus' as  an
independent  country.  Khadyka now faces a possible three-year
prison  term  for  "organizing  action  resulting   in   great
disturbance of peace."

The purpose  of singling out Khadyka,  former U.S.  Ambassador
David H.  Swartz told me, is to "discourage further repression
of opposition" to Lukashenko's policy of rejoining Russia in a
reconstitution of the Soviet Union. "The present government is
not  willing  to  tolerate dissent",  added Swartz,  a 28-year
veteran of the U.S.  foreign service who resigned in  1994  in
protest against Clinton administration's coddling of the Minsk
regime.

Leaked documents and  diplomatic  sources  make  itclear  that
President  Clinton  and  Secretary  of State Warren Cristopher
have given a green light to Russian President  Boris  Yeltsin,
running   for  re-election,  to  proceed  with  re-integrating
constituent parts of  the  former  Soviet  Union.  Given  this
attitude,  would  the  Clinton  administration  intervene when
Belarus represses dissent? The answer is that it does not. The
dilemma  at  the  State  Department  is  intense.  One  senior
official there told me that "we support freedom  of  assembly,
support  freedom  of  speech  and  condemn violations of those
freedoms" in a former Soviet  republic  which  has  become  an
American  client  state.  But  he  indicated  no  knowledge of
Khadyka's  imprisonment.  That  may  have  been  a  diplomatic
circumvention,  considering  assertions by American Belarusian
groups who say they have brought Khadyka's predicament to this
very official's attention.

Khadyka is  a victim of flotsam from the old Communist tyranny
that has risen in the  surface  in  Soviet  successor  states.
President   Lukashenko,  a  career  Communist  bureaucrat  who
managed a collective farm,  yearns for return of dictatorship.
He  has expressed admiration for Adolf Hitler's leadership and
prefers to rule  by  edict,  ignoring  wherever  possible  the
parliament  whose  very election he opposed.  Lukashenko wants
ful integration with a  Kremlin  ruled  by  one  of  Yeltsin's
authoritarian  presidential  rivals  but  will  settle  for  a
Yeltsin- run Russia- at east for now.  The erratic  Belarusian
president  consequently  was  not  happy  when  20,000  people
demonstrated in downtown Minsk April 2 against the pact signed
that  day  by  Lukashenko  and Yeltsin for renowed integration
between Russia and Belarus.  When the same  opposition  forces
organized  another  demonstration  of  some 30,000 April 26 in
Minsk to mark the 10th anniversay  of  the  Chernobyl  nuclear
disaster,  Lukashenko cracked down. The marshers, assured safe
passage by the police,  colided with the  cordon  of  "special
forces".  Dozens  of peaceful demonstrators were beaten in the
streets,  and more than 200 were arrested. Most were convicted
in "administrative trials" and then confined for from three to
10 days in jail.

Yury Khadyka was given different treatment.  He  was  arrested
April  27  and  then  held  incommunicado  for  a week- denied
contact with lawers or family.  He finally was charged on  May
4. Despite a petition from seven prominent citizens (including
four members of parliament) guaranteeing that he  will  appear
for trial,  Khadyka remains in prison while an "investigation"
goes on for at least two and possibly  six  months.  Khadyka's
29-year-old son, Alexey, is a field representative in Belarus'
for the  Washington-  based  Krieble  Institute,  which  began
promoting  democracy  in Eastern Europe long before the Soviet
Union's collapse."Do you think it is possible  that  the  U.S.
Embassy  will  make a note [ of protest]?" the son asked May 2
in an e-mail to Krieble headquarters.

The answer <a name=L10002></a><a href=#L10003>so</a> far is no. If Clinton could meet with Yeltsin in
their  latest  summit and not protest the carnage in Chechnya,
it  is  not  difficult  for  him  to  overlook  repression  in
Belarus'.  The  American president's determination is to elect
Yeltsin to another term and worry about  unhappy  developments
in the former Soviet Union after that.
