From: ecodefense@glas.apc.org
Newsgroups: reg.eeurope
Subject: X-USSR NUKE NEWS N1
Date: 05 Jul 1996 11:10:52 +0300

From: ecodefense@glas.apc.org (Vladimir Slivyak)

* X-USSR NUKE NEWS * N 1 * BY ANTINUCLEAR CAMPAIGN IN X-USSR *
______________________________________________________________

IGNALINA POWER PLANT,  LITHUANIA --  A  NUCLEAR  FUEL  STORAGE
FACILITY  IS  PLANNED  at the Ignalina power plant and will be
financed by Ontario Hydro Company together with  tenders  from
Canadian AECL and German GNB companies.  Spent nuclear fuel in
Ignalina is stored today  in  underwater  reservoirs  situated
under  the  plant reactors.  The reservoirs will soon be full.
The Ontario Hydro director for Eastern  Europe,  John  Kieran,
said  his  company  already  worked with Ignalina power plant,
including the implementation of a program related  to  quality
management at the station.
______________________________________________________________

ST PETERSBURG  --  ALEXANDER  NIKITIN  WILL  BE  JUDGED  BY  A
MILITARY  COURT  and  not by a civilian court,  according to a
recent decision by a city court.  Mr Nikitin has been  accused
of  revealing  state  military  secrets  in  his  work  on  an
environmental report  on  the  damage caused by (nuclear waste
of) the Northern Fleet.  His lawyer  has  issued  an  official
protest against  the  decision  for  him  to  be  judged  by a
non-civilian court.  Mr Nikitin was working for the  Norwegian
independent environmental  association  Bellona  when  he  was
arrested at the beginning of the year.
______________________________________________________________
     
LUKASHENKO CALLS FOR NUCLEAR-FREE ZONE, MINSK, - The president
of Belarus on  Wednesday  said  the  nations  of  central  and
eastern Europe should be kept free of nuclear weapons.
Belarus inherited part of Moscow's nuclear arsenal after  1991
Soviet collapse,  along mwith Russia,  Ukraine and Kazakhstan.
Belarus promised to disarm by the end of 1996.
"I propose  that  the  former  socialist  countries of eastern
Europe, Belarus,  Ukraine and the Baltic countries should  set
up a nuclear free zone," President Alexander Lukashenko said.
But he  added  that  "a   unilateral   step   toward   nuclear
disarmament is  not enough" and expressed concern about NATO's
eastward expansion.
______________________________________________________________

BALTIC SEA STATES ADOPT COOPERATION PROGRAMME,  KALMAR,  - The
foreign ministers  of  the  Baltic  Sea  states  on  Wednesday
adopted an action programme to boost regional  cooperation  in
crime-fighting, the   economy,  the  environment  and  nuclear
safety.
The 11 foreign ministers,  representing nine states around the
Baltic Sea plus Norway and Iceland,  hammered out the  details
of the  17-page  document  on  Tuesday  evening  and Wednesday
morning.
Several investments in the region are planned,  including road
and railway maintenance and harbour developments, totalling 40
billion kronor ($6,01 billion) for the 1995-1999 repiod.
Estonia, Latvia,  Lithuania,  Poland and Russia  will  receive
assistance in  cleaning up the environment,  particularly with
regard to treating toxic waste.
______________________________________________________________
Sources: ELTA, AP, AFP
Prepared: by x-USSR Antinuclear Campaign (ANC)
Contact: Vladimir Sliviak, International Nuclear Campaigner
* Socio-Ecological Union/ANC, PO Box 211, 121019 Moscow, Russia
Tel/fax: 7-095-2983087
* ECODEFENSE!/ANC, PO Box 1477, 236000 Kaliningrad, Russia
