FLOOD HAVOC - HEAVY rains in Siberia led to flooding which has
caused hundreds of thousands of pounds worth of damage in  the
Irkutsk region, the Interfax news agency reported yesterday.
_______________________________________________________________

    RUSSIA:  WORLD'S FIRST FLOATING NUCLEAR PLANT ...

Construction of the world's first floating nuclear power plant
is underway in Russia,  and engineers hope to have it ready to
operate by 2001,  a prospect that fills environmentalists with
horror but has Russia looking south for potential buyers.
   Andrei Gagarinsky,  vice  president  of the Russian Nuclear
Society and head of international relations at  the  Kurchatov
Institute in Moscow, confirmed to IPS this week that the first
of the plants was under construction after years of  financial
delays.
   But environmentalists contend that the threat of ecological
catastrophe  from  accidents  involving oil tankers will be as
nothing to a sea disaster involving a floating  nuclear  power
plant.
   Russia has long had  plans  to  build  a  series  of  small
floating  nuclear power plants for use in remote regions which
are not connected to the national grid or to  replace  thermal
nuclear  power plants that have grown too expensive because of
high fuel transportation costs.
   "Russia will  need  at  least 15 small,  low-power floating
nuclear power plants," says Gagarinsky.  "They will be used in
inaccessible  regions  of the Far East,  extreme North,  Altay
Territory and the Kola Peninsula."
   He noted  that  Russia is the world leader in small nuclear
power plant production and sees  them  as  potential  exports,
especially  to developing countries.  He added that Indonesia,
South Korea, China, and Vietnam have all expressed interest.
   But western  environmentalists are not convinced.  "A major
area of concern with these plants must be  containment,"  said
Antony Froggatt of the Greenpeace nuclear campaign in London.
   "The Chernobyl explosion blew the reactor lid,  a 2,000 ton
block of concrete,  into the air.  These vessels will not even
have that sort of protection.  This must pose a clear risk  to
both the marine and land environment."
   The floating plant is essentially a  ship  with  two  small
pressurized  water  reactors (PWRs) known as KLT-40s,  adapted
from those used to power Russia's nuclear icebreakers.
   The KLT-40   enhanced   safety   PWR,   designed   by  OKBM
Experimental Design Bureau of Mechanical Engineering in Nizhny
Novgorod,  has been used for over 20 years to power the USSR's
seven nuclear icebreakers as  well  as  nuclear-powered  cargo
ships.  During  this  time (over 130 reactor years) there have
been no major accidents involving the KLT.  The reactors  each
have a power output of 35-50 megawatts (MW),  giving the plant
an overall capacity of up to 100 MW of power  or  50  MW  plus
power   generating  heat.  Besides  the  OKBM,  the  Kurchatov
Institute in Moscow and  the  Aisberg  Design  Bureau  in  St.
Petersburg  were  involved in the design of the plant which is
now being built at the Baltisky Shipyard in St. Petersburg.
   The first  plant  will  be  sited  at the Arctic seaport of
Pivek in the Chukotka Peninsula in the far northeast.  It will
be operated by 40-50 people working in shifts and has a design
life of around 40 years.
   Spent fuel  and wastes will be stored on board and every 13
years it will be towed 4,000 kilometers through Arctic seas to
Murmansk  in  the  Kola  peninsula  in  Russia's northwest for
maintenance and reloading with fresh fuel.
   During this  procedure,  which  will take around a year,  a
substitute floating plant will be put in place. It is expected
to cost $254 million and will take six years to build.
   Electricity from the plant is expected  to  be  five  times
cheaper  than  from  any  other  source.  There  are around 50
suitable  sites  for  such  reactors  along  Russia's   Arctic
coastline.
   According to Alexander Poloushkin,  Director General of the
Malaya  Energetika Research and Production Association,  small
nuclear plants can contribute up to percent of the  power  and
heat  needed by these regions.  He insists that the plant will
be very safe.
   "The plant  has  reliable  protection  systems to safeguard
against all possible risks,  including sinking,  capsizing and
even an aircraft crashing on top of it,  " he says.  "It won't
pollute the area with any nuclear waste  because  it  will  be
stored on board."
   Similar opinions  were  expressed  by  Nikolai  Filozov,  a
spokesman  for  the  Russian  state  nuclear supervisory body,
Gosatomnadzor.
   But Froggatt  pointed out that most PWRs have problems with
their steam generators which can ultimately lead to  accidents
involving loss of coolant.

A ship  reactor  accident at a shipyard on the Russian Pacific
coast in 1985 killed several people  and  has  left  areas  of
Chazma Bay still contaminated.
   The largely state-owned Malaya Energetika ("Small  Energy")
company    is    hoping   to   market   the   reactor   design
internationally.  Poloushkin believes there is a market for at
least 100 and says his company is hoping to sell the plants to
China, Indonesia, the Philippines and other countries.
   Designs have been drawn up to use the KLT-40 as a basis for
a floating or shore-based  desalination  plant  (APVS-40),  an
underground  power plant and a shore-based power plant shipped
in by sea.  The APVS-40 which comprises  one  KLT-40  and  two
desalination  units,  can  supply up to 80,000 cubic meters of
water a day.
   The APVS-40   plant   was   designed   by  the  same  three
organizations  along  with  the  Yekaterinburg  Research   and
Development  Institute  of  Chemical  Mechanical  Engineering.
There has already been considerable interest  in  this  design
from  countries  in the Middle East,  Africa Latin America and
Asia.
   In 1992   The  Kurchatov  Institute  discussed  a  possible
contract  to  supply  a  plant  to  Israel,  but  negotiations
foundered  because  Israel  has  not  yet  signed  the Nuclear
Non-Proliferation Treaty.
   "We have  done  a range of studies for offshore and onshore
nuclear  power  plants  as  well  as  underground  plants  and
desalination stations based on the KLT-40," says OKBM Director
Fyodor Mitenkov.
   By simultaneous  manufacturing  the reactor,  floating base
and support facilities he  says  construction  time  could  be
reduced  to  as  little  as  three  and  a half years from the
signing of any contract  and  in  the  event  of  large  scale
manufacture unit costs could be reduced to $180 million each.
_______________________________________________________________

BIG DEMO AGAINST EXPANSION OF THE TEMPORARY STORE OF AHAUS AND
FOR THE CLOSURE OF ALL NUCLEAR PLANTS

The strong protest against the Castortransport to Gorleben has
turned the eyes of the public away from the temporary  storage
facility  in  Ahaus.  With  good  conscience  some politicians
consider now bringing the radioactive  waste  to  Ahaus  which
should go originally to Gorleben.
We don't  want  any nuclear waste dumps as long as radioactive
waste still is produced!
305 Castor-containers already  are  stored  in  the  temporary
nuclear  fuel  storage  site  of  Ahaus.  The  store  shall be
extended by the triple now.  This must be prevented  with  all
strength.
The red  green  coalition  of the country of NRW declares,  to
have withdrawn from the use of nuclear energy.  But apparently
it does not care about BEZ in Ahaus which in fact turns into a
permanent storage depot.  This store and the one  in  Gorleben
form  the  prerequisite  for  the  use  of  the atomic energy.
Without "waste  management  evidence"  -  as  the  stores  are
counted  for  - no nuclear power stations may be operated.  As
long as all nuclear power stations aren't switched off and the
amount  of  radioactive  waste  to dispose always is increased
further,  we aren't ready to discuss allegedly meaningful  and
sure waste management possibilities!
Against the  expansion of the BEZ-Ahaus we want to demonstrate
for the immediate turn energy of energy politics on 10-08-1996
in Ahaus (near Muenster)
The march  starts  at  the  city  hall place (Rathausplatz) at
11.00 hours.
This is  an  action  the  environment  cycle  tour  "Gegenwind
(headwind)".  "Gegenwind"  is  organized  by  a  team of young
people,  coordinated by the BUNDjugend NW (youth  organization
of  FoE Germany in Northrhine-Westfalia) with participation of
the departement for environment,  environmental  planning  and
farming ("Umweltministerium") in NRW.

Further information:  Johanna of the Driesch,  Bahnhofstr. 21,
48565 Steinfurt, tel: +49-2551-2301 or via e-mail:
BERND.HARMSEN@WIREPOOL.ruhr.de (Bernd Harmsen)
