Scandals

ILLEGAL NUCLEAR TRANSIT

Kaliningrad/Russia, July 29 (EDI),  - The secret  contract  on
nuclear  materials  transportation through one of the ports of
Kaliningrad,  a russian city near Baltic Sea, is working since
the  beginning  of  1996,  at least,  told unanimous source at
russian Kaliningrad' sea port on Sunday.  The source also told
that    the    nuclear    materials   are   sending   by   the
Sankt-Petersburgh'  company  "Isotop"  to  the   USA   through
Kaliningrad'  port.  It's  possible that the workers operating
materials  know  not  about  the   radioactivity   from.   The
Kaliningrad'   branch   of   GosAtomNadzor   (GAN  is  nuclear
supervisory body of  russian  president)  do  know  about  the
contract  but have no information about level of radioactivity
and the danger for port' workers.

Kaliningrad/Koenigsberg, July 30 (EDI), - The  "Amber-2"  ship
with nuclear  materials (uranium concentrate) arrived  to  the
waters of Kaliningrad' region.
There is 19 of 23-f containers with uranium. The ship is going
from Sankt-Petersburgh  port  to the USA,  San-Francisco.
The non-governmental  organizations  are  protesting  the ship
entering to the Kaliningrad' port;  the  ship  is  staying  in
Kaliningrad' territorial    waters   and   waiting   for   the
opportunity to  enter the seaport or for additional directions
from the authorities.
There is no any necessary equipment for  the  operations  with
radioactive materials  in  the  seaports  of Kaliningrad.  The
Kaliningrad is not included in the governmental  list  of  the
ports which  can  operate  radioactive  materials.  That's the
violation of the Russian law "On the use of nuclear power"  (#
41) if  the  ship will enter to the port and the port and city
authorities will allow that.  Because of no special  equipment
the port  workers as well as all the population of Kaliningrad
region are  in  very  dangerous  situation  when  even   small
accident will  be  followed  by  very  serious consequences of
radioactive contamination of the land and the sea.
Ministry of   atomic  power  of  Russia  (Minatom)  and  their
enterprise "Isotop" (Sankt-Petersburgh) has  a  contract  with
american parties to transport the uranium.  It's still unclear
who are american partners for them.  But clear that Minatom is
trying to  use  the  seaport  of  Kaliningrad  to  transit the
dangerous radioactive   materials.  In  1993  non-governmental
organizations sent to the local parliament the law project for
nuclear-free zone  in  Kaliningrad region and demanded to stop
all the operations with radioactive  materials.
If you want to support NGOs protesting sea nuclear transit   -
ask the editor for the message of support which you'll need to
send by fax.
PS. On August 1, EDI have got new information that the uranium
is  going  from  Kazakhstan  and  can  be  like the payment of
Kazakhstan to the US for some contracts or credits.
Source from Regional Environmental Protection Committee of Ka-
liningrad region.
_______________________________________________________________

ACCIDENT AT NUCLEAR PLANT KILLED WORKER

TWO ACCIDENTS  AT UKRAINIAN NUCLEAR PLANT KILL WORKER,  RELEASE
RADIATION. Two accidents at the Khmelnytsky nuclear power plant
on  25  July killed an employee and leaked radiation inside the
station,  Western and Ukrainian agencies reported the same day.
The  incidents  occurred  as the station's only working reactor
was being tested for a planned restart since it was  shut  down
on 20 April for maintenance. One employee sustained fatal inju-
ries and burns when a steam pipe burst during the testing.  Se-
veral  hours  later,  radioactive  water leaked into a nitrogen
storage area after workers failed to make a safety check. Plant
managers  said  radioactive contamination was limited to inside
the plant and that the leaks measured level three on the IAEA's
seven-level scale for nuclear accidents.  Chrystyna Lapychak

_______________________________________________________________
Baltics'

Kaliningrad/Russia, July  29  (EDI),  -  The   second   annual
environmental  camp for the youth is ended the work on Monday,
in russian national park "Kuronian Spit" on Baltic Sea  coast.
During  10 days expirienced activists of russian environmental
movement   and   environmental   scientists   trained    young
environmental activists under 18 for environmental campaigning
on community level.  The Direct action training was a part  of
camp'  programme  for 3 days like workshops on flora and fauna
of Baltic Sea region and ecosystem' recreation.

Kaliningrad/Russia, 28  July  (EDI),  -   A   new   electronic
conference  news.nuclear  will be opened for all users of APC'
(accociation of  progressive   communications)   networks   in
mid-August, told    representative    of    ECODEFENSE!,    an
environmental group  in  Kaliningrad,  on  Sunday.   The   new
conference will be focused on several aspects of nuclear power
developments in ex-USSR,  also on nuclear weapon thematics. It
will serve information as in Russian as in English. Organizers
of the conference believe in strong interest  of  specialists,
as  well  as activists of environmental movements worlwide for
new conference,  especially from the west because  of  unknown
before  information will be distributed through.

Bayer admits burying chemical waste in Patagonia BUENOS AIRES/
Argentina, July 24 (Reuter) - German pharmaceutical firm Bayer
AG acknowledged  on Wednesday it buried tons of chemicals in a
remote  area  of  Patagonia  after  authorities  requested  an
investigation into.

SANKT-PETERSBURG, July 13 (Nevskoe Vremya  newspaper),  -  THE
RUSSIAN  FEDERAL  SECURITY SERVICE PURPOSELY ALLOWED ALEXANDER
NIKITIN to obtain sensitive environmental information  on  the
Northern  Fleet  in  order  that the FSB then have evidence to
arrest him,  according to a recent statement by  Yuri  Shmidt,
Mr. Nikitin's lawyer. Mr. Shmidt has argued in public that the
Federal Security Service  (FSB)  had  followed  Mr.  Nikitin's
activities  as  soon  as  he  began  to work for the Norwegian
environmental  organization   Bellona   and   that   the   FSB
consciously allowed an "information leak".  Mr. Nikitin's time
in solitary confinement was recently extended to August  6  in
order that other he appear in court again. The report on which
the  accusation  of  treason  is   based   is   available   at
<a href=http://www.grida.no/ngo/bellona.>http://www.grida.no/ngo/bellona.</a>

SOSNOVII BOR,  July  12  (Smena  newspaper),  - THE LENINGRAD
NUCLEAR POWER PLANT (LAES) has  been  the  site  of  a  worker
sit-in  strike  in  the  past  days  as workers have protested
against the fact  that  salaries  not  received  since  March.
Workers also have demanded that working conditions be improved
and the station director  be  dismissed.  The  workers  report
working   in  closed  rooms  of  up  to  50  degrees  with  no
ventilation.  A state commission was  formed  on  July  12  to
review  the  reasons  for  the events of the strike and salary
payment situation.  Directors of  all  Russian  nuclear  power
plants  have  been  invited  to participate in the commission.
LAES  is  the  only  nuclear  station  in  Russia   which   is
financially independent of Rosenergoatom.

TALLINN, July  5  (Apiraev newspaper),  - THE SMUGGLING OF OIL
PRODUCTS INTO ESTONIA CONTINUES. The Estonian National Customs
Board  has  fined  yet another company guilty of smuggling oil
products into  Estonia  with  three  million  kroons  and  has
confiscated their products. The customs confiscated a total of
6,000 tons of oil products imported by AS Boliden from Russia.
The shipment consisted of low-octane petrol brand A76, A92 and
diesel fuel.  Rein Talvik,  director general of  the  National
Customs   Board,   said   that   Estonian   customs  officials
intercepted the first tankcars with smuggled oil  products  on
May 29.  Yet the shipment was divided into several lots, and a
Russian refinery kept sending the tankcars  to  Estonia  until
June 20,  according to an Estonian customs official.

IGNALINA NUCLEAR  POWER PLANT,  July 3 (ELTA) - SWEDISH AID TO
LITHUANIAN NUCLEAR SECURITY has been presented in the form  of
new  computer equipment for the Ignalina Power Plant.  Swedish
Nuclear Power Inspectorate  experts  delivered  computers  and
necessary  software  to  the  Lithuanian  State  Atomic Energy
Security  Inspection  on  July  3.  The  equipment  will  help
Lithuanian  atomic  energy security inspection to improve work
reliability,  as many of the present operations done  manually
are now to be carried out by computers.  The equipment is also
designed  for   use   by   other   educational   and   medical
institutions,   construction  and  oil  companies  which  have
activities related to the nuclear field.  The  equipment  cost
more than 250,000 Swedish crowns.
_______________________________________________________________
        
Ex-USSR'

Chernobyl gave  Greek  children  leukaemia-study,  Maggie Fox,
LONDON July 24 (Reuter) - Greek children who were  exposed  to
radioactive  fallout  from the 1986 Chernobyl nuclear disaster
while still in their mothers' wombs were twice  as  likely  to
develop leukaemia.

Nuke power  plants can solve energy crisis in NAKHODKA/Russia,
July 24 (Itar-Tass) -  Viktor  Gnezdilov,  the  mayor  of  the
Russian  Far  Eastern  city  of  Nakhodka,  told  Itar-Tass on
Wednesday he believed that underground  nuclear  power  plants
can solve energy crisis.
     
Moscow/Russia, July 28 (EDI) -  The  russian  enironmentalists
are setting  up  the  action  camp  near  Rostov nuclear power
plant, central Russia.  The camp is beginning on August  7  to
prevent the start of the plant where unit-1 is 95%  completed.
The local authority and population are both against  this  NPP
which is big threat to fish population in the region.

41 tons of caviar, 807 tons of fish confiscated, MOSCOW, July
25 (Itar-Tass) - A total of 41 tons of  caviar,  807  tons  of
fish and marine products, fishing nets 347 kilometers long and
869 floating facilities worth 19  billion  roubles  have  been
confiscated in the 1996

Moscow/Russia, July    25    (EDI),    -   The   ECOJURIS,   a
non-governmental organization in Moscow,  working  to  protect
environmental  rights  of  russian  population,  organizes the
training for lawyers working in environmental non-governmental
groups in Russia. The training will be started in October 1996
and will be focused on information rights of russian citizens,
strategy  in  trial,  public participation in decision making,
etc.  The financial support is provided  by  Ford  Foundation.
_______________________________________________________________

SACRED EARTH NETWORK' SEMINAR FOR ENVIRONMENTAL ACTIVISTS

On July  12-14,  the  Sacred  Earth  Network held a seminar in
Nakhabino (a suburb of Moscow) for environmental activists who
concentrate  on  alternative  energy  and  sustainable  living
issues.  The seminar was  run  in  cooperation  with  Golubka,
ECOLOGIA,  and  the Center for Information and Coordination of
the  Socio-Ecological  Union  (CCI-SEU)  and  was   aimed   at
promoting   increased   communication   and   cooperation   on
alternative energy work in Eurasia.

The seminar begin with team building excercizes led by Golubka
staff  and  ended with an on-line Internet training session at
the offices of  CCI-SEU  lead  by  Alexander  Georgievsky  and
Sergei   Diamon   (Ecoline).  Seminar  participants  exchanged
information on  funding  sources,  approaches  to  information
management and proposed future cooperative work.

Upon conclusion   of   the   seminar   and   working   groups,
participants  agreed  to  initiate  an  e-mail  conference  to
formulate  a  project  proposal  for  increasing  awareness on
alternative  energy  and  sustainable  living  systems  across
Eurasia.

The list  of  the  seminar participants (14 representatives of
environmental NGOs in ex-USSR) can be sent on request.

More information:  Susan Cutting, SEN' In-country coordinator,
Moscow/Russia,  e-mail:  sen@glas.apc.org,  tel: 7-095-7190150
_______________________________________________________________
