CONTENTS

News cleeps
JOURNALISTS IN RUSSIA + KGB GUIDE BOOK

Conflict
NUCLEAR WORKERS STOP SIT-IN

Contract
RUSSIA-KOREA' RADIOACTIVE TRADE
_______________________________________________________________
JOURNALISTS' RIGHTS ARE VIOLATED

MOSCOW (E-C) Belarus, Russia, Tadjikistan, and Ukraine are the
republics   where   journalists'   rights  are  violated  most
frequently and grossly,  according to Oleg Panfilov,  head  of
the  monitoring  service  of  the  Glasnost Defence Foundation
(GDF), speaking at a press-conference on 22 July.
Panfilov presented the Foundation's account on  violations  of
journalists'  rights,  based on the information of Russian and
the foreign press,  human rights organisations  and  the  GDF.
Panfilov  pointed  to  the  murder  in  late June of Aleksandr
Motrenko,  an  employee  of  the  Simferopol   radio   station
"Trans-m-radio," by officers of the law-enforcement organs, as
a particularly serious attack on the press.

NIZHNI TAGIL JOURNALISTS ON HUNGER STRIKE

NIZHNI TAGIL.  For a fourth day Pavel Gross,  a journalist  of
the municipal television studio "Tagil-TV," has been on hunger
strike.  One of his colleagues told "Express-Chronicle" on  22
July  that the basic condition for the cessation of his hunger
strike was the payment of arrears in wages to  all  "Tagil-TV"
employees for May and June this year.

KGB GUIDE-BOOK

MOSCOW (E-C)  The  launching  of  the  book  "KGB Guide to the
cities of the world" was held on 24 July in  the  premises  of
the External Intelligence Service (SVR) of Russia. The book is
presented as "an original guide book,  which will  familiarise
the  reader  with  the  sights  of cities,  [and] recount many
unknown facts from the history of espionage." It was issued by
"Sovershenno Sekretno" publishers,  with a print-run of 20,000
copies.
The preface,  written by  Yuri  Senkevich  of  the  television
programme  "Traveller's Club," states that the "book is unique
not  only  in  its  contents,  but  also  in  its  authors   -
professionals from the external intelligence of the former KGB
of the USSR,  who in various years worked in New York, London,
Rome,  Paris,  Cairo, Mexico and Bangkok." Most of the authors
of the book attended the launching:  Leonid  Kolosov,  Mikhail
Liubimov,  Lev  Bausin,  Oleg Brykin and Pavel Yefremov.  Yuri
Kobaladze,  head of SVR's centre for public  liason,  declared
that "the intelligence [service] received no money,  no income
and royalties from the publication of the guide book" and  the
"the  SVR  presented  the  book  because it was written by our
former agents."
_______________________________________________________________

                NUCLEAR WORKERS STOP SIT-IN

By Yevgenia Borisova

The workers  of  the  nuclear  power  plant  in  Sosnovy   Bor
suspended  their  sit-in  Friday last week for the second time
this month when they learned that their director's resignation
was accepted by the minister of atomic energy of Russia.
Alexander Barantsov,   head  of  the  Leningrad  Atomic  Power
Station's (LAES) trade union,  said,  "We suspended the action
until  August  8  when  we  got  the  signed order that [plant
director Anatoly] Yeperin is gone  and  the  new  acting  head
assured  us  that they are working on a plan to get out of the
crisis situation."
Beginning in mid-June,  the workers,  who said they  have  not
been paid for three months, were arranging meetings of protest
and sit-ins at the plant,  urging the LAES management  to  pay
their wages.
Barantsov said LAES owed the employees about 30 billion rubles
($6 million) in unpaid wages dating  back  to  the  middle  of
April.
LAES management  said they did not have enough cash to pay the
wages,  because 95 percent of their financial  operations  are
barter deals.
Barantsov said   Monday   that  Valery  Lebedev,  LAES'  chief
engineer,  who was approved as acting head of  LAES  beginning
July 29,  promised to provide a plan for management changes at
LAES by August 2.
He added that by August 7 a plant to repay the  workers  would
be prepared by LAES management, and a draft plan to get out of
the crisis will be ready by August 9.
Barantsov said he believed this week's meetings with the heads
of  workshops  and  departments  at LAES will help to create a
plan for coping with the crisis,  and  that  he  expects  that
Leningrad  Oblast  Governor  Alexander  Belyakov would come to
LAES to speak to the workers this week.
Lebedev was not available for comment Monday.
The LAES is a Chenobyl-type nuclear power plant located in the
town  of  Sosnovy Bor,  approximately 70 kilometers (43 miles)
northeast of St Petersburg.
_______________________________________________________________

     RUSSIA TO REPAY LOANS WITH URANIUM, HELICOPTERS

SEOUL - Russia will repay part of  South  Korea's  loans  with
enriched  uranium  and helicopters instead of steel as earlier
agreed on, the Finance and Economy Ministry announced today.
The replacement of loan payment items was agreed upon after  a
meeting  in Moscow late last month between the two sides,  the
ministry said.
Under the agreement,  Russia will supply,  instead  of  steel,
enriched uranium worth 75 million U.S. dollars and helicopters
worth 15 million dollars.
Besides the enriched uranium and helicopters,  Russia is  also
supposed  to  provide South Korea within the year with defense
equipment worth 154  million  dollars,  aluminium  51  million
dollars, enriched uranium 18 million dollars and helicopters 8
million dollars.
Of the loans totaling 1.47  billion  dollars  Russia  obtained
from  South  Korea,  Moscow had repaid 40.4 million dollars in
kind by the end of July last year -- 19.3 million  dollars  in
aluminium  and  21.1  million dollars in helicopters.

