Editorial...

VICTORY OF "STOP NUCLEAR SHIPPING!" CAMPAIGN

ON JULY 30, The "Amber-2" ship with nuclear materials (uraniumconcentrate) arrived  to  the  waters  of Kaliningrad' region.There were  19  of 23-f containers with uranium.  The ship was
going from Sankt-Petersburgh  port  to the USA, San-Francisco.
"Amber-2" was  planning  to  visit Kaliningrad seaport to take
additional equipment for the carrying it to the USA.
The ex-USSR Antinuclear Campaign  received  information  about
dangerous transport  from own sources in Kaliningrad and imme-
diately started the fax-attack of local authorities.  The  de-
mands of the campaign were: 1) to close seaport for any nucle-
ar transit;  2) to accept by the regional  administration  the
regional status  of  territory without nuclear power,  nuclear
weapon and nuclear transit.

Comments 1:
The ex-USSR  Antinuclear  campaign  was founded by ECODEFENSE!
group (Baltic Sea region)  and  Socio-Ecological  Union  Int'l
(the  union  of  about  250  grassroot environmental groups in
ex-USSR). These two NGOs were campaigning in 1993 to stop nuke
transit  through Kaliningrad when first nuclear shipping there
took place.  From 1993,  the ECODEFENSE!  started to fight for
nuclear-free  zone with no opportunity for nuke transit in Ka-
liningrad region.
"

Parallel to fax-attack, the campaign started to organize local
resistance to nuclear shipping. Also, together with some jour-
nalists the campaign started the dialogue with local authority
to force them for "nuclear-free zone" decision immediately.

Some officials of Kaliningrad authorities were interviewed  in
the begining of the campaign:
Correspondent - Do you know about the ship with uranium?
1. Regional administration: No answer.
2. Vice-Major of the city: Uranium? it's terrible! what to do?
3. Regional committee of nature protection:  No, we know about
this ship nothing.
4. Gosatomnadzor (nuclear control organization of  president):
It's not dangerous. Cor.: How do you know? Have you any infor-
mation about the ship?  G.:  No,  we have no information,  but
it's not dangerous.
5. The  port authorities:  The head of regional administration
commanded to organize the service for  this  ship.  We  should
work on this ship or we'll loose our jobs.
Comments 2:  Ministry  of atomic power of Russia (Minatom) and
their enterprise "Isotop" (Sankt-Petersburgh) has  a  contract
with  american  parties  to transport the uranium.  It's still
unclear who are american partners for them. But clear that Mi-
natom  is  trying to use the seaport of Kaliningrad to transit
the dangerous radioactive materials.  In 1993 non-governmental
organizations sent to the local parliament the law project for
nuclear-free zone in Kaliningrad region and demanded  to  stop
all the operations with radioactive materials.
"

The reasons why NGOs wants to stop this transit are very clear.
There is no any necessary equipment for  the  operations  with
radioactive materials in the seaports of Kaliningrad.  The Ka-
liningrad is not included in  the  governmental  list  of  the
ports which can operate radioactive materials. That's the vio-
lation of the Russian law "On the use of nuclear power" (# 41)
if  the ship will enter to the port and the port and city aut-
horities will allow that.  Because of no special equipment the
port  workers as well as all the population of Kaliningrad re-
gion are in very dangerous situation when even small  accident
will  be  followed by very serious consequences of radioactive
contamination of the land and the sea.

Comments 3: On 20 of May, 1996, the soldier died from leukemia
- he  guarded  same ship with radioactive materials in 1995 at
Kaliningrad seaport.
"

The ship was staying in Kaliningrad'  territorial  waters  and
waiting for  the opportunity to enter the seaport or for addi-
tional directions from the authorities for more than  two  we-
eks. That  time The ex-USSR antinuclear campaign was trying to
talk with local authorities and this talking was supported  by
internatinal faxes very effectively.  Thanks to several people
from Europarliament,  Greenpeaces of Russia,  Sweden and  USA,
other NGOs and some UN' awarded physicians the authorities un-
derstood also that international public opinion  is  attracted
for situation  in  Kaliningrad,  that NGOs are still powerfull
and alive in Russia.
    
Since the July 30 press-release of the  antinuclear  campaign,
american radio "Svoboda" (Freedom) and Radio of Russia distri-
buted information about the ship to all  around  former  USSR.
The main political newspaper in Russia "Izvestia" prepared the
article about. Local media in Kaliningrad published and broad-
casted a  lot.  The  governmental  radio agency in Kaliningrad
broadcasted very environmentalist-friendly special news  issue
against nuclear shipping.
    
The head  of  regional Kaliningrad administration Yury Matoch-
kin, the major of Kaliningrad Vitaly Shipov,  the chairman  of
governmental environmental protection committee of Kaliningrad
Vladimir Litvinenko and local mass-media have received totally
about 15  international faxes protesting the nuclear shipping.
The campaign also organized the phone call'  action  in  Kali-
ningrad that  resulted in some thousands of calls of local ci-
tizens asking the administration of Kaliningrad  region  about
nuclear shipping.

Finally, the result of two weeks dialogue, phone call' action,
international fax pressure and effective work with  press  was
local authority' decision to give no permission for the nucle-
ar transit. The ex-USSR antinuclear campaign did one more step
to the nuclear-free zone  in Kaliningrad region.

The nuclear  industry  have lost up to million of US $ because
of antinuclear campaign' protests. At present time, the Baltic
Marine Prosecution started to investigate the case and sent to
Kaliningrad seaport' authority the message demanding  to  stop
any nuclear transit through Kaliningrad until the case will be
inmvestigated finally.

For more  information:
Vladimir Sliviak - Int'l Nuclear Campaigner
Socio-Ecological Union International/ECODEFENSE!
Ex-USSR Antinuclear Campaign
 ed@cci.glasnet.ru  or  ecodefense@glas.apc.org 
WWW <a href=http://cci.glasnet.ru/antinuclear.html>http://cci.glasnet.ru/antinuclear.html</a>
_______________________________________________________________
PRESS-RELEASE
AUGUST 13, 1996

LITHUANIA: EIB LOAN FOR ROAD  UPGRADING VIA BALTICA

The European Investment Bank (EIb), the long-term financing
institution of the European Union, is providing ECU 20 million
for the rehabilitation of the  internationally  important  Via
Baltica road in Lithuania.  The 20 year EIB loan to the Repub-
lic of Lithuania will be used by the Lithuanian Road Administ-
ration  (LRA)  for upgrading a road section between Kaunas and
the Polish border to a 2-lane highway.  Works  will  start  in
1997 and are expected to be completed by the end of 2000.
    Via Baltica is the most important road link  between  Hel-
sinki  and Warsaw through Estonia,  Latvia and Lithuania.  The
most important upgrading needs are in Lithuania.  The EIB loan
is to cover some 34 %  of the rehabilitation which is also re-
ceiving financial support from the European Bank  for  Recons-
truction and Development (EBRD) and from the Nordic Investment
Bank (NIB).  The EU-Phare Programme is concentrating its grant
aid  financing  to improve border crossing.  The nearby Polish
sections are being upgraded with the help of the World Bank.
    The development  of  a  reliable route linking Helsinki to
Warsaw is being prommoted by the Via Baltica  Monitoring  Com-
mittee, involving senior officials from all countries involved
and the European Commission,  and supported by the Swedish and
Finnish Governments which provide the committee's chairmanship
and secretariat respectively.  Commenting the  loan,  EIB  Vi-
ce-President Woifgang Roth said: "The importance of Via Balti-
ca for all countries in the region, including the Nordic coun-
tries and the European Union,  is well known to the EIB.  With
regard to Lithuania, the project will strengthen its role as a
transit country,  accelerate regional economic cooperation and
facilitate the country's integration into the European Union."
    Note to the Editor: EIB lending in Central and Eastern Eu-
    rope takes place under
a mandate  from  the Bank's Board of Governors (the fifteen EU
Finance Ministers) and is  concentrated  in  eleven  countries
linked to the EU under cooperation agreements.  The total aut-
horised for the period 1990-95 is ECU 4.7 billion of which <a name=L10001></a><a href=#L10002>so</a>-
me  ECU  3.9  billion have <a name=L10002></a><a href=#L10003>so</a> far been provided:  Poland (1126
million),  Hungary (832 million), the Czech Republic (737 mil-
lion), Romania (385 million), Bulgaria (286 million), Slavakia
(253 million),  Slovenia (120 million),  Estonia (68 million),
Lithuania  (59  million),  Albania  (34 million) and Latvia (5
million).  A new mandate for EIB lending in the CEECs for  the
period 1997-2000 is expected soon.
    For further details,  please contact the EIB's Information
and  Communications Department (Mr Max Messner,  tel 352 43 79
31 50)
    The conversion  rates used by the EIB for statistical pur-
poses during  the  current  ouarter  are  these  obtaining  on
31/03/96, when ECU 1 = DEM 1.89, 5.02876 LTL.

_______________________________________________________________
