ALBANIEN

Albanian civil Society Foundation

(by Steven Sampson) Albania has about 350 NGOs. The First
Albanian NGOs were started in 1991 most of the Albanian NGOs are
weak, as they lack essential resources, have inadequate
coordination among each other and weak links to the
international NGO community. NGOs and the government are unaware
of how to work with each other (or unwilling), and the image of
Albanian NGOs in the public is weak and not always positive. The
Albanian Civil Society Foundation (ACSF) has been established in
order to improve this situation. Located in Tirana and with a
five-member staff, the ACSF has been operating since March 1995.
Funding comes from a 1 million dollar grant from the Danish
Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Danida) to last until the end of
1997. The goal of the ACSF is to strengthen the development of
civil society in Albania, mainly through support to Albanian
NGOs through training and project grants. ACSF is furthermore
providing information to Albanian NGOs, between NGOs and the
government, and especially to link Albanian NGOs with foreign
counterparts and donors. The ACSF is the only foundation in
Albania providing support to the full spectrum of Albanian NGOs.
ACSF has the following programs:

Grant Making to NGOs: The ACSF has disbursed about 80 grants to
Albanian NGOs in all sectors (including environment, women,
youth, human rights, ethnic minority, agricultural development,
business/commerce, civic education, social service). In granting
activities, the ACSF collaborates closely with other NGO support
programs, including UNDP, the Soros Foundation, ORT Democracy
Network Program and the Albanian NGO Forum.

Training Activities: The ACSF also conducts and funds training
courses for Albanian NGO on a wide range of topics such as
fund-raising, management issues, media relations, government
relations, etc. The ACSF has commissioned a survey (in
collaboration with the Washington based International Center for
Non-Profit Law) of the legal framework of Albanian NGOs. This
will lead to a range of seminars and handbooks on legal issues.

A Citizens Center: A major activity for the foundation in 1996
is the newly created "Citizens Center" in which Albanian NGO
members and individuals can meet, get information, arrange
courses, receive phone calls, faxes, mail, and (hopefully by
June 1996) e-mail, make photocopies, and utilize the computer
equipment.

Information Services: A part of the Albanian Civil Society
Foundation is an Information Office that shall facilitate
linkages between Albanian NGOs and their potential partners,
such as donors, foreign visitors, agencies seeking contacts with
an Albanian NGO, other Albanian NGOs, Government authorities,
the general public, etc. The Albanian Civil Society Foundation
publishes a quarterly Newsletters in Albanian and English, and
publishes the first comprehensive, frequently updated Guide to
Albanian Non-Governmental Organisations.

Organization: The Albanian Civil Society Foundation is
registered as an Albanian NGO and is governed by a nine-member
board, eight of whom are Albanians. Board meetings are held
about every 6 weeks. The staff is headed by executive Director
Rolanda Dhimitri. The Information Officer is Elvis Toci. The
ACSF's budget derives from the Danish Government aid to Albania.
It is planned that the foundation can become self-sustaining.

Contacts: Rolanda Dhimitri's home number: Phn/fax +3 55 42
26497, or via Steven Sampson, Project coordinator, Phn: +45 3332
0251, Fax: +45 3332 1345, E-mail: sting@inet.uni-c.dk


BALLERINA Workshop For Baltic Sea Environmental Cooperation

Stockholm - The first BALLERINA (BALtic Sea Region On-line
Environmental Information Resources for INternet Access)
workshop brought together about 65 representatives of a wide
variety of government, academic, and non-government
organizations from the Baltic Sea region to Swedish
Environmental Protection Agency headquarters on June 13-14 to
discuss the development of an Internet-based environmental
network in the region. Participants at the workshop expressed
unanimous support for the BALLERINA initiative. The aim of the
workshop was to discuss and provide guidelines on how to make
the BALLERINA initiative the gateway for environmental
information on the Baltic Sea region on the Internet through the
use of a series of World Wide Web pages with a coordinating
function of the many existing information sources now available
about the environment in the Baltic Sea region. A representative
from the Great Lakes Commission, Carol Cratza, presented the
experience of the Great Lakes Information Network (GLIN). The
BALLERINA initiative will be able to draw on the example of GLIN
as a successful electronic network concerning the environmental
issues of international waterbodies. An ad hoc committee was
designated and approved by the workshop for further organization
and realization of the BALLERINA initiative. A first general
assembly of BALLERINA participants is now planned for early 1997.

Dr. Sindre Langaas, phone +46-8-161737, e-mail
 langaas@grida.no . Internet: <a href=http://www.grida.no/ballerina/>http://www.grida.no/ballerina/</a>

Kurzmeldungen: (Ecodefense; Infobalt; X-USSR Nuke News)

Baltic State Leaders have sverely criticized a proposed
agreement between Russia and the United States 

for Russians to station 600 armored vehicles in the Pskov region
at Russia's border with Estonia and Latvia, in place of the 180
vehicles there at present. The desire of Russia to increase its
forces in this area is considered to be a counter measure to
NATO expansion. Russia, as a result of the proposed agreement,
would be allowed to station arms at its boundaries with the
Baltic and Nordic states in 5 times higher numbers than the
conventional arms agreements allow. (ELTA)

Baltic Sea States Adopt Cooperation Programme:

(Kalmar) - The foreign ministers of the Baltic Sea states on
Wednesday adopted an action programme to boost regional
cooperation in crime-fighting, the economy, the environment and
nuclear safety. The 11 foreign ministers, representing nine
states around the Baltic Sea plus Norway and Iceland, hammered
out the details of the 17-page document on Tuesday evening and
Wednesday morning. Several investments in the region are
planned, including road and railway maintenance and harbour
developments, totalling 40 billion kronor ($6,01 billion) for
the 1995-1999 repiod. Estonia, Latvia, Lithuania, Poland and
Russia will receive assistance in cleaning up the environment,
particularly with regard to treating toxic waste.

Russia-Baltics-Poland - The Highway Project "Via Hanseatic"
between St.Petersburg and Gdansk,

which would link several former Hanseatic cities, is to be
supported by funds from the European Union. More than 900
million ECU are expected to be invested in project before 1999.
This project would complement "Via Baltica", which is to lead
between Helsinki, Tallinn, and Warsaw. (Vecher. Peterburg)

Estonian Ministries Of Finance And Transport And Communication

have publicly disagreed on a highway project to connect Tallinn,
through Tartu and Voru, with the existing St. Petersburg-Kiev
Highway. Ministry of Transport representative Lembit Kiviloo
stated that the project is without perspective for Estonia. The
Via Russica project would include upgrading the existing
Tallinn-Tartu road into a highway, connecting Tartu with Voru
via Petseri (Pechora), and renovating the railway link from
Valga to Pihkva (Pskov). Southeastern Estonia would in this way
become a transit point from Russia to Scandinavia. The Ministry
of Transport representative believes that the development of
railways should be the sole main priority, as today only five
percent of cargo traffic goes by highway. (ETA, 26 Apr.)

Latvia Spent Significntly Less Last Year On Environmental
Protection 

than in the previous year, according to the Central Statistical
Bureau of Latvia. About 36 million U.S. dollars were spent on
environmental protection and the rational utilization of natural
resources in Latvia in 1995, which represents a decrease of 45
percent in comparison with 1994, according to the Statistical
Bureau. (LETA)

Construction Of A New Hydro Electric Power Plant

on the Daugava River in the vicinity of Daugavpils is under
consideration. Scientists from the Latvian Environmental
Protection center, members of the organization Daugavas Loki,
and local farmers are all opposed to the project. They argue
that environmental damage will exceed any economic advantage
gained from the new power plant. Local government and business
interests are in favor of the construction to provide relatively
inexpensive electric power and to create new job opportunities
in the region. (LETA, 14 May)

ECAT-Riga officially closed his office on 1st June 1996 but
there are still some westerners 

working in the Latvian Environmental Consulting and Monitoring
Centre (ECMC) which is the successor of ECAT-Riga. The European
Union funding for ECAT-Riga has run out and the Latvian staff of
the ECMC is paid by the Latvian state. The ECMC is subordinated
to the Latvian Ministry for Environmental Protection and
Regional Development. Although there will be in the future a new
ECAT-Riga-office which will be responsible for environmental
projects which are financed by foreign institutions the old
e-mail adress will not exist anymore. You can reach the ECMC by
ist new e-mail adress vkmc@main.vvi.gov.lv.

A nuclear Fuel Storage Facility is planned at the Ignalina power
plant 

and will be financed by Ontario Hydro Company together with
tenders from Canadian AECL and German GNB companies. Spent
nuclear fuel in Ignalina is stored today in underwater
reservoirs situated under the plant reactors. The reservoirs
will soon be full. (ELTA)

Lithuania's Ignalina nuclear Power Plant,

the home of two Chernobyl-type reactors, remains a major source
of concern to the Baltic state's Nordic neighbors, stated one
Scandinavian diplomat in Vilnius. "There is a general level of
concern in the Nordic countries about the possibility of an
accident at Ignalina," he said. Ignalina supplies about 80
percent of Lithuania's electricity, making Lithuania the most
nuclear-power dependent country in the world. Four reactors were
originally planned for Ignalina, but construction on the third
was halted in 1987 by massive public protests in the wake of the
Chernobyl disaster.

Police In Lithuania Have Seized Ten Kg Of Caesium-133

and arrested two men who were trying to sell it, the country's
prosecutor's office said. Lithuania and Baltic neighbors Latvia
and Estonia are suspected of being key gateways for the
smuggling to the West of radioactive and rare metals pilfered
from the former Soviet bloc. Caesium can be produced as a deadly
by-product of nuclear fission but the prosecutor's office said
the caesium-133 variety is not radioactive. It is, however, very
poisonous. The two men were arrested in Kaunas after they tried
to sell the metal, a prosecution statement said.

A $ 6.7 million loan from the Nordic Investment Bank for
Lithuania shall help finance 

the construction of the Via Baltica trans-European highway.
Lithuanian deputy communication minister Algirdas Sakalys told
Interfax that final results were expected from loan talks by
Tuesday. Lithuania is planning to build 100-km of the highway by
the year 2000 for $60 million.

The Lithuanian Parliament has ratified the Berne Convention, the
European Agreement on Wild Nature 

and Natural Environment Protection. Lithuanian Minister of the
Environment Bronius Bradauskas said ratification of this
document was a significant step for Lithuania in its integration
into European Union environmental structures. The Berne
Convention came into force on July 1, 1982. It has been signed
by 31 European states and is an important international
agreement for the preservation of nature, wild vegetation, and
rare animals. (ELTA)

The Environmental Threat to the Lithuanian forests is serious
today, but not catastrophic, 

said Forestry Minister Albertas Vasiliauskas at a news
conference. Up to 3,000-3,200 cubic meters of wood have been
felled annually in Lithuania's forests since 1961, whereas the
maximum possible output could reach 5,000 cubic meters without a
harm to the forest resources, he said. A 1.5-fold increase in
wood production, followed by its export, is expected over the
course of the next five years. He described new plans to build a
new modern pulp mill in Lithuania to produce about 300 thousand
tons of pulp per year, which would satisfy Lithuania's own
demand and allow exports of about 100 thousand tons. (ELTA)


Lukashenka calls For Nuclear-Free Zone

(aus: X-USSR Nuke News) Minsk - The president of Belarus on
Wednesday said the nations of central and eastern Europe should
be kept free of nuclear weapons. Belarus inherited part of
Moscow's nuclear arsenal after 1991 Soviet collapse, along mwith
Russia, Ukraine and Kazakhstan. Belarus promised to disarm by
the end of 1996. "I propose that the former socialist countries
of eastern Europe, Belarus, Ukraine and the Baltic countries
should set up a nuclear free zone," President Alexander
Lukashenka said. But he added that "a unilateral step toward
nuclear disarmament is not enough" and expressed concern about
NATO's eastward expansion.

Bulgarien

Eu and Bulgaria sign agreement On nuclear power plant

(Based on Commission Press Release IP/96/431 of 5/21/1996)
Following a signed agreement between the European Commission and
the government of Bulgaria, Unit 1 of Kozloduy Nuclear Power
Plant was shut down for safety tests on 15 May 1996. Last
winter, concern was expressed when Unit 1 was restarted by the
Bulgarian government despite advice from EU experts that tests
were needed to ensure that the reactor was safe. If the present
tests show that the safety of Unit 1 needs to be improved, the
necessary work will be carried out. The decision on whether to
restart Unit 1 will be taken on the basis of common agreement
between the main designer and Bulgarian and EU experts. The
Commission will provide assistance from the PHARE technical
assistance programme for the Central and East European countries
for the tests and for helping with alternative energy supplies
for winter 1996/1997. The Kozloduy Nuclear Power Plant generates
around 40% of Bulgaria's electricity. The power plant has six
nuclear reactors, of which Units 1 to 4 are of the oldest type
of Soviet-designed pressurized water reactors. Units 5 and 6 on
the other hand are the most modern type of Soviet nuclear
reactors. In 1994 European experts expressed the opinion that
the reactor pressure vessel (the reinforced container within
which the nuclear reactions take place) of Kozloduy Unit 1 had
to be tested to assess its safety. The Commission has been
working closely with the Bulgarian government to ensure that
until these reactors are permanently closed they are operated in
the safest possible conditions.

MOLDOVA

Folgende Informationen ueber Moldavien aus: News From Moldova,
#4, April 1996, #5, May 1996, #6, June 1996.

Sergiu Fandofan on Ecological Problems in Moldova

(Sergiu Fandofan is General Director of the Department on the
Environmental Protection and Natural Resources of the Republic
of Moldova) - First of all it refers to the water resources
preservation and water use problem. The problem of water supply
for the population, especially in the southern regions of the
country, is closely connected with the health of the nation. We
even had to appeal to the foreign experts and international
organizations for help. The latter, by the way, expressed their
willingness to assist to Moldova with a complex programme "APELE
MOLDOVEI" working out. The experts of the Danube convention have
joined this project <a name=L10001></a><a href=#L10002>so</a> far, as Moldova enjoys the rights as its
member. Till recent time, the Department has been mainly
concerned about the spring floods situation. According to the
local experts' estimation, the main water artery of Moldova, the
Dniester river, was under a threat of pollution, because of the
heavy snow melting.In the neighboring Ukraine a threatening
situation might appear in the region, because of probability of
the upper Dniester tank floods. It could lead to the necessity
of letting out an artificial sea, which took the main blow of
the accident at the Stebnikovsky Chemical Complex in 1983, when
a considerable part of the harmful emission was managed to be
kept in the alignment of the dike. Every time when speaking
about water resources conservation in Moldova, a question of "a
building of the century", an oil terminal in Gurgulesti, appears
to be inevitably. Not only ecologists were frightened by the
scope of <a name=L10002></a><a href=#L10003>so</a>-called "giantmania". This syndrome is still kept
going nowadays. However, as the western experience shows, even
those industrial monsters could work normally without any
environmental impacts, if the strict ecological requirements are
observed thoroughly. Today the economy of Moldova needs some
alternative sources of power supply. The terminal building in
Gurgulesti undoubtedly is one of the real ways of this uneasy
problem solution. Nevertheless, taking into consideration the
mistakes of the past, one should definitely remember
indisputable truth: no economical necessity of a certain project
could prevail over the ecological safety considerations and the
international obligations of Moldova before the neighboring
states. As to the building of the oil terminal, its
environmental impact assessment will be surely done. This
tedious work is entrusted to the scientific center of the same
profile - the National Institute of Ecology, said Sergiu
Fandofan in conclusion.

Dendroparks: Hard Times

by Valentina Malikova, IEA "Altair" - During a voluntary day of
work in the dendropark the citizens of Chisinau fixed more than
five hectares of the unique plantations. On the National Day of
Trees Planting forty volunteers came to the park: people of
different professions, schoolchildren, pensioners. Together with
the officials of the dendropark they cleaned flower-beds from
the last year's leaves and helped to refresh the trees'
saplings. The dendropark is a famous sight of Moldova's capital.
It captures visitors by its inimitable beauty, recognized as a
landmark of landscape architecture. Situated in the place of the
busy freeways almost in the centre of the city this green area
clears the air and absorbs traffic noise. Not accidentally a
small lake here was chosen by wild ducks for a winter stay while
nightingales got accustomed to living in brushwood of the
bushes. The dendropark of Chisinau was set up forty five years
ago by the scientists of the Botanical Garden of the Republican
Academy of Sciences. Now flora representatives from almost all
the continents grow and fruit here. (...) The shortage of
finances causes high staff fluidity. For the same reason it's
quite hard to provide protection of green plants as well as the
proper care of them. Many (...) people (...) use this
unfavourable situation to destroy shrubs' and trees' collection.
The State Department for Environmental Protection and Natural
Resources hopes for the improvement of the situation in the
dendroparks with the adoption of the Law on Protected Natural
Territories. Well, we shall see the outcome.

A Right To Informaton

by Natalya Sinyaeva - The working group of the Ecological
Society "Biotica" started the elaboration of the draft law of
Moldova on the Right to Ecological Information. "The work
supported by the USAID through Eurasia Foundation is planned to
be over this September," Petr Gorbunenko, the president of
Biotica, reported. The importance of the legislative regulation
of the right to get the ecological information is explained by
the fact that despite the right reflected in the Constitution of
Moldova neither citizens, nor their organizations or journalists
could use it to the full advantage as the mechanism of its
realization has not been worked out properly. Whereas in 1990
the countries of the European Union worked out the minimal rules
on getting the information about the environmental conditions.
The inculcation of these rules into the national legislation is
being finished this year. Moldova took the commitment of
providing this right after signing the Declaration of Sofia
Conference of the Environmental Protection European Ministers
(1995). The realization of the right to the ecological
information should permit NGOs and citizens a possibility of
getting full information about potentially dangerous enterprises
and to make a proper public environmental impact assessment.
Certainly some resistance on the part of the authorities towards
the adoption of the effective law could be awaited still the
initiators hope to overcome these obstacles. In case of success
it will be the first law of the kind in CIS countries.

Ecological Society "Biotica", e-mail: bio@mdearn.cri.md

Pollution And Infections

by Valentina Malikova, IEA "Altair" - With summer coming to
Moldova, microbe pollution monitoring of the rivers, lakes and
other open reservoirs has been reinforced. The systematic
laboratory tests of water samples for timely exposure of the
acute intestinal infections, including a vibrio of cholera have
been set. "The acute intestinal infections present a serious
problem for the health of the population of our republic",- said
V.P. Chicu, Candidate of Medical Sciences, Assistant Professor,
a Deputy Director of the National Scientific- Practical Center
of Hygiene and Epidemiology. "As a matter of fact, 19,843
patients with the diseases of that profile were registered last
year, that is 457 people for 100,000 local residents. The most
prevailing diseases were dysentery, enterocolitis,
gastroentercolitis, food toxic infections, salmonellosis. In
addition, 1995 was registered as a year of critical rise in
cholera infection - 240 cases all in all. Among the most
affected places were Tiraspol, the regions of Slobozea, Stefan
Voda, Comrat, Ungheni. The highest level of the intestinal
infections spreading was registered in the regions of Ribnita,
Dubosari, Cahul, Stefan Voda and Causeni. In the region of
Transnistria this index was 1.6- 2.6 times higher than the
average republican level. And, everywhere children under six
years were, as usual, the main victims of these diseases. A risk
of the intestinal infections in Moldova is aggravated by the
biological pollution of the environment, especially of natural
reservoirs. Certainly, a threat of the acute epidemic outbreaks
is increased when contaminated waste waters got into these
reservoirs. In 1994 there was such an outbreak in the town of
Straseni after the pouring rains and heavy flooding. Microbe
pollution of the local centralized water supply sources promoted
the epidemic acceleration. There was also a dysentery outbreak
in the first term of 1996 in the town of Falesti, caused by the
drinking water pollution. The epidemiological troubles caused by
these infections are a direct pollution effect of the natural
objects by the wastes waters which are not managed effectively
by the majority of purification works. Whereas a cholera vibrio
manifests miracles of survival. It can circulate in different
hydrobionts throughout many years, for example, in the bodies of
fish and molluscs, becoming an element of the ecosystems chosen.
<a name=L10003></a><a href=#L10004>So</a>, the water basins turn into reservoirs of the constant threat
of cholera spreading, which can influence the human health and
cause the death outcome. The situation seems to be likely in
Moldova against the background of the drinking water quality
worsening and activities reduction concerning the environmental
protection from the biological pollutants. In addition, many
water pipes functionate spasmodically, because they are
exhausted. The sanitary-technical conditions of wells are
absolutely unsatisfactory. As a result, in 1995 about 10 per
cent of water samples from the centralized sources and
practically every fourth sample taken from the wells didn't meet
the requirements of the state standards according to the
microbiologic indices. Meanwhile, there is a definite
correlation between the rate of water basins pollution and the
intestinal infections morbidity growth among the local
residents. It stands to reason, that in order to determine and
eliminate a microbe pollution of the environment, it is
necessary to reinforce activities of all the services,
departments and residents' groups. (...)

The Doctors Of Geneva Advise

by Tatyana Dobrynina (Nezavisimaya Moldova, N97, April 1996)
Recently in the framework of "Eurohealth" programme our republic
has been visited by the WHO mission. For several days the
members of the delegation were studying the situation regarding
the public health services in Moldova of the last years. They
visited the Republican Clinical Hospital and Children's Clinical
Hospital, the Yaloveni Regional Hospital and one of the regional
health centers. The delegates met the President of Moldova and
ministers of public health, finance and economy. The WHO experts
confirmed the preliminary information that the health services
expenses per capita have been reduced in the republic 7 times in
comparison to 1970. They paid attention to the low living
standard of the citizens of Moldova, because of insufficient and
low calories nutrition, psychological unsteadiness and
ecological impact, which cause many diseases. A critical
worsening in the demographic indices was registered, stating
that the general, and especially children's mortality increases,
while the birth-rate decreases. For example, 5 years ago a
national increase of population made up 8 for 1000, the last
year it was registered only 1.8 for 1,000, while in the majority
of the regions of the republic this increase is equal to zero,
and sometimes is even below zero. As far as different programmes
of aid to the states with the similar problems have been worked
out by the WHO head office in Geneva, the members of the
delegation needed only to arrange preliminary coordination of
the future mutual activities in order not to dispense efforts,
but concentrate them on the key hot problems of the day, working
on the public health protection development in Moldova.
"Together with the WHO experts", - T. Mosneaga, Minister of the
Public Health of Moldova, said, - "we managed to determine the
public health development priorities in the republic. First of
all, it is a mother-and-child health protection, family
planning, hygienic and sexual education problems solution.
Besides, we are going to introduce medical insurance, which
helps to provide medical aid to the pensioners, expectant
mothers and children. The visit of such an authoritative
delegation let us to create a programme of aid to the Republic
of Moldova. The Ministry of Public Health appealed to the WHO
with a request to examine the situation in the republic, to
admit its pitiful state in order to render assistance in
specialists training and partnerships establishing with medical
men of other countries.

Don't Destroy The Living Beauty

It happened <a name=L10004></a><a href=#L10005>so</a> that the beauty of primroses became a reason for
their death, <a name=L10005></a><a href=#L10006>so</a> far as being taken from the awakening ground
they immediately lose the life-giving threads and die. (...)
Among the first spring flowers 24 kinds are rare, 16 of the list
are included into the Red Book of Moldova. (...) In the
framework of their project on primroses protection in Moldova,
the ecological group FAUNA have published several articles in
the local papers realizing the goal to raise the population's
ecological culture and awareness on this point. The group also
appealed to the residents of Moldova not to destroy wild spring
flowers as well as not to buy them.

USAID-Activities on Environmental Problems in Moldova

As a part of the U.S.-Government's program of assistance and
cooperation with Moldova, the Agency for International
Development (USAID) is sponsoring a program of technical
assistance, training, and the provision of equipment for
environmental improvements. The purpose of the "Environmental
Policy and Technology Project (EPT)" is to address environmental
concerns related to agricultural practices and provide an
opportunity for the agricultural, ecological and public health
communities to utilize modern concepts of risk decision making
and, through cooperative efforts with improved technical
capabilities, provide solutions for environmental improvement
and address public health concerns relating to agricultural
production. The project began in January 1995, implementing a
number of valuable activities, including the support of Moldovan
ecological research institutions (NGOs and GOs), organization of
number of workshops on introducing the methodology of
environmental risk assessment, on improved agricultural
production practices, a Soil Erosion Modeling Training workshop,
and computer application training. A special course on risk
assessment has been introduced at six Universities during
Winter-Spring of 1996. In order to ensure the opportunities and
avenues for cooperation three localities-farms have been
selected in three different zones of Moldova to serve as
tangible settings for introducing alternative agricultural
practices that reduce environmental contamination (and,
subsequently, environmental risk) supported by improved
analytical capabilities. These sites are also to provide a
setting for technical training in improved agricultural
production techniques and practices, and in advanced soil
erosion monitoring. The sites are also utilized in initiating an
educational outreach campaign on the relationships between
agricultural production, environmental protection and public
health. (...) More activities are planned for the rest of 1996.
The main concern is demonstrating reduction in soil degradation
and pollution prevention methods. Several technical seminars and
training workshops, educational field tours to the demonstration
sites for children and students, publication of public awareness
brochures on ecological issues, including sustainable
agriculture are to occur by the end of the Project. (...)

For more information, please, contact: EPT Moldova Field Office
Chisinau, MOLDOVA 31 August str., 98, #411 Ph: (373-2) 248 762
Fax: (373-2) 248 478 E-mail: root@ept.moldova.su

GTZ-Activities on Environmental Problems in Moldova

On April 27- 30, 1996 in Chisinau the second seminar on the
project management for ecological NGOs of Moldova was held. It
was organized in the framework of the project "The Sphere of
Ecology Development in Moldova", supported by GTZ ( The German
Society on Technical Cooperation). Udo Heitmann, a GTZ
independent consultant, was the moderator of the seminar. 12
ecological organizations took an active part in the work of the
seminar. 5 projects on biodiversity preservation and 1 project
on the ecological NGOs of Moldova organizational development
have been worked out. Besides, the participants of the seminar
got acquainted with the GTZ information services in applied
technologies "Information and Advisory Service on Appropriate
Technology (ISAT)", along with the ecological literature and
information about the activities of some German NGOs, which
could be potential partners for the NGOs of Moldova. During the
work of the seminar a regular meeting of the NGO coordination
council took place. At this meeting a strategy of the further
project development and planned activities have been discussed.
There groups discussed also the council members' actions
coordination and other current organizational issues. A library,
organized on the basis of the Association of Ecological
Education and Information " TERRA NOSTRA", began its work. Here
one can find methodical materials, literature and other
documents, represented at the conference.

Contact person: Lidia Romanchiuk, Ecological Education and
Information " TERRA NOSTRA", Address: 60, Mateevich str.,
Chisinau 2009, MOLDOVA, Tel: (3732) 240043, E-mail:
duca@TERRANOS.moldova.su

Milieaukontakt is Developing Contacts to NGOs in Moldova

On the 1-st of May, 1996 the meeting of the representatives of
Milieukontakt Oost-Europa, an NGO from the Netherlands, Math
Noortmann and Itske Lulof with ecological NGOs of Moldova took
place. The goal of the meeting was to get acquainted with the
local NGOs activities, to study the local situation and problems
the NGOs face, to get contact information in addition with some
questionnaire data. The meeting was organized within the
framework of a feasibility study. The objective of the
feasibility study was to find out whether and if, in which way,
Milieukontakt Oost-Europa could support the capacity building of
the Moldovan environmental movement. In our previous issue we
informed our readers about the expected visit of the
Milieukontakt representatives to Moldova. Unfortunately, the
information the correspondent of ALTAIR received concerning the
intentions of Milieukontakt in Moldova was not quite accurate.
As it became known after the meeting with the representatives of
this organization, presently there is no any definite project.
On the basis of the analysis and evaluation of the information
gathered during the trip to Moldova, a report will be published,
which will contain the conclusions and recommendations. On the
basis of this report a decision concerning a project in Moldova
will be taken. 

Giurgiulesti Oil-Terminal: Appeal For the Protection Of The
Danube

By the order of the government of the Republic of Moldova the
design works on the purified oil products terminal are being
finished. The terminal will be located in the south of the
republic in the place of the confluence zone of the Prut and the
Danube rivers. It is near the village of Giurgiulesti on the 400
m length of the Danube littoral. In the end of May the project
is to be approved and presented to the European Bank for
Reconstruction and Development with the purpose of getting
credit in the amount of 30 million US dollars. The terminal will
operate in the ecologically vulnerable location in immediate
proximity to the biosphere reserve "DELTA DUNARII", a territory
protected by UNESCO, and to the nature reserve "PRUTUL DE JOS",
protected by the state. One oil terminal has been already
functioning in this region, namely, in Reni, Ukraine. The
Giurgiulesti terminal differs from the latter in the following
way: it will deliver processed fuel (like gasoline, diesel oil,
tar, etc.) and it will be equipped with a 173 m length wharf
with a berth for tankers of 5-10 thousand tons capacity running
in the Sumena branch. In 1994, ecological NGOs of the Republic
of Moldova were invited to two meetings, at which the experts of
the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development were
discussing technical and economical substantiation of the
temporary wharf building for processed oil products. Then we
established the following: 1. The papers presented were not
subjected to the thorough ecological examination. 2. The
population residing the area of the terminal construction and
operation was not fully informed about the advantages and
shortcomings of this industrial object, supposed to be located
on the territory of the Giurgiulesti municipality.
Social-ecological problems were not touched upon in the papers
properly. Today it is proposed to carry out the work on the
project along with the experts' examination. This procedure is
permitted, but it can't replace a complex examination and
environment impact assessment of the project. We consider, that
after the preparatory works on the project it must be subjected
to the complex ecological examination on the part of the state
bodies and non-governmental organizations with the participation
of the specialists of the Republic of Moldova and neighbouring
countries on the national, regional and international levels in
different spheres: water and atmosphere resources; biodiversity,
landmarks and reserves; economic ecology; soil condition,
geological and hydrological situation; social and human ecology;
water transport; and international ecological legislation and
agreements ratified with neighbouring countries. We would like
to ask you to take into consideration the fact that the world
practice knows the cases when serious accidents on the terminals
located in the protected areas took place. It is not excepted
either that as a result of construction and exploitation of the
Giurgiulesti terminal there could take place a large-scale
ecological disbalance both in the mouth of the Danube and the
Prut rivers.

Association of University and Postgraduate Ecological Education,
Alla Ciumac, Dr. of Agriculture; "MOLDOVA-ECO" Foundation,
Valeriu Briceag; Association "AGRO-ECO", Efim Sergentu, Dr. of
Agriculture; Public Republican Association "ACME", Professor
Sergiu Cuznetov, Dr. Habilitat of Biology; Association of
