New Law On Ecological Examination And Impact Assessment

by Ilya Trombitskiy (Member of the Parliament of the Republic of
Moldova) On May 29, 1996, the Parliament of Moldova has adopted
the Law on Ecological Examination and Environmental Impact
Assessment. Since coming to the Parliamentary Commission from
the Government the draft law has undergone some principal
changes, connected with the necessity of turning it into a
document, meeting the international requirements concerning the
environmental impact assessment procedures. Primarily, the
project was called "About the State Ecological Examination", and
it didn't contain any description of the public and NGO
participation procedure in the future economic activities
decisions, while the Environmental Impact Assessment was not
envisaged at all. At the members' of the Commission urgent
request a separate chapter has been included into the bill,
explaining in details the ecological NGOs' and initiative
groups' participation procedure in case they wish to get
information about any ecologically dangerous activities planned
and the officials' responsibility who prevent these groups from
examination. To realize a public ecological examination an NGO
should apply to the local authorities where the object
construction is planned. In their application the NGO should
indicate information on the expert commission staff along with
the information on the object of examination, terms of its
undertaking, an extract from the NGO's regulations stating that
it stipulates such kind of activities. In case when applications
came from two or more public associations, a mixed commission is
formed. The local authorities are to present the project
documentation. The results of the public ecological examination
should bear a recommending character till their approval by the
state ecological examination. In case when a supposed object is
a large-scaled one or it is potentially ecologically dangerous,
according to the law, the environmental impact assessment
procedure should be prior to the state ecological examination.
Both registered public nongovernmental associations and
initiative groups of residents, including not less than 100
people, could take part in examination. However, at greater
length the law regulates the state ecological examination. The
projects of the legislative, normative and instructive
documents, the projects dealing with the problems of
environmental pollution, international and concessive
agreements, social development plans, economic activities are
subjected to this examination. The system of the state
ecological examination includes subdivisions and organizations
of the central ecological department, which activities are
determined by the department documents. A representative of the
customer or the elaborator of the project, also representatives
of the ministries and organizations whose activities are related
to the object examined, cannot act as the state ecological
examination experts. The document adopted seems to have a number
of shortcomings. Firstly, it contains a rule according to which
only a specialist having no less than five years of experience
in the industrial objects projecting can be a state ecological
examination expert; this fact makes an examination a kind of
one-sided technically in advance. Secondly, the standard,
according to which an NGO presenting a public examination
application should form a mixed expert commission by a forced
order, is obviously non-democratic. At last, a public ecological
examination of one industrial object cannot be undertaken more
than twice, what allows a more informed NGO to use efficiently
both opportunities (possibly - even a customer himself can use
them). Besides, an expediency of making a state ecological
examination procedure regulation exclusively by the department
instructions, not by the law, is rather doubtful. Nevertheless,
the adopted law makes grounds for civilized settlement of
collisions, which are likely to appear among ecologists,
producers and community during any possible planning of new
economic projects.


Conservation Management Support Network

A joint undertaking of the Dutch Karkonosze Foundation
(established in 1990 as a facilitating organisation for
cooperation with Central European institutes, GOs and NGOs), the
Board for Polish National Parks (NP) and all national park
administrations in Poland

by Henry Baumgartl 17.06.96 - The motivation for establishing
CMSN is the recognised need to substantially strengthen the
(organisational) capacity of national parks in Poland if they
are to effectively fulfil their role as corner stones of the
Polish strategy to conserve the still substantial landscape and
biological diversity in Poland, take action to prevent the
irreversible loss of currently threatened values and, where
possible, prepare for the restoration of lost biodiversity. And,
to create circumstances for the future of sensitive areas to
become truly sustainable. Establishing CMSN is to provide a
solid structure and model for effective communication /
co-ordination / co-operation among peers and relevant
stakeholders. And, to create the right infrastructure to build a
practical National Park Information System for the Polish
national park system (Poland has, at present, 21 national parks
(276 000 hectares) of which 6 are designated Biosphere Reserves
in the UNESCO MaB programme) which may, then, be easily adopted
by similar organisations (particularly in Central Europe).
Element of an ongoing process of landscape and biological
diversity protection efforts, developing the concepts for CMSN /
NPIS has been integrated in a number of closely related and
coordinated projects in Poland and countries to the South and
East of Poland. CMSN in particular, represents an innovative,
joint effort of Intergovernmental (IGO), governmental (GO), non
governmental (NGO) organisations, institutes and corporations to
participate in long term Biodiversity Protection efforts. In
practical terms, CMSN is part of the work programme of the
National Parks Component for which the Polish government has
borrowed two million US dollars from the World Bank under a
Polish Forestry Development Project financed by the World Bank
and the European Investment Bank. The additional funding
required for the realisation of the full NP Component will be
generated by applying a number of equally innovative strategies,
involving an even wider variety of sources than CMSN. The
initiators of CMSN are three organisations, whereby the
Karkonosze Foundation will initiate international, the Board for
Polish National Parks national (i.e. government, national
foundations / funds), and the national park administrations
local (i.e. regional and local governments, institutes, local
NGOs) input to CSMN. Any reader having had experience in the
management of conserving landscape and biological diversity,
will be well aware of the complexity of the described effort,
and I sincerely hope many of you will find the concept
interesting and challenging enough to become one of many active
participants in its realisation. The entire (development)
project will continue until the year 2000. As we hope to involve
a number of students / graduates in interdisciplinary workgroups
to realise specific tasks, do not hesitate to contact me to see
if this effort could be of help to you as well as to the
development process.

Henry Baumgartl, Karkonosze Foundation P.O.Box 2298 NL - 1620 EG
Hoorn The Netherlands, Tel & Fax +31 229 241992, Email:
H.Baumgartl@inter.NL.net

Institute for Sustainable Development (Warsaw)

(aus: WWF-US CEE Environmental Affairs Newsletter, June '96) The
Institute for Sustainable Development in Warsaw was founded in
1991 by Andrzej Kassenberg, Krzysztof Kamieniecki, and Zbigniew
Bochniarz. The Institute has compiled an extraordinary record of
accomplishments, addressing such pressing issues as
privatization and the environment, environmental impact
assessment, sustainable development in the "Green Lungs of
Poland", financing mechanisms and the environment, sustainable
tourism, agriculture and the environment, and transportation and
the environment. The author of the following report, on behalf
of the Polish Ecological Club, arranged the editor's initial
visit to Poland in April 1989. For further information, contact
The Institute for Sustainable Development (Instytut na rzecz
Ekorozwoju), ul. Lowicka 31, 02-052 Warsaw, Poland.

by Krzysztof Kamieniecki (October 1995) - Major Accomplishments:
For me, the greatest achievement of recent years is the founding
of the Institute, together with Andrzej and Zbyszek. It was
established as the end product of the thoughts and activities as
well as the frustrations of its founders through the 1980s.
Between 1991 and 1995, we managed to create a modern
institution, generating views, opinions, and inspiration for
politicians and high ranking State officials favorably inclined
towards proenvironmental transformations. The ease with which
the Institute reaches environmental organizations makes it
impossible for politicians and the administration antagonistic
to sustainable development to ignore the results of the studies
we conduct. The strength of the Institute lies in the
currentness of its actions, its professionalism, and the care
with which it engenders ties with NGOs. (...)

Major Pressing Issues: The question of constitutional order. I
place great weight on the question of how the newly emerging
Polish Constitution will relate to matters important to
sustainable development - the responsibility of the State for
the use of resources, the rights of present and future
generations to nature, the "right to know," and the obligations
of the public to the environment. The Institute initiated
discussions on ecology and the new Constitution; today is the
time to undertake more determined actions (lobbying,
campaigning) to guarantee a place for this topic in the basic
law of the land. Unfortunately, the atmosphere pervading work on
the draft Constitution does not promote such activities - a
greater organizational effort is needed. With respect to
regional issues, transportation is crucial. The Institute
started a project in 1995 on a proenvironmental concept for
transportation in Poland. There is an absence of a comprehensive
program of action for NGOs and pro-environmental politicians
throughout the whole of Europe to bring about change in the
transportation system. (...)

Unaddressed Needs: Developing an ability to communicate with the
community. I get the impression that local government, like the
NGOs, though in a different dimension, is having problems with
maintaining collaboration with the public among which and for
whom it acts.

Major Positive Surprises: The possibility of cooperation with
foreign institutions for sustainable development in developing
and implementing the concept of sustainable development is
exciting. Such collaboration is easy and interesting in the case
of American institutions, significantly more difficult among
European ones, and almost non-existent when speaking of Latin
American institutions.

Major Unexpected Problems and Possible Solutions: Difficulties
in embarking on collaboration with medium- and large-scale
business. Polish business fails to see benefits in participating
in the process of pro-environmental transformations of the
economy. (...)

Major Changes Impacting Our Work Positively and Negatively:
There can be no doubt that the return of democracy for Poland is
a good thing. We are living in a different country and hopefully
this will remain true for as long as possible. The existence and
activities of the Polish Ecological Club (PKE) are a continuing
phenomenon. I am concerned about the appearance of unemployment
and the lack of any proposal for its amelioration through
sustainable development. European works on this point, though
interesting, are fragmentary. Should eco-politicians be
successful in creating a program significantly decreasing
unemployment, then there will be a breakthrough in the
implementation of sustainable development. Local government will
open up to it, and NGOs will have a new, creative field for
action.

