MINATOM of Russia Has Discussed The New NPP Projects

by Oleg Bodrov, Sankt-Petersburgh (According to the materials of
Russian MinAtom collegium) - Giving the opportunity to EBRD to
be engaged in the questions of safety of old Russian NPPs,
MinAtom of Russia has considered the new projects. The
worth-while NPPs are seemed to be V-407 and V-392. The first of
reactors, known as NP-500 or WWER-640, is intended to be built
in Sosnovy Bor (the main power unit) and also, in Kola NPP (3
nuclear power units), and in Far East of Russia (4 nuclear power
units). The project has gained interest in Bulgaria and
Byelorussia. The reactor of large power B-392 is intended to
inculcate in Novovoronezh (2 nuclear power units). To obtain the
permission to build new reactors in Sosnovy Bor and Novovoronezh
is considered to be the main task of MinAtom for the 1995 year.
The designers of nuclear power submarines from Nizhny Novgorod
will get the minimal financial support, too. The NPP project
proposed by them with new reactor WPBER-800 accumulated the
experience of creating of more than 300 reactors for nuclear
submarines. New technical decisions for this NPP will be tested
on the new stand KV-2. The designers of brider reactors BN-800
are advised "to persistently knock at the region doors. "The
most perspective place for this knocking is Chelyabinsk "Mayak".
As for channel-type reactor MKER-800, that is proposed to
substitute old RBMK-1000, it already has the source of
financing. The source is... the sold electrical energy of
operating RBMK-1000 power units, and, to some extent, EBRD
support. 

Storm over nuclear waste brewing in Russian Far East

By Philippa Fletcher (Vladivostok, April 18, Reuter) - (...) The
people of the Far Eastern port city Vladisvostok have mixed
feelings about the ban on dumping radioactive waste at sea,
despite the fact that the latest culprit was the Pacific Fleet,
based right on their doorstep. Officials, ecologists and
journalists here share the view that little harm was done by
liquid nuclear waste once poured into the sea by many countries
and dumped here quietly and regularly until 1993, when the world
found out and protested. What bothers them more is that other
countries might now send their radioactive waste to Russia for
reprocessing. (...) After the latest dumping became public,
Russia called for help to solve the problem <a name=L10006></a><a href=#L10007>so</a> that it could
turn a hastily imposed temporary ban into a permanent one.
Japan, where fish prices had plummeted on news that the Russian
navy had poured 800 tonnes of radioactive waste into nearby
seas, quickly offered $25 million to fund a nuclear reprocessing
facility. At the beginning of this year, a contract was finally
signed with an international consortium led by Japan's Tomen
Corporation. Local ecologists were suspicious of the large
planned capacity which they argue exceeds the Fleet's needs.
Their fears multiplied after a radio interview early this year
with the head of the Taiwan power company who said he was
negotiating to dispose of low level nuclear waste in Russia.
Officials have denied repeatedly that any such agreement exists
with Taiwan or any other country, although the environmental
group Greenpeace reported last month that it had won a court
case to stop a plan to deliver foreign waste to a plant further
west in Siberia. The Vladivostok newspaper Vremya summed up
local concerns: "Japanese taxpayers' money will be put into a
project which is totally unnecessary for their safety and which
will probably be used by Russian officials as a source of income
from reprocessing foreign waste," it said. Mixed up amid the
allegations and denials is a separate row between the local
authorities in Vladivostok and Moscow, seven time zones further
west. This one could scuttle the project. The locals, who
complained they were not consulted over the project, insist that
Marubeni Corporation should process the waste, because its offer
was cheaper and more efficient. They feel <a name=L10007></a><a href=#L10008>so</a> strongly about it
that they are planning to catch Moscow out on one of its own
regulations -- the environmental requirements for any project
dealing with radioactivity. "They are <a name=L10008></a><a href=#L10009>so</a> strict that they have
never once been followed ...but they create a hook to catch
people on," said Anatoly Lebedev, an ecologist from the Far
Eastern Academy of Sciences. Yevgeny Simatyuk, the local
official dealing with the nuclear waste issue, is behind plans
to lodge a protest against the contract with the prosecutor
general. He is recovering from an assault by unknown attackers
outside his home which left him with a fractured skull. In the
meantime, the Fleet has been forced to introduce an alternative
way of dealing with the nuclear waste, stored since 1993 in
rusting tankers. Environmentalists say the Russian design system
is coping for the time being although it creates the problem of
dealing with the filters contaminated in the process. Where all
the attention is focused on the liquid waste problem, the issue
of how to deal with the far more dangerous solid nuclear waste
has taken a back seat. Valery Denilyan, head of the Pacific
Fleet's chemical defence service, said three badly damaged
nuclear submarines are moored off the coast. The reactor in one
exploded in 1985 in an accident similar to the nuclear disaster
at Chernobyl less than a year later. (...) There are up to 10
more dismantled reactors on pontoons and another 50 submarines
awaiting decomissioning by 2010. The Star repair and
decommissioning plant in Bolshoi Kamen, on the opposite side of
the bay from Vladivostok, takes apart barely more than one
submarine a year. "It's a question of financing, then there's
the problem of what to do with the spent nuclear fuel. (...)
With problems like these, Denilyan welcomed international help
but not everyone in the Russian military feels the same. When
the European Union launched a tender to investigate the "Lepse"
vessel in Russia's far north, a problem as serious as Denilyan's
three submarines -- it became caught in a row over alleged
military secrets contained in the tender document. (...)

Radioactive water threatens Russian region of Chelyabinsk

By Timothy Heritage (Moscow, April 11, Reuter) - An official
ecology commission said a new environmental disaster could hit
Russia's Chelyabinsk region, one of the most radioactive places
on Earth, and asked the government to investigate. Alexei
Yablokov, who chairs the ecological safety commission in
President Boris Yeltsin's advisory Security Council, called for
a government review of the potential threat posed by a series of
reservoirs contaminated by liquid radioactive waste. He told a
news conference there was a risk that the water, polluted by
emissions from the nearby Mayak nuclear plant, could overflow
the reservoirs' walls in the River Techa and endanger the local
environment and population. The Chelyabinsk region, in the
southern Ural mountains, is already scarred after a nuclear
accident in 1957 which Yablokov said had made a lake near Mayak
"the most radiation-polluted place on Earth." "If anything
happens to the reservoir walls, all the population living
downstream could be in a critical condition," Yablokov, an
anti-nuclear campaigner, said. Yablokov issued a document drawn
up by his commission asking the Russian government to review the
likely dangers if an accident hit the reservoirs. The commission
said it considered it a priority to remove any risk of disaster
and that a plan should be worked out to evacuate the local
population if there were an accident. Yablokov said 400 million
cubic metres (14.14 billion cubic feet) of poisoned water were
contained in the reservoirs. He did not say how many people
might be affected if the water overflowed but towns downstream
from Mayak, such as Muslyumovo, are still inhabited. For decades
the Soviet government hushed up a series of nuclear disasters in
the Chelyabinsk area, about 1,500 km (950 miles) east of Moscow,
when Mayak was a top secret centre of the Soviet Cold War
weapons programme. Officials say that in the first seven years
of its operation, from 1949 to 1956, the Mayak plutonium plant
poured 76 million cubic metres (2.68 billion cubic feet) of
liquid radioactive waste straight into the Techa. In 1957, an
explosion at a reservoir containing nuclear waste blasted
radiation over an area of 20,000 sq km (7,723 sq miles) of the
lakeland region. The full effects of the accident remain
uncertain to this day because victims were evacuated to distant
parts of the Soviet Union and no records were kept of where they
went. About 44,000 people have responded to requests to complete
a register of those who were in the area at the time, Yablokov
said. But this represented only about one in 10 of the total.
Yablokov said 120 million curies of radiation had polluted the
nearby Karachai Lake, more than twice the amount of radiation
spewed out in the Chernobyl nuclear disaster. Much of Karachai
has been sealed with concrete but Yablokov said the 300,000
curies of radiation in the Techa posed a greater threat. "We
think this is now a bigger danger than the Karachai," he said.

Norway, Russia to cooperate on nuclear waste

By Philippa Fletcher MOSCOW, Dec 15 (Reuter) - Russia and Norway
agreed on December 15, 1995, to work together to dispose of
military waste, including spent nuclear fuel dumped by Russia in
areas close to the Norwegian border. But the deal, signed by the
two countries' defence ministers was short on substance and
clouded by Russia's charge of spying against the work of the
Norwegian environmental group which has drawn most attention to
the nuclear dumping problem. Grachev said reporters concerns
about radioactive pollution from nuclear waste buried on
Russia's Arctic Novaya Zemlya island or stored in vessels moored
off the Kola Peninsula were unfounded. "The level of
radioactivity on Novaya Zemlya is lower than in my office in the
defence ministry," he said, blaming the media for whipping up
the problem with distorted information. "In order to convince
people that it is safe we decided to work more closely on
checking and informing the population...I suggested to Minister
Kosmo to...fly together to Novaya Zemlya with a Geiger counter
and fly wherever my guest wants." Norwegian scientists
previously invited to check radiation levels in the region have
said they are not above normal. But they have been stopped from
going to certain areas deemed to be militarily sensitive and
remain concerned about the danger. Siri Engesaeth, activist of
the Norwegian environmental group Bellona, told by telephone
from Oslo that the only available technology the Russians have
to remove the military nuclear waste would involve exposing
5,000 people to deadly levels of radiation. "They want to tow it
to Novaya Zemlya and store it there," she said, adding that
project's future was now unclear.

Dismantling Of Nuclear Submarines May Increase Pollution

by Christian Rekkedal (Oslo/Norway, 04.07.96) - (...) Kvaerner
Moss Technology have made the pre-study to a project dealing
with dismantling of decommissioned nuclear submarines. Norway
shall use 150 million NOK. The negotiations on a
Norwegian-Russian agreement shall be finished within June 30.
"The plan presumes, among other things, that the storages for
spent fuel at the Andrejeva bay shall be emptied. The fuel are
to be sent to the reprocessing facilities at Mayak. (Norway
shall eventually also contribute to building a temporarly
storage plant in Majak.) "Bellona asks the Foreign department to
forget the plans. The foundation states that the venture will
not contribute to a betterment of the environmental situation in
Russia. On the contrary they point to the huge problems in
association with the waste and emmissions from the reprocessing
plant at Mayak. "If the authorities goes forth with this
problem, it will mean increased emissions and direct health
consequences for the populace in the area," states Thomas Nilsen
at Bellona. (...)

Russian Citizens Are Fighting A U.S. Co-Funded Reprocessing Plant

Citizens of the Russian town of Sergei Posad are fighting a
government plan to build a U.S. co-funded plant in their town to
reprocess thousands of tons of heptyl, a highly toxic chemical
used as liquid rocket fuel. There are unwanted stocks of heptyl
(dimethylhydrazine) at various military installations around
Russia where missiles and rockets are made and launched. Russia
continued to use liquid rocket fuel long after America switched
to solid fuel, largely because it was cheaper. However, heptyl
is highly toxic, carcinogenic, easily soluble in water (which
means in the event of a leak it can spread quickly and easily)
and, of course, very volatile. Estimates of how much heptyl is
stored in Russia's former "closed cities," the Soviet-era secret
towns like Sergei Posad, in Soviet days known as Zagorsk, range
from 50,000 tons to 150,000 tons. At the Scientific Research
Institute of Chemical and Construction Machines (SRICCM) based
in Sergei Posad, there are over 100 tons of heptyl in storage.
And if the new reprocessing facility is installed, at least
another 10,000 tons will be brought there from the other sites
in Russia. Hundreds of signatures have been collected on
petitions protesting about the plans. "The people of this town
object to these plans, and rightly <a name=L10009></a><a href=#L10010>so</a>," says the mayor of Sergei
Posad, Vasili Goncharov, who is leading the protests. "We
already have enough problems to contend with in this area,
including a radon depository and a testing site for storage of
pesticides and household waste." (...) The facility to be built
in Sergei Posad, some 70 kilometers from Moscow, will be
constructed with U.S. aid under the Congress-backed Nunn-Lugar
technical assistance program. This has raised fears that foreign
heptyl will also be brought in for treatment. "The reprocessing
project is tied to deliveries of heptyl from abroad, especially
from the United States," alleges Goncharov. "This is part of a
wider policy of dumping dangerous and harmful production
processes on us here in Russia." Henryk Matysyak, Director of
SRICCM, absolutely denies this. "Only Russian heptyl will be
processed in Sergei Posad," he insists. (...) Matysyak is
certain that the town's people will eventually accept the
facility. He cited earlier protests against the dismantling of
naval missiles, which rapidly abated. "Given the high level of
unemployment today and the fact that the reprocessing project
will create good jobs, I do not expect the opposition to last
long," he explains. "The facility will give workers the
opportunity of earning up to 500,000 rubles ($100) a month with
no payment arrears." Average wages paid by cash-strapped
employers are significantly lower than this in Russia. (...)
Viewed in the wider context, however, the project is causing
concern to environmentalists who fear that Russia may rapidly be
becoming the world's toxic waste dump. Last year the
environmental commission of Russia's Security Council found that
over 2,000 tons of dangerous wastes from abroad were being
brought into the country every day. (...)

RUSSIA NEEDS FOREIGN ASSISTANCE TO DESTROY CHEMICAL WEAPONS

by Scott Parrish (24.7.96) - Nikolai Bezborodov, deputy chairman
of the Duma Defense Committee, said that Russia will need
significant financial assistance to destroy its stock of some
40,000 tons of chemical weapons, ITAR-TASS reported on 22 July.
He was commenting on the latest session of the Preparatory
Commission for the Establishment of an Organisation for the
Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (OPCW) in the Hague, which is
reviewing progress toward implementing the 1993 Chemical Weapons
Convention. Bezborodov said Russia would need 17 trillion rubles
($3.3 billion) to liquidate its chemical weapons stockpile,
adding: "I think we will not manage without serious foreign
aid." Russia has still not ratified the convention, and
Bezborodov said it would not do <a name=L10010></a><a href=#L10011>so</a> until after the "material,
legislative, and other preconditions for its implementation are
in place."

Phenol poisoning hits Russian region after crash

Moscow, May 20 (Reuter) - Highly toxic phenol released in a
train crash last week has caused an ecological disaster in
central Russia, putting more than 100 people in hospital and
threatening many more, Itar-Tass news agency said on Monday. It
said those taken ill had been involved in clearing up after
several freight wagons were derailed near the town of Shumerlya,
600 km (375 miles) east of Moscow, on May 14. Health authorities
said a further 100 people still working at the accident site
were at risk and there was also a threat of a "mass poisoning"
of the local population, Tass reported. Phenol, also known as
carbolic acid, seeped into streams, causing widespread
ecological damage, and had polluted the Sura river, which flows
north into the Volga. Vapours, which damage the liver and
kidneys, had also been released into the air. (...) Environment
Minister Viktor Danilov-Danilyan was quoted as saying on Monday
that of a stockpile of 80 billion tonnes of industrial and
consumer waste in Russia, 1.6 billion tonnes of it posed a
threat to human health and the environment. The country created
around 800 kg of dangerous waste per head of population every
year, Tass reported him as saying. 

Informations and Scientific Work On Lake Baikal Needed.

In March of 1996 USAID informed represantatives of Russian
environmental NGOs that a grant to provide assistance to solve a
problem related to the Baikalsk Pulp and Paper Mill. CH2MHill
was chosen as a contractor to carry out this project. Director
of the Project Dennis Whelan asked us to help with distribution
of the following letter:

"(May 8, 1996) Dear Colleagues: I am writing for help in
developing background information on environmental issues
relating to Lake Baikal. (...) In coordination with ongoing
Gore-Chernomyrdin-Commission activites, the Ministry of the
Environment of the R.F. asked USAID to help with evaluations of
various proposals to restructure / reprofile the Baikalsk Pulp
and Paper Mill (BPPM). USAID, in turn, has asked CH2M Hill to
work on this task in its role as a contractor for the
Environmental Policy and Technology Project. In this regard, I
am writing for your help in securing the names and contact
information for international scholars and experts who have done
previous work on Lake Baikal in general and on environmental
issues related to the Baikalsk Pulp and Paper Mill in
particular. We know that there are many independent Russian and
international teams that have worked the limnology of the lake,
the effects of human activity upon the lake, and alternatives to
pulp production at the BPPM. We would greatly appreciate any
help that you can give us in contacting these individuals and in
accessing the vast body of data and information that already
exists in connection with these problems, including the names
and contact information for individuals and groups that have
information and experience relating to Baikal and the BPPM.
Thank you for your anticipated help. Dennis Whelan Deputy
Regional Director EPT Project/CH2M Hill International"

Greenpeace Russia's World Heritage Project

(Greenpeace International, Patrick Anderson, (GP) December 8,
1995) As part of a major nature conservation project centered in
Russia, Greenpeace has announced the first of a set of
territories to be included in the World Natural Heritage List,
UNESCO's "Nobel Prize" of natural objects. The Project's intent
is the full protection of Russia's most valuable and extensive
funds of biodiversity both in the short term as Russia suffers
an environmental-economic crisis and in the long term as
catalysts in the search for environmentally sound alternative
investment projects. After six years of unsuccesful attempts by
the government to prepare the nomination for Lake Baikal and at
the same time risking the environmental balance of the lake and,
in fact, the majority of intact ecosystems left in Russia, this
ambitious project aims to protect some of Russia's most valuable
natural spaces. Greenpeace Russia has taken the lead in
organising the nominations of several natural areas to the List
by tapping into the resources and guiding the efforts of dozens
of local and national conservation groups, indigenous peoples
and government agencies. The list, administered by the United
Nations' organisation, UNESCO, also contains such natural
wonders as the Grand Canyon and the Great Barrier Reef and
provides a forum for protection and recognition of the world's
most important natural and cultural sites. In order to carry out
the project, Greenpeace has had push for the creation of entire
new park and conservation zone systems, lobby local governments
to devote the areas and promise to conserve them and animate
researchers and conservation planners to make the project
effective. Indigenous peoples and local communities have played
an important and leading role in the development of nearly all
of the sites, demonstrating the need for a fuller consideration
of the sustainability of life-styles outside of both Western and
Eastern industrial paradigms and based on closer relationships
to nature. Greenpeace has already made the first nomination to
the list, the Virgin Komi Forests, 3.2 million hectares of
pristine forest along the Ural Mountains in the Republic of Komi
in the Russian Far North. Current proposed nomination sites for
the list: Primorsky Kray, Far East: a vital habitat of the
endangered Amur tiger and the Far East leopard, 4 million
hectares including the Sikhote-Alin Natural Complex and the
Bikin Valley, the home of the Udege Indigenous people. The
Volcanoes of Kamchatka: active and dormant volcanoes, geysers,
thermal and mineral springs and bubbling mud cauldrons among
perfectly conserved transforming coastal and forest ecosystems.
4 million hectares. The Sources of the Great Ob, Altai
Mountains, Central Siberia: 6.5 million hectares of virgin
mountain taiga, glaciers and the sacred Telestkoye Lake.
Vodlozero Park, Northwest of European Russia: Europe's largest
intact old-growth boreal forests and pristine wetlands. 1
million hectares. Ubsunur Hollow, Tuva Republic: a
Cultural-Natural project carried out in conjunction with the
Mongolian government, 7.5 million hectares, one of the largest
intact watersheds in Central Asia where 40,000 archeological
sites can be found from histroically famous nomadic tribes such
as the Scythians, the Turks and the Huns.

The Virgin Komi Forests: Forming Europe's natural eastern border
along the Ural Mountains, the Virgin Komi Forests are the
continent's largest unfragmented old-growth forests representing
a wide variety of integrated ecosystems ranging from boreal
forests in the southern part of the territory to subarctic taiga
in the north. The forests, mountains, wetlands and river valleys
that make up the system are a haven for dozens of rare species
and contain one of Europe's most valuable stores of
biodiversity. The area counts 43 species of mammals, including
the brown bear, sable and the highly migratory elk, 204 species
of birds, including the Whitetailed eagle, and 16 species of
fish, the most valuable of which is the salmon that helps
sustain the economies downstream. The forests consist of spruce,
cedar and fir, filled with unique and rare slow-growth floral
species. Indigenous peoples Early Russian chronicles from the
tenth and eleventh centuries record the existence of native
peoples in the area of what is now the Komi Virgin Forests. Up
to the present day many place names as well record the passing
of these peoples: the Pechora River, for example, is named for a
tribe that has since either disappeared or has been incorporated
into larger groups. The peoples that still live in the area,
today known as the Komi, still depend upon the natural
surroundings as they have stood for thousands of years. The
herds of reindeer that need the vast forests to graze , the
salmon and other small-scale fisheries, the berries, nuts and
mushrooms that are collected seasonally, and the hunting of wild
hare and various wild forest birds all attest to the necessity
of keeping the forests in their present, virgin state. In 1994
these forests came under direct threat from many sides. A
foreign timber company began to carry out clearcut logging along
the Pechora and Ilych Rivers while one of the world's largest
oil spills destroyed the river and villages downstream. There
was no help in sight: park officials can go months without pay
and nature conservation has been forgotten in the economic
crisis. While Greenpeace campaigners decried the destruction
downstream, Greenpeace researchers got to work upstream to
organise a nomination to UNESCO's World Natural Heritage List.
In making the nomination, Greenpeace completed its successful
campaign to stop French and Austrian logging companies from
using destructive and unsustainable clearcut methods on Komi
territory and demonstrated the need to assure protection for
these vital natural areas.

Siberian tigers future threatened by cash crunch

Vladivostok, Russia, April 16 (Reuter) - An anti-poaching team
set up to protect endangered Siberian tigers in Russia's Far
East is set to be disbanded in July because the regional nature
protection committee can no longer afford to fund it. Committee
chairman Mikhail Bibikov said instructions from Moscow to cut
back on staff left him no choice but to lay off the team,
despite the threat to the remaining tigers, who number no more
than 230. "How can I keep them on? There's no money. I have to
cut back 62 staff and the brigade will be among them," Bibikov
told Reuters. Bibikov's committee is part of the Environment
Ministry. "The government signed a resolution to defend the
tigers but they did not give us a kopeck," he said. "I found the
money from somewhere but I cannot any longer." The brigade, set
up in 1994, got $180,000 in annual international donations last
July, mainly from the German branch of the World Wildlife Fund
and U.S.-based Global Security Network. But that alone was not
enough. "The foreigners do not want to let the tigers disappear.
But the government does not seem to care about Russia's natural
riches," he said. Most of the Siberian, or Amur, tigers live in
the taiga of the Primorsky region in Russia's far southeastern
corner sandwiched between China and Sea of Japan. "There is very
strong pressure on the tigers today because there is great
demand in China for their skins, their bones, their meat. As a
result their number has been reduced by half," said Bibikov. "If
the team is not there, then anyone would be able to shoot
anything they like in the taiga," he said. Bibikov said the team
has confiscated 16 tiger skins last year as well several
leotards and many bear skins. They also made a string of arrests
and confiscated weapons. "They worked well, got good results.
It's a shame," said Bibikov.


Diamond mining in Sakha - need for environmental protection

By Nina A. Trofimova (29.04.96) - (...) Russia's industrial
"progress" has taken a particular toll on the fragile ecosystems
of the North. Two hundred miles of radiation-poisoned riverbank
near Aikhal in Siberia bear the scars of repeated nuclear tests,
as does the lunar landscape carved out by extensive mining
operations in the Vilyui River Basin. Pollution from mining The
largest mining company operating in Sakha, Almazy Rossii-Sakha
(Russia-Sakha Diamonds), was originally established in the '50s
as part of an industrialization strategy for the Vilyui basin.
Under the plan, a series of mining towns sprouted up almost
overnight, including the city of Mirny and the towns of Aikhal
and Udachny. Near these boomtowns, numerous large-scale quarries
were gouged out of the land. One such mine is the Mir complex,
525 meters deep and 1.5 kilometers in diameter. Today mining
operations occupy 1,655 hectares of land in Sakha. Accidental,
but nonetheless frequent, releases of untreated mineralized
water (with concentrations of up to 100 grams per liter) into
surface watercourses over the last 10 years have resulted in
average annual contamination levels as much as eight times the
maximum allowed. The impact on mortality rates in polluted areas
is undeniable: the average life span in the Vilyui region is
less than 58.9 years for men and 67.1 years for women, far below
the average for Sakha as a whole. Infant mortality in the area,
38.1 percent in 1993, is also significantly higher than the
republic-wide rate of 23 percent. While mining severely pollutes
waterways and defaces natural landscapes wherever it occurs, the
effects of mining are especially pronounced in the Arctic
regions of the republic. Despite a significant reduction in
mining activity in recent years, landscape degradation and water
pollution due to diamond mining in the Vilyui River Basin remain
high especially since exhausted mines continue to contaminate
their surroundings with toxic by-products for up to 10 years
after they cease operating. As a result, in 1992 the Russian
Federation declared the Vilyui Basin an important part of the
Lena River watershed, an environmental disaster area. Regulatory
disarray Russia's worsening economic situation exacerbates
Sakha's environmental crisis. The desire for rapid prosperity
has prompted a frenzied rush for resources despite the fact that
the outdated industrial technologies in use throughout the
region are ravaging the land. (...) (Nina A. Trofimova is the
specialist on independent environmental impact statements for
the Association of Humanitarian Initiatives. Translated by
Herrick Fox.)

Overflight Of The Sukpai, Samarga and Khor Watersheds

by Dale Miquelle (RFE EPT Biodiversity Manager) April 13, 1996
The upper portion of the Samarga, Bikin and adjacent sections of
the watersheds in Khabarovsk Krai are the last intact remnants
of the central Sikhote-Alin bioregion and with the exception of
minimal native impact on sustainable replenishable resources,
these regions are wilderness in the classic sense of the
concept. This could change very quickly, with pending road plans
and free market economics placing new pressures on these regions
and directly threatening the vitality of biodiversity upon which
local peoples are dependent for the traditional ways of life
that have evolved with region. Ecologically Sustainable
Development (ESD) booked an overflight of the Sukpai and Khor
River watersheds in southern Khabarovskii Krai and the Samarga
watershed in northern Primorskii Krai in order to check existing
land use patterns.(...) Flying across the 'Khabarovsk Nakhodka'
highway, that is now being constructed on the far side of the
Bikin River about 150 kilometers south of our flight line, and
skirting the villages of Obor, Durmin and Malaya Sidima on our
port side, the flatlands give way to quickly rising mountains
that are girded by an extensive road system. Intensive harvest
of these forests began around 50 years ago, in most part by
people held in rehabilitation camps before and after the second
world war. The approaches to the peaks have been heavily
harvested and a snowy background highlights where the forest has
been removed. We were told that relatively good natural
regeneration is occurring in these regions. We also saw a couple
of locations where logging roads 'illegally' cross over
watershed divides, a remnant of Soviet era forest management.
Heading east, we soon came to the confluence of the Khor and
Sukpai Rivers with the village of Sukpai to our port. As we
continued east up the Sukpai drainage, to our north, large snow
covered clear cuts came into view, the aftermath of harvesting
efforts by the Cubans who worked these forests until the early
'90's. According to forest service officials, these forests were
first clear cut and then burnt and since then have repeatedly
burnt; no significant effort has been made to restock the
cleared lands. There are also a large number of 'natural'
openings formed as a result of forest fires. The southern side
of the Sukpai is a patchwork of harvest areas that reveal no
apparent pattern, as the Cubans cut where they wanted and what
they wanted. There is little evidence of clear cuts. This area
also has many burned over sections. These forests are mixed
conifer (spruce-fir), with extensive stands of larch in the
Tagemu and Yaa drainages. North Koreans are now working in these
areas. A plan was forwarded in the '80's to develop a zakaznik
in the lower and middle drainages of the Sukpai because of its
extraordinary biodiversity values. However, forest management
decisions put these plans to bed and there are few reasons to
now argue for limits on timber harvest here. Since the lower and
middle Sukpai have lost their significance as a potential
protected territory, the current effort is to protect the Chuken
drainage whose confluence with the Khor is about 30 kilometers
downstream of the point where our flight line crossed the
latter. This does not mean, however, that lower and middle
drainages should be abandoned to industrial harvest and large
scale clear cutting. These forests are degraded and ground
truthing is need to determine how timber removal has affected
general forest species diversity. What should follow is a forest
management plan that allows for sustainable timber harvest and
that works to restore forest values <a name=L10011></a><a href=#L10012>so</a> that a primary need for
timber can meet in conditions that also provide for wildlife and
human values intricately interwoven into the fabric of these
lands. And special attention should be given to any management
plans for the headwaters of the Sukpai. This forest is a vital
buffer zone for the Bikin and Samarga watersheds. Any effort to
develop the upper Sukpai will create additional incentives to
open up these other watersheds, especially once a road system is
in place to remove timber from the headwaters. <a name=L10012></a><a href=#L10013>So</a> of particular,
immediate interest is the current status of the east/southeast
road that runs north of the Sukpai in a valley between this
river and the Kabuli drainage. The road draws close to the
Sukpai, and crosses it with the river via a major concrete
bridge, about 30 kilometers downstream of its confluence with
the Tagemu drainage. Given the capital expense to construct such
a structure, there is apparent strong interest in harvesting
timber in the headwaters of the Sukpai. (...)


